upload/report_updates/the-dawn-of-indias-future-cities-special-focus-nagpur-november-2017.pdf</ref>\n| blank_name_sec2                 = [[Human Development Index|HDI]]\n| blank_info_sec2                 = {{color|#090|Very High}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maharashtra.gov.in/Site/upload/WhatsNew/Economic%20Survey%20of%20Maharashtra...pdf |title=Economic Survey of Maharashtra 2014\u201315 |website=Maharashtra.gov.in |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n| website                         = {{URL|www.nagpur.gov.in}} <br /> {{URL|www.nmcnagpur.gov.in}} <br /> {{URL|www.nitnagpur.org}} <br /> {{URL|www.nmrda.org}} <br /> {{URL|www.nagpurpolice.gov.in}}\n| leader_title2                   = [[District collector|Collector]]\n| leader_name2                    = Ravindra Thakre<ref>{{cite news |last1=Anparthi |first1=Anjaya |title=On ECI order, collector Mudgal transferred {{!}} Nagpur News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/on-eci-order-collector-mudgal-transferred/articleshow/71340355.cms |accessdate=8 October 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=28 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> ([[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]])\n| leader_title3                   = [[Municipal Commissioner (India)|Municipal Commissioner]]\n| leader_name3                    = Tukaram Mundhe ([[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]])<ref>{{cite news |title=Tukaram Mundhe is New Nagpur Municipal Commissioner |url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/tukaram-mundhe-is-new-nagpur-municipal-commissioner/01212007 |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=Nagpur Today |date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Anparthi |first1=Anjaya |title=Govt replaces Abhijit Bangar with Tukaram Mundhe as Nagpur municipal commissioner {{!}} Nagpur News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/govt-replaces-bangar-withmundhe-as-mpl-commissioner/articleshow/73531450.cms |accessdate=24 January 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=23 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n| leader_title4                   = [[Police Commissioner]]\n| leader_name4                    = B. K. Upadhyay<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nagpurpolice.gov.in/know_your_commissioner_of_police  |title=Nagpur Police Official Site |publisher=nagpurpolice.gov.in |date= |accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> ([[Indian Police Service|IPS]])\n| blank2_name                     = {{nowrap|Official language}}\n| blank2_info                     = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| blank3_name                     = {{nowrap|UN/LOCODE}}\n| blank3_info                     = IN NAG\n}}\n\n'''Nagpur''' is the third largest city and the winter capital of the Indian state of [[Maharashtra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/state/maharashtra.html|title=Maharashtra Population Sex Ratio in Maharashtra Literacy rate data|website=Census2011.co.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> It is the 13th largest city in [[India]] by population<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nriol.com/india-statistics/biggest-cities-india.asp|title=India's 100 Biggest Cities, Largest Cities in India|publisher=|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref> and according to an Oxford Economics report, Nagpur is projected to be the fifth fastest growing city in the world from 2019 to 2035 with an average growth of 8.41%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/17-of-20-fastest-growing-cities-in-the-world-will-be-from-india/articleshow/66978406.cms|title=17 of 20 fastest-growing cities in the world will be from India |first1=Surojit |last1=Gupta |date=6 December 2018 |website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>. It has been proposed as one of the [[Smart Cities Mission|Smart Cities]] in Maharashtra and is one of the top ten cities in [[India]] in [[Smart Cities Mission|Smart City Project]] execution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/centre-releases-list-of-98-cities-for-smart-city-project/article7586751.ece|title=Centre unveils list of 98 smart cities; UP, TN strike it rich|last=Jeelani|first=Mehboob|work=The Hindu|access-date=17 May 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/city-maintains-first-rank-among-100-smart-cities/articleshow/67916110.cms|title=City maintains first rank among 100 Smart Cities |first1=Anjaya |last1=Anparthi |date=9 February 2019 |website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sharma |first1=Nidhi |title=In 4th year, mission Smart Cities sees big gains |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/in-4th-year-mission-smart-cities-sees-big-gains/articleshow/69935983.cms |accessdate=12 August 2019 |work=The Economic Times |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNagpur is the seat of the annual [[Winter Session of Maharashtra State Assembly|winter session of the Maharashtra state assembly]]. It is a major commercial and political centre of the [[Vidarbha]] [[Regions and Divisions of Maharashtra|region]] of Maharashtra. In addition, the city derives unique importance from being the headquarters for the [[Hindu nationalist]] organisation [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh|RSS]] and an important location for the [[Dalit Buddhist movement]]. Nagpur is also known for [[Deekshabhoomi]], the largest hollow stupa among all the Buddhist stupas in the world.\n\nAccording to a survey by [[ABP News]]-[[Ipsos]], Nagpur was identified as the best city in [[India]] topping in [[livability]], greenery, [[Public Transport|public transport]], and [[Health Care|health care]] indices in 2013.<ref name=\"Best City in India 2013\">{{cite web|title=Nagpur tops in 4 categories, bags ABP News Best City for the year 2013 but lost the position to Delhi and Mumbai later in year 2014 and 2015|url=http://www.newsbullet.in/india/34-more/40067-nagpur-tops-in-4-categories-at-abp-news-best-city-awards|work=ABP News Bureau|publisher=Newsbullet.in|accessdate=9 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309112032/http://www.newsbullet.in/india/34-more/40067-nagpur-tops-in-4-categories-at-abp-news-best-city-awards|archive-date=9 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Best City Awards Winners\">{{cite web|title=List of winners at ABP News Best City Awards |url=http://www.newsbullet.in/india/34/40068|work=ABP News Bureau|publisher=Newsbullet.in|accessdate=9 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310071526/http://www.newsbullet.in/india/34/40068|archive-date=10 March 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Video: Nagpur gets the Best City Award\">{{cite web|title=Best City Award goes to Nagpur|url=http://www.newsbullet.in/video/india/40088-best-city-award-goes-to-nagpur|work=ABP News Bureau|publisher=Newsbullet.in|accessdate=9 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310071922/http://www.newsbullet.in/video/india/40088-best-city-award-goes-to-nagpur|archive-date=10 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The city was adjudged the 20th cleanest city in India and the top mover in the western zone as per [[Cleanest cities in India#Swachh Sarvekshan|Swachh Sarvekshan 2016]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thehitavada.com/Encyc/2016/2/16/Nagpur-is-among-top-20-clean-cities.aspx|title=Nagpur is among top 20 clean cities|website=Thehitavada.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> It was awarded as the best city for innovation and best practice in [[Cleanest cities in India#Swachh Sarvekshan|Swachh Sarvekshan 2018]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/nagpur-best-in-innovation-best-practicesapos/articleshow/64196453.cms |title=Nagpur best in 'innovation & best practices' |first1=Proshun |last1=Chakraborty |date=16 May 2018 |website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> It was also declared as open defecation free in January 2018 under [[Swachh Bharat Mission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/nagpur-city-declared-open-defecation-free/articleshow/62343270.cms|title=Nagpur city declared Open Defecation Free |first1=Proshun |last1=Chakraborty |date=2 January 2018 |website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>  It is also one of the safest cities for women in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amuserr.com/2441/top-indian-cities-which-are-safe-for-females/|title=Top 8 Indian Cities Which Are Safe For Females|date=15 November 2016|website=Amuserr}}</ref> The city also ranks 31st in Ease of Living index among 111 cities in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/city-ranks-31-on-ease-of-living-index-amravati-at-16/articleshow/65392884.cms|title=City ranks 31 on Ease of Living index, Amravati at 16 &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> It was ranked the 8th most competitive city in the country by the Institute for Competitiveness for the year 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://competitiveness.in/city-competitiveness-report-2017/ |title=City Competitiveness Report 2017 |website=Competitiveness.in |date=5 January 2018 |accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n \nIt is famous for [[Nagpur orange]]s and is sometimes known as the Orange City for being a major trade center of oranges cultivated in large part of the region.<ref name=\"Nagpur also popularly known as Orange City\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/yw/2006/03/31/stories/2006033100200500.htm|title=Stamps from the Orange City|work=The Hindu |access-date=19 June 2006|location=Chennai, India|date=31 March 2006}}</ref> It is also called the ''Tiger Capital of India'' or the ''Tiger Gateway of India'' as many tiger reserves are located in and around the city and also hosts the regional office of [[National Tiger Conservation Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-nagpur-to-be-country-s-tiger-capital-1532395|title=Nagpur to be country's tiger capital|author=|date=16 April 2011|website=DNA India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Govt-approves-IG-posts-for-NTCA-HQ-regional-offices/articleshow/7279842.cms|title=Govt approves IG posts for NTCA HQ, regional offices |date=2011|website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> The city was founded in 1703 by the [[Gond people|Gonds]] King [[Bakht Buland Shah]] of [[Deogarh, Madhya Pradesh|Deogarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://203.129.203.6/en/city-information.html |title=City Information |publisher=203.129.203.6 |date= |accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref> and later became a part of the [[Maratha Empire]] under the royal [[Bhonsale]] dynasty. The [[British East India Company]] took over Nagpur in the 19th century and made it the capital of the [[Central Provinces and Berar]]. After the first re-organisation of states, the city lost its status as the capital. Following the informal [[Nagpur Pact]] between political leaders, it was made the second capital of Maharashtra.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Nagpur}}\n{{see also|Nagpur state}}\n\n===Etymology===\nNagpur is named after the [[Nag River|river Nag]] which flows through the city. The old Nagpur (today called 'Mahal') is situated on north banks of the river Nag. The suffix ''pur'' means \"city\" in many Indian languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/most/p2vidal.htm|title=Management of Social Transformations (MOST) Programme \u2013 United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|access-date=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOne of the earlier names of Nagpur was \"Fanindrapura\". It derives its origin from the [[Sanskrit]] word ''fana'' (\u092b\u0923\u093e; meaning hood of a [[cobra]]). Nagpur's first newspaper was named ''Fanindramani'', which means a jewel that is believed to be suspended over a cobra's hood. It is this jewel that lights up the darkness, hence the name of the newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Andhare-shines-a-light-on-Nagpurs-history/articleshow/46401555.cms|title=Andhare shines a light on Nagpur's history|work=The Times of India|access-date=27 July 2015}}</ref> [[B. R. Ambedkar]] claimed that both the city and the river are named after \"Nag people\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/itc/mealac/pritchett/00ambedkar/txt_ambedkar_conversion.html|title=Why Was Nagpur Chosen? by Dr. B. R. Ambedkar|website=Columbia.edu|access-date=27 July 2015}}</ref> During British rule, the name of the city was spelt and pronounced as \"Nagpore\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=W-iNBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT15&lpg=PT15&dq=british%20pronounced%20nagpore#v=onepage&q=british%20pronounced%20nagpore&f=false|title=FACETS: An empowering testimony of faith, recovery and fulfilment|first=Mariette|last=Ross|date=4 September 2014|publisher=Xlibris Corporation|access-date=25 November 2016|via=Google Books|isbn=9781499001150}}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Early and medieval history===\nIn the 18th century, the city was created by the leader of Gond Dynasty named [[Bakht Buland Shah]] in the first half of the century. Human existence around present-day Nagpur can be traced back 3000 years to the 8th century BCE. ''Mehir'' burial sites at the Drugdhamna (near the Mhada colony) indicate that the [[megalithic]] culture existed around Nagpur and is still followed.<ref name=\"3000-year-old burial site unearthed\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Cities/3000-year-old_burial_site_unearthed/rssarticleshow/2830035.cms |title=3000-year-old burial site unearthed|work=The Times of India|accessdate=1 March 2008|date=2 March 2008}}</ref> The first reference to the name \"Nagpur\" is found in a 10th-century [[Indian copper plate inscriptions|copper-plate inscription]] discovered at Devali in the neighbouring [[Wardha District|Wardha]] district. The inscription is a record of grant of a village situated in the Visaya (district) of Nagpura-Nandivardhana during the time of the [[Rashtrakutas|Rastrakuta]] king Krsna III in the [[Saka year]] 862 (940 CE).<ref name=\"Copper-inscription info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/FINAL_GAZETTEE/history.html |title=History of Nagpur District: Ancient Period |publisher=Maharashtra State Government Directorate of Government Printing, Stationery and Publications |accessdate=28 July 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709142805/http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/FINAL_GAZETTEE/history.html |archivedate=9 July 2007 }}</ref> Towards the end of the 3rd century, King [[Vakataka dynasty|Vindhyasakti]] is known to have ruled the Nagpur region. In the 4th century, the [[Vakataka Dynasty]] ruled over the Nagpur region and surrounding areas and had good relations with the [[Gupta Empire]]. The Vakataka king [[Vakataka Dynasty#Prithvisena I|Prithvisena I]] moved his capital to Nagardhan (ancient name Nandivardhana), {{convert|38|km|mi}} from Nagpur.<ref name=\"Ancient Indian History and Civilization\">{{Cite book|author=Sailendra Nath Sen|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization |publisher=New Age International |year=1999|pages=242\u2013248|isbn=978-81-224-1198-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA242&dq=nagpur+district+administration#PPA243,M1}}</ref> After the Vakatakas, the region came under the rule of the [[Hindu]] kingdoms of the [[Badami Chalukyas]], the [[Rashtrakutas]]. The [[Paramara]]s of [[Malwa]] appear to have controlled the Nagpur region in the 11th century. A ''[[prashasti]]'' inscription of the Paramara king [[Lakshmadeva]] (r. c. 1086\u20131094) has been found at Nagpur.<ref>{{cite book |author=Pratipal Bhatia |title=The Param\u0101ras, c. 800\u20131305 A.D. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a5gcAAAAMAAJ |year=1970 |publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal |page=111 }}</ref> Subsequently, the region came under the [[Yadavas of Devagiri]]. In 1296, [[Allauddin Khilji]] invaded the Yadava Kingdom after capturing [[Daulatabad, Maharashtra|Deogiri]], after which the [[Tughlaq Dynasty]] came to power in 1317. In the 17th century, the [[Mughal Empire]] conquered the region, however during Mughal era, regional administration was carried out by the [[Gondi people|Gond]] kingdom of [[Deogarh-Nagpur]] in the [[Chhindwara district]] of the modern-day state of [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nagpur.gov.in/ehtmldocs/left_link/history.html|title=HISTORY|publisher=Nagpur.gov.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> In the 18th, century [[Bhonsle]]s of the [[Maratha Empire]] established the [[Nagpur Kingdom]] based in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/776978/forgotten-indian-history-the-brutal-maratha-invasions-of-bengal|title=Forgotten Indian history: The brutal Maratha invasions of Bengal|first=Shoaib|last=Daniyal|website=Scroll.in}}</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\n[[File:Nagardhan-Fort-Main-Entrance.jpg|thumb|right|Main entrance of the Nagardhan Fort, commissioned by [[Raghuji Bhonsle]] of the [[Bhonsale|Bhonsale dynasty]] of the [[Maratha Empire]] in the 18th century]]\nAfter Bhakt Buland Shah, the next Raja (king) of Deogarh was [[Chand Sultan]], who resided principally in the country below the hills, fixing his capital at Nagpur, which he turned into a walled town.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TCNfWRGXd04C&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=king+of+deogarh+chand+sultan#v=onepage&q=king+of+deogarh+chand+sultan&f=false|title=Continuity and Change in a Little Community|first=Ayyappan Madhava|last=Kurup|date=25 April 1986|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|accessdate=25 April 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref> On Chand Sultan's death in 1739, Wali Shah, an illegitimate son of Bakht Buland, usurped the throne and Chand Sultan's widow invoked the aid of the [[Maratha Empire|Maratha]] leader [[Raghuji Bhonsle|Raghoji Bhosale]] of Berar in the interest of her sons Akbar Shah and Burhan Shah. The usurper was put to death and the rightful heirs placed on the throne. After 1743, a series of Maratha rulers came to power, starting with [[Raghoji Bhonsle|Raghoji Bhosale]], who conquered the territories of Deogarh, [[Chandrapur|Chanda]] and [[Chhattisgarh]] by 1751.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpur-hotels.com/nagpur-tourism/history-of-nagpur-people.aspx|title=Nagpur \u2013 History \u2013 People \u2013 Art and Culture \u2013 Festivals|publisher=Nagpur-hotels.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nNagpur was burnt substantially in 1765 and again partially in 1811 by marauding [[Pindari]]s. However, the development of the city of Nagpur continued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://csridentity.com/nagpur/index.asp|title=About Nagpur district|publisher=Csridentity.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> In 1803 [[Raghoji II|Raghoji II Bhosale]] joined the [[Peshwa]] against the [[United Kingdom|British]] in the [[Second Anglo-Maratha War]], but the British prevailed. After Raghoji II's death in 1816, his son Parsaji was deposed and murdered by [[Mudhoji II Bhonsle|Mudhoji II Bhosale]]. Despite the fact that he had entered into a treaty with the British in the same year, Mudhoji joined the Peshwa in the [[Third Anglo-Maratha War]] in 1817 against the British but suffered a defeat at Sitabuldi in present-day Nagpur. The fierce battle was a turning point as it laid the foundations of the downfall of the [[Bhonsale|Bhosale]]s and paved the way for the British acquisition of Nagpur city.<ref name=\"Sitabuldi's importance, fought in 1817, major players involved, etc.\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurcity.net/netzine/981215a2.html |title=The Battle of Sitabuldi |publisher=Nagpurcity.net |accessdate=1 June 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060111202642/http://www.nagpurcity.net/netzine/981215a2.html |archivedate=11 January 2006 }}</ref> Mudhoji was deposed after a temporary restoration to the throne, after which the British placed [[Nagpur kingdom#Raghoji III|Raghoji III Bhosale]], the grandchild of [[Raghoji II]], on the throne. During the rule of Raghoji III(which lasted till 1840), the region was administered by a British resident. In 1853, the British took control of Nagpur after Raghoji III died without leaving an heir.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gSFYAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA2-PA12&lpg=RA2-PA12&dq=Raghoji%20III%20died%20without%20leaving%20an%20heir#v=onepage&q=Raghoji%20III%20died%20without%20leaving%20an%20heir&f=false|title=Proceedings of a Public Meeting for the formation of The Northern Central British India Society held in the Corn Exchange, Manchester, on Wednesday evening, August 26th, 1840|first=Northern Central British India Society|last=(MANCHESTER)|date=1 January 1840|publisher=Northern Central British India Society|accessdate=25 November 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n[[File:Nagpur.png|left|thumb|Map of Nagpur district with major towns and rivers]]\n[[File:Central Provinces India 1903.gif|thumb|right|Central Provinces and Berar, 1903. Princely states are shown in yellow.]]\n\nFrom 1853 to 1861, the [[Nagpur Province]] (which consisted of the present Nagpur region, [[Chhindwara]], and [[Chhattisgarh]]) became part of the [[Central Provinces and Berar]] and came under the administration of a commissioner under the British central government, with Nagpur as its capital. Berar was added in 1903.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dUzvBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=nagpur%20province#v=onepage&q=nagpur%20province&f=false|title=Maharashtra General Knowledge|publisher=Upkar Prakashan|accessdate=25 November 2016|via=Google Books|isbn=9789350133576}}</ref> The advent of the Great Indian Peninsula Railway (GIP) in 1867 spurred its development as a trade centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maharashtraweb.com/Cities/Nagpur/historyofnagpur.asp|title=History Of Nagpur|publisher=Maharashtraweb.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Tata group]] started its first textile mill at Nagpur, formally known as [[Tata Textile|Central India Spinning and Weaving Company Ltd]]. The company was popularly known as \"Empress Mills\" as it was inaugurated on 1 January 1877, the day queen [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]] was proclaimed Empress of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catalign.in/2010/06/innovations-in-jamsetji-tatas-empress.html|title=Innovations in Jamsetji Tata's Empress Mills at Nagpur|publisher=Catalign.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[non-co-operation movement]] was launched in the Nagpur session of 1920.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.importantindia.com/16194/causes-and-importance-of-non-co-operation-movement/|title=Non-cooperation Movement: Introduction, Causes, Result and Importance \u2013 Important India|date=17 December 2014|publisher=inprotantindia.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> The city witnessed a Hindu\u2013Muslim riot in 1923 which had profound impact on [[K. B. Hedgewar]],<ref name=\"Gandhi in His Time and Ours\">{{Cite book|author=David Hardiman|title=Gandhi in His Time and Ours|publisher=Orient Blackswan|year=2003|pages=165\u2013166|isbn=978-81-7824-114-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qvvgOvby58YC&pg=PA165&dq=nagpur+riots+of+1923}}</ref> who in 1925 founded the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] (RSS), a Hindu nationalist organisation in Mohitewada Mahal, Nagpur with an idea of creating a [[Hindu nationalism#Hindu Rashtra|Hindu nation]]. After the [[1927 Nagpur riots]] RSS gained further popularity in Nagpur and the organisation grew nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/topic/Rashtriya-Swayamsevak-Sangh|title=Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh (RSS) \u2013 Hindu organization|publisher=Britannica.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===After Indian independence===\nAfter [[Partition of India|India gained independence]] in 1947, [[Central Provinces and Berar]] became a province of India. In 1950, the Central Provinces and Berar was reorganised as the Indian [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Madhya Pradesh]] with Nagpur as its capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mp.gov.in/en/web/guest/home-history |title=History \u2013 Govt. of MP India |publisher=Mp.gov.in |date=26 January 1950 |accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref> When the Indian states were reorganised along the linguistic lines in 1956, Nagpur and Berar regions were transferred to the [[Bombay state|state of Bombay]], which was split into the states of Maharashtra and [[Gujarat]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiansaga.com/history/postindependence/reorganization.html|title=History of India|publisher=Indiansaga.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> At a formal public ceremony held on 14 October 1956 in Nagpur, [[B. R. Ambedkar]] and his supporters converted to Buddhism, which started the [[Dalit Buddhist movement]] that is still active.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/dalits-throng-deeksha-bhoomi-in-nagpur/article5231936.ece|title=Dalits throng Deeksha Bhoomi in Nagpur|first=Pavan|last=Dahat|date=14 October 2013|publisher=Thehindu.com|accessdate=25 November 2016|via=The Hindu}}</ref> In 1994, the city of Nagpur witnessed its most violent day in modern times in the form of [[1994 Gowari stampede|Gowari stampede]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/morcha-of-gowaris-turns-into-bloody-stampede-claims-113-lives/1/294701.html|title=Morcha of Gowaris turns into bloody stampede, claims 113 lives|publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nNagpur completed 300 years of establishment in the year 2002. A big celebration was organised to mark the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/model-for-beautification-of-zero-mile-to-be-finalized-soon-patankar/08251914|title='Model for beautification of Zero Mile to be finalized soon': Patankar|publisher=Nagpurtoday.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== Topography ===\nNagpur is located at the exact centre of the [[Indian peninsula]]. The city has the [[Zero Mile Stone (Nagpur)|Zero Mile Stone]] locating the geographical centre of India, which was used by the British to measure all distances within the Indian subcontinent.\n\nThe city lies on the Deccan plateau of the Indian Peninsula and has a mean altitude of 310.5 meters above sea level.<ref name=\"imdnagpur.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://imdnagpur.gov.in/Climate_NGP.pdf |title=Climate of Nagpur \u2013 Regional Meteorological Centre Airport, Nagpur |author1=P. K. Nandankar |author2=P. L. Dewangan |author3=R.V. Surpam |date=16 December 2011 |publisher=India Meteorological Department |accessdate=1 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071817/http://imdnagpur.gov.in/Climate_NGP.pdf |archivedate= 4 March 2016 }}</ref> The underlying rock strata are covered with alluvial deposits resulting from the flood plain of the Kanhan River. In some places, these give rise to granular sandy soil. In low-lying areas, which are poorly drained, the soil is alluvial clay with poor permeability characteristics. In the eastern part of the city, crystalline [[metamorphic rocks]] such as gneiss, schist and granites are found, while in the northern part yellowish sandstones and clays of the lower [[Gondwana]] formations are found.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nagpur.nic.in/gazetteer/gaz1966/final_gazettee/geo.html |title=Nagpur District Gazetteer|publisher=Nagpur.nic.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\nNagpur city is dotted with natural and artificial lakes. The largest lake is [[Ambazari Lake]]. Other natural lakes include [[Gorewada Lake]] and Telangkhedi lake. Sonegaon and Gandhisagar Lakes are artificial, created by the city's historical rulers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bionanofrontier.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/SPECIALISSUEMANU2012VOL.5(2-I)/124.pdf |title=AVIFAUNAL DIVERSITY OF NAGPUR CITY, M.S., INDIA : PRIYA D. WANJARI : Santaji Mahavidyalaya, Wardha Road, Nagpur |website=Bioanofrontier.org |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> Nag river, Pilli Nadi, and [[stream|nallas]] form the natural drainage pattern for the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nagpurwater.com/PageMoreInfo.aspx|title=NMC Water Distribution Management Project |website=Nagpurwater.com |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Nagpur is known for its greenery and was adjudged the cleanest and second greenest in India after [[Chandigarh]] in 2010.<ref name=TET>{{cite web |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-12-24/news/27722689_1_nagpur-growth-nucleus-second-greenest-city |title=Nagpur \u2013 Growth Nucleus of India |date=24 December 2008 |work=The Economic Times |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630031536/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-12-24/news/27722689_1_nagpur-growth-nucleus-second-greenest-city |archive-date=30 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n{{climate chart\n|Nagpur\n|10.4|30.6|10\n|13.0|34.1|12\n|17.0|38.3|18\n|21.9|42.2|13\n|25.9|44.6|16\n|24.3|39.8|172\n|22.1|33.5|304\n|21.6|32.4|292\n|20.9|33.8|194\n|17.8|34.6|51\n|12.9|32.4|12\n|10.1|30.2|17\n|source=[http://www.worldweather.org/066/c00533.htm World Weather Information Service]\n|float=right\n|clear=left\n}}\n\nNagpur has [[tropical savannah climate]] (''Aw'' in [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]) with dry conditions prevailing for most of the year. It receives about 163&nbsp;mm of rainfall in June. The amount of rainfall is increased in July to 294&nbsp;mm. Gradual decrease of rainfall has been observed from July to August (278&nbsp;mm) and September (160&nbsp;mm).<ref name=\"imdnagpur.gov.in\"/> The highest recorded daily rainfall was 304&nbsp;mm on 14 July 1994.<ref name=\"Highest rainfall recorded\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1042519/report-flooding-power-cuts-after-nagpur-rains|title=Flooding, power cuts after Nagpur rains|publisher=dnaindia.com|accessdate=18 July 2006}}</ref> Summers are extremely hot, lasting from March to June, with May being the hottest month. Winter lasts from November to January, during which temperatures drop below 10&nbsp;\u00b0C (50&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=\"imdnagpur.gov.in\"/> The highest recorded temperature in the city was 48&nbsp;\u00b0C on 19 May 2015, while the lowest was 3.5&nbsp;\u00b0C on 29 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.mherrera.org/temp.htm|title = Extreme Temperatures From Around the World|accessdate = 24 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Extreme weather====\n\nThe average number of [[heat wave]] days occurring in Nagpur in the summer months of March, April and May is 0.5, 2.4 and 7.2 days respectively. May is the most uncomfortable and hottest month with, for example, 20 days of heat waves being experienced in 1973, 1988 and 2010. The summer season is characterised by other severe weather activity like [[thunderstorm]]s, [[dust storm]]s, [[hail]]storms and [[squall]]s. Generally, hailstorms occur during March and dust storms during March and April. These occur infrequently (1 per 10 days). Squalls occur more frequently with 0.3 per day in March and April rising to 0.8 per day in May.<ref name=\"imdnagpur.gov.in\"/> Due to the heat waves in the city the [[Indian Government|Indian government]] with the help of New York-based National Resources Defense Council has launched a heat wave program since March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/govt-plans-heat-wave-programs-in-nagpur-bhubaneswar-ahead-of-summer/story-9aAVm4K1YkwM5xlDuaJ54H.html|title=Govt plans heat wave programs in Nagpur, Bhubaneswar ahead of summer|date=9 March 2016|publisher=Hindustantimes.com|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = [[Nagpur Airport]] (1971\u20131990)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|temperature colour = \n|Jan record high C = 36.6\n|Feb record high C = 39.2\n|Mar record high C = 45.0\n|Apr record high C = 46.1\n|May record high C = 47.8\n|Jun record high C = 47.7\n|Jul record high C = 40.6\n|Aug record high C = 37.8\n|Sep record high C = 38.9\n|Oct record high C = 39