as the capital of [[Central Provinces and Berar]] for 100 years. After the State Reorganisation in 1956, Nagpur and [[Vidarbha]] region become part of the new Maharashtra State. With this Nagpur lost the capital status and hence a pact was signed between leaders, the [[Nagpur Pact]]. According to the pact, Nagpur is the second capital of Maharashtra and one session of state legislature and the state legislative council takes place in [[Vidhan Bhavan, Nagpur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epw.in/system/files/pdf/1960_12/18/maharashtra_and_gujerat.pdf |title=The Economic Weekly |date=30 April 1960 |website=Epw.in |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>{{rp|671}}Usually the winter session takes place in the city exception being in 1966, 1971 and 2018 when the monsoon session took place in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/maharashtra-assembly-to-hold-monsoon-session-in-nagpur-after-47-years-from-14-july-to-30-august-4600201.html|title=Maharashtra Assembly to hold Monsoon Session in Nagpur after 47 years, from 14 July to 30 August|author=|date=|website=Firstpost|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>  Nagpur has a district court and its own bench of the [[Bombay High Court]] which was established on 9 January 1936. The city consists of six [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituencies namely [[Nagpur West (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Nagpur West]], [[Nagpur South (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Nagpur South]], [[Nagpur South West (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Nagpur South West]], [[Nagpur East (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Nagpur East]], [[Nagpur North (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Nagpur North]] and [[Nagpur Central (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Nagpur Central]]. These constituencies are part of the [[Nagpur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Nagpur Lok Sabha constituency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nagpur.constituency.co.in/p/about.html|title=About|publisher=Nagpur.constituency.co.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Local government===\n{{See also|Greater Nagpur Metropolitan Area|List of localities in Nagpur}}\n\nThe Municipal Council for Nagpur was established in 1864. At that time, the area under the jurisdiction of the Nagpur Municipal Council was 15.5&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> and the population was 82,000. The duties entrusted to the Nagpur Municipal Council were to maintain cleanliness and arrange for street lights and water supply with government assistance. The Municipal Corporation came into existence in March 1951. Nagpur is administered by the [[Nagpur Municipal Corporation]] (NMC), which is a democratically elected civic governing body. The Corporation elects a Mayor who along with a Deputy Mayor heads the organisation. The mayor carries out the activities through various committees such as the Standing Committee, health and sanitation committee, education committee, water works, public works, public health and market committee. The mayor of Nagpur is Sandip Joshi,<ref name=\"TOI23Nov2019\">{{cite news |last1=Anparthi |first1=Anjaya |title=New mayor Joshi's devpt plan seeks citizens' help, 'reconnect' with BJP {{!}} Nagpur News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/new-mayor-joshis-devpt-plan-seeks-citizens-help-reconnect-with-bjp/articleshow/72190712.cms |accessdate=23 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=23 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The administrative head of the Corporation is the Municipal Commissioner, an [[Indian Administrative Service]] (IAS) officer appointed by the state government. The Municipal Commissioner along with the Deputy Municipal Commissioners, carry out various activities related to engineering, health and sanitation, taxation and its recovery. Various departments such as public relations, library, health, finance, buildings, slums, roads, street lighting, traffic, establishment, gardens, public works, local audit, legal services, waterworks, education, octroi and fire services manage their specific activities. The activities of NMC are administered by its zonal offices. There are 10 zonal offices in Nagpur \u2013 Laxmi Nagar, Dharampeth, Hanuman Nagar, Dhantoli, Nehru Nagar, Gandhi Baugh, Sataranjipura, Lakkadganj, Ashi Nagar and Mangalwari. These zones are divided into 145 wards. Each ward is represented by a corporator, a majority of whom are elected in [[local elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmcnagpur.gov.in/en/about-nmc.html|title=About NMC|publisher=Nmcnagpur.gov.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> NMC has various departments including healthcare, education, and a fire brigade dedicated for each service and project of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmcnagpur.gov.in/en/departments.html|title=Departments|publisher=Nmcnagpur.gov.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Nagpur Improvement Trust]] (NIT) is a local planning authority which works with NMC and carries out the development of the civic infrastructure and new urban areas on its behalf. NIT is headed by a Chairman, an [[Indian Administrative Service]] Officer appointed by the state government.<ref name=\"NIT Home.\">{{cite web|url=http://nitnagpur.org/home.html|title=About Trust |website=Nagpur Improvement Trust |accessdate=23 June 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080417055901/http://www.nitnagpur.org/home.html|archive-date=17 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Since the 1990s the urban agglomeration had rapidly expanded beyond the city's municipal boundaries. This growth had presented challenges for the future growth of the city and its fringes in an organised manner. With a view of achieving balanced development within the region, the [[Nagpur Improvement Trust]] (NIT) was notified as the Special Planning Authority (SPA) for the Nagpur Metropolitan Area (NMA) and entrusted with the preparation of a Statutory Development Plan as per provisions of the MRTP Act, 1966. The notified NMA comprises areas outside the Nagpur city and includes 721 villages under 9 tehsils of the Nagpur District spreading across an area of 3,567&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nitnagpur.org/pdf/Metro_Region_DP.pdf |title=Nagpur Metropolitan Area Development Plan 2012\u20132032 |date=February 2015 |website=Nagpur Improvement Trust, Nagpur |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> In 1999, the government of Maharashtra declared that the Nagpur Metropolitan Area shall comprise all of Nagpur city, Nagpur Gramin (rural areas near Nagpur), [[Hingna]], [[Parseoni]], [[Mauda]] and [[Kamptee]] [[Taluka]] and parts of [[Savner]], [[Kalmeshwar]], [[Umred]] and [[Kuhi]]. The boundaries of the \"Metro region\" around the municipal corporation limits of the city have been defined as per the notification. In 2002, the government extended the jurisdiction of the Nagpur Improvement Trust (NIT) by 25 to 40 kilometres. This new area was defined under clause 1(2) of NIT Act-1936 as \"Nagpur Metropolitan Area\".<ref name=\"Metro Region\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nitnagpur.org/metro.aspx|title=Nagpur Metropolitan Area |website=Nagpur Improvement Trust, Nagpur}}</ref> [[Government of Maharashtra|Maharashtra State Cabinet]] in 2016 had paved the way for NIT to become [[Nagpur metropolitan area|Nagpur Metropolitan Region Development Authority(NMRDA)]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/NIT-to-become-NMRDA/articleshow/52099139.cms |title=NIT to become NMRDA |date=3 May 2016|website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> NMRDA was notified by the [[Government of Maharashtra]] in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/govt-finally-notifies-nmrda/articleshow/57524541.cms|title=Govt finally notifies NMRDA |first1=Ashish |last1=Roy |date=7 March 2017|website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> NMRDA has been made on the lines of [[Mumbai Metropolitan Region Development Authority]]. NMRDA has been mandated to monitor development in the metropolis comprising 721 villages across nine tehsils in the district. The body is headed by Metropolitan Commissioner, an [[Indian Administrative Service]] Officer appointed by the [[Government of Maharashtra|state government]] as was with the NIT chairman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/mudgal-holds-four-of-five-top-posts-of-the-city/articleshow/64018524.cms|title=Mudgal holds four of five top posts of the city |first1=Anjaya |last1=Anparthi |date=3 May 2018 |website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> Although delayed, NIT was to be dissolved and merged with NMC till 15 June 2018 as stated by the state government<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/complete-merger-with-nmc-by-june-15-govt-to-nit/05251222,%20https://www.nagpurtoday.in/complete-merger-with-nmc-by-june-15-govt-to-nit/05251222|title=Complete merger with NMC by June 15: Govt to NIT |first=Nagpur|last=News |date= |website=www.nagpurtoday.in |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> but has been given a stay order from Nagpur Bench of Bombay High Court in June 2018.<ref>http://thehitavada.com/Encyc/2017/12/3/State-Government-set-to-miss-deadline-for-NIT-dissolution.aspx</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/hc-stays-govts-move-to-dissolve-nit/articleshow/64578446.cms|title=HC stays govt's move to dissolve NIT |first1=Vaibhav |last1=Ganjapure|date=13 June 2018|website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Maharashtra government had appointed [[Larsen & Toubro]] (L&T) as the implementation partner to convert Nagpur into the country's first large scale, integrated, [[smart city]]. The state government had also decided to develop the city complete with five hubs, from textile centres to defence sector.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/infrastructure/lt-gets-maharashtra-government-contract-to-convert-nagpur-into-smart-city/articleshow/53724968.cms|title=L&T gets Maharashtra government contract to convert Nagpur into smart city |date=16 August 2016|access-date=16 August 2016}}</ref> Nagpur was selected from [[Maharashtra]] among other cities under [[Government of India|Government of India's]] [[Smart Cities Mission]]. City was selected in the third round of selection. For the implementation of the projects under [[Smart Cities Mission]] a special purpose vehicle was formed which was named Nagpur Smart and Sustainable City Development Corporation Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Smart-City-work-begins-in-14-days-of-selection/articleshow/54685592.cms |title=Smart City work begins in 14 days of selection |first1=Anjaya |last1=Anparthi|date=4 October 2016|website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nagpur Police]] is headed by a [[Police Commissioner]] who is of the rank of Additional Director General of Police of [[Maharashtra Police]]. Nagpur Police is divided into 5 Zones, each headed by a Deputy Commissioner of Police,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nagpurpolice.gov.in/know_your_DCPs|title=Nagpur Police|website=nagpurpolice.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/crime-branch-for-five-zones-inaugurated-simultaneously-in-the-city/08011738,%20https://www.nagpurtoday.in/crime-branch-for-five-zones-inaugurated-simultaneously-in-the-city/08011738|title=Crime Branch for five zones inaugurated simultaneously in the city|first=Nagpur|last=News|website=www.nagpurtoday.in}}</ref> while traffic zones are divided into eight zones each headed by an inspector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/with-over-18l-vehicles-city-to-get-2-more-traffic-zones/articleshow/65507337.cms |title=With over 18L vehicles, city to get 2 more traffic zones |first1=Proshun |last1=Chakraborty|date=22 August 2018|website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/one-traffic-cop-manning-3106-vehicles-in-city/articleshow/66976795.cms|title=One traffic cop manning 3,106 vehicles in Nagpur &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The state C.I.D Regional Headquarters<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mahacid.com/organization.htm|title=C.I.D. : Organization|publisher=|access-date=25 November 2016}}</ref> and State Reserve Police Force Campus<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mahapolice.gov.in/mahapolice/jsp/temp/srpf.jsp|title=Welcome to MPD, INDIA !!!|website=Mahapolice.gov.in|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> are situated in Nagpur.\n\n===Utility services===\nOriginally, all the utility services of the city were carried out by NMC departments, but from 2008 onwards privatisation had started for major utility services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/NMC-ayes-water-supply-privatisation/articleshow/1984268.cms|title=NMC ayes water supply privatisation |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> The Orange City Water Private Limited (OCW), a joint venture of [[Veolia Water|Veolia Water India Pvt. Ltd]] and Vishwaraj Infrastructure Ltd., manages the water supply for the city as well as Nagpur Municipal Corporation's water treatment plants at Gorewada, all the elevated service reservoirs, ground service reservoirs, master balancing reservoirs commonly known as water tanks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ocwindia.com/?page_id=28|title=History \u2013 Orange City Water|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> This joint venture was established in November 2011 and was awarded the contract to execute 24x7 water supply project and operational and maintenance of waterworks for 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Double-blow-for-Orange-City-Water-Limited-as-Nagpur-Municipal-Corporation-Centre-tighten-strings/articleshow/13828881.cms|title=Double blow for Orange City Water Limited as Nagpur Municipal Corporation, Centre tighten strings |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Kanak Resources Management Ltd. was awarded the contract for garbage collection in the city as per Nagpur Bin Free Project in 2009 by NMC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kanakresources.com/index.php/2013-09-10-09-41-47/nagpur-bin-free-project|title=Nagpur Bin Free Project|last=Administrator|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tniusnews.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=16902:nmc-to-beautify-locations-of-earlier-garbage-bins&catid=157:public-health-sanitation-&Itemid=206 |title=NMC to beautify locations of earlier garbage bins \u2013 TNIUS, Coimbatore |publisher=Tniusnews.org |date=8 November 2010 |accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref> It was replaced by AG Enviro Infra Project Pvt Ltd and BVG India in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/nmc-to-lift-garbage-in-2-shifts-after-two-new-agencies-take-charge/articleshow/71318946.cms|title=Nagpur Municipal Corporation to lift garbage in 2 shifts after two new agencies take charge &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> In [[electricity supply]], which was first managed by [[Maharashtra State Electricity Board|MSEB]] was then replaced by [[Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Company Limited|MSEDCL]]. After some years the distribution franchisee system was introduced to reduce the losses in the divisions and so Spanco Nagpur Discom Ltd.(SNDL) was awarded the distribution franchisee for 15 years to manage three of the four divisions from Nagpur Urban circle namely, Civil Lines, Mahal and Gandhibagh on 23 February 2011 by [[Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Company Limited|MSEDCL]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahadiscom.in/Nagpur-MSEDCL_SpancoAgreement_01.pdf |title=Distribution Franchise Agreement |website=Mahadiscom.in |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poweradvisor.in/news/detail/2364|title=MSEDCL awards distribution franchisee contract for Nagpur urban circle to Spanco Ltd. \u2013 power News \u2013 Power Advisor|last=IndiaElectron.com|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> The power distribution and maintenance for the fourth division i.e. Congress Nagar division was still managed by [[Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Company Limited|MSEDCL]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mahadiscom.in/Nagpur-Distribution-franchisee-RFP_DFA-2010.pdf |title=Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Co. Ltd |website=Mahadiscom.in |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> As SNDL mounted losses it intimated [[Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Company Limited|MSEDCL]] to takeover the franchises as it was unable to maintain the franchisee areas under it. [[Maharashtra State Electricity Distribution Company Limited|MSEDCL]] thus took over all the Nagpur urban circle areas as on September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/msedcl-takes-over-sndl-area-staffers-to-be-recruited-as-well/articleshow/71039586.cms|title=MSEDCL takes over SNDL area, staffers to be recruited as well &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Nagpur Fire Brigade has nine fire stations at various locations in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nmcnagpur.gov.in/fire-brigade-department|title=Fire Brigade Department, Nagpur Municipal corporation &#124; Nagpur Municipal Corporation|website=www.nmcnagpur.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/only-one-firefighter-for-6263-properties-in-city/articleshow/67388949.cms|title=Only one firefighter for 6,263 properties in Nagpur! &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/new-fire-station-almost-ready-but-wheres-the-staff/articleshow/67999500.cms|title=New fire station almost ready, but where's the staff? &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> [[India Post]] which is a governmental postal department has two head post offices and many post offices and sub-post offices at various locations in the city and are part of the logistics services in the city along with various other private operators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/GPO-Head-Post-Office-to-get-ATMs/articleshow/21906550.cms|title=GPO, Head Post Office to get ATMs |website=The Times of India |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\n{{see also|List of hospitals in Nagpur}}\nNMC in collaboration with [[Central Government]], [[State Government]], [[UNICEF]], [[World Health Organization]] and [[Non-governmental organisation]] conducts and maintains various health schemes in the city. City health line is an initiative started by [[Nagpur Municipal Corporation|NMC]] dedicated to the health of citizens of Nagpur. This includes providing computerised comparative information and action in the field to local citizens.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://ijsetr.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/IJSETR-VOLUME-2-ISSUE-5-1104-1107.pdf |title=A Decisive Study on Health Department of Nagpur Municipal Corporation (NMC), Nagpur |journal=International Journal of Science, Engineering and Technology Research |volume=2 |date=May 2013 |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> NMC runs three indoor patient hospitals including Indira Gandhi Rugnalaya at LAD square, Panchpaoli Maternity Hospital in Panchpaoli and Isolation Hospital in Immamwada. Besides, the civic body runs three big diagnostic centres at Mahal, Sadar and also at Indira Gandhi Rugnalaya. Apart from these, NMC has 57 outpatient dispensaries (OPDs), including 23 health posts sanctioned under Union Government's schemes, 15 allopathy hospitals, 12 ayurvedic hospitals, three homoeopathy hospitals, three naturopathy hospitals and one Unani hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/NMC-to-hand-over-hospitals-to-pvt-players/articleshow/10170107.cms|title=NMC to hand over hospitals to pvt players |first1=Anjaya |last1=Anparthi |date=29 September 2011 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> In 2013, [[ABP News]]-[[Ipsos]] declared Nagpur the country's best city for health care services.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sainani |first=Richa |url=http://www.zero-mile.net/4-awards-for-nagpur-for-best-city-2013 |title=4 Awards For Nagpur For Best City 2013 |publisher=Zero-mile.net |date= |accessdate=30 October 2013}}</ref> The city is home to [[list of hospitals in Nagpur|numerous hospitals]], some run by the government and some private and consists of various super-specialty and multi-specialty ones. Recently various cancer speciality hospitals providing treatment till tertiary care for cancer patients have been established in the city making it a natural medical hub for nearby areas and boosting healthcare system in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/us-institute-nangias-start-cancer-hosp-in-midc/articleshow/62907340.cms|title=US institute-Nangias start cancer hospital in MIDC |first1=Snehlata |last1=Shrivastav |date=14 February 2018 |website=The Times of India|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/healthcare-global-launches-cancer-centre-in-nagpur-2299885.html|title=Healthcare Global launches cancer centre in Nagpur|author=|date=|website=Moneycontrol|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/New-cancer-hospital-aims-to-bring-affordable-care-to-region/articleshow/52963121.cms |title=New cancer hospital aims to bring affordable care to region |first1=Shakti |last1=Singh |date=29 June 2016 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Nagpur is a health hub for Central India and caters to a large geographical area arbitrarily bounded by Delhi in the north, Kolkata in the east, Mumbai-Pune in the west and Hyderabad in the south. People from [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Orissa]], [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Telangana]] regularly come to Nagpur for their health needs.<ref name=TET/> Nagpur boasts of super-specialty physicians and surgeons<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jointreplacementclinic.com/arthritis-content.php?app=2 |title=Welcome to Arthritis & Joint Replacement Clinic |publisher= |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> serving its population in both public sector government-run hospitals and well equipped private hospitals catering to all strata of society.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jointreplacementclinic.com/ |title=Arthritis & Joint Replacement Clinic |publisher= |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences, Nagpur|AIIMS]] is the latest feather in the cap of Nagpur health care services which will be located near MIHAN.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/AIIMS-to-come-up-on-200-acres-near-GMCH/articleshow/40830845.cms |title=AIIMS to come up on 200 acres near GMCH |date=23 August 2014 |work=The Times of India|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to 2005 National Family Health Survey, Nagpur has a fertility rate of 1.9 which is below the [[Sub-replacement fertility|replacement level]].<ref name=\"pdf.usaid.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://pdf.usaid.gov/pdf_docs/Pnadq634.pdf |title=Health and Living Conditions in Eight Indian Cities [OD58&#93; |date= |accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref>{{rp|46,47}} The infant [[mortality rate]] was 43 per 1,000 live births, and the mortality rate for children under five was 50 per 1,000 live births.<ref name=\"pdf.usaid.gov\"/> {{rp|47,48}} About 57% slum and 72% non-slum children have received all the mandatory vaccines which include [[BCG vaccine|BCG]], [[Measles vaccine|measles]] and full courses of [[Polio vaccine|polio]] and [[DPT vaccine|DPT]].<ref name=\"pdf.usaid.gov\"/>{{rp|48,49}}  In Nagpur, 78 percent of poor children are anaemic, including 49 percent who have moderate to severe anaemia.<ref name=\"pdf.usaid.gov\"/>{{rp|55}} About 45% of children under five years of age and 31% of women are underweight.<ref name=\"pdf.usaid.gov\"/>{{rp|54,55}} The poor people from the city mostly cite the reason of the lack of a nearby facility, poor quality of care and excessive waiting time for not visiting any government hospitals for treatment.<ref name=\"pdf.usaid.gov\"/>{{rp|61}} According to the National Family Health Survey (NFHS-4) of 2015-16 for Nagpur, households having improved drinking water source is 95.3%, households having improved [[sanitation]] facility is 77.3% and households having [[clean fuel]] for cooking is 87.6%. [[Health Insurance]] coverage among households in the city are 19.5%. [[Female sterilisation]] is more prominent than [[male sterilization|male sterilisation]] in Nagpur. Institutional births in the city is 97%. Children below 5 years who are anaemic are 43.50%, while women and men in the age group of 15 to 49 years who are anaemic are 45.00% and 21.20% respectively.<ref>http://rchiips.org/nfhs/FCTS/MH/MH_FactSheet_505_Nagpur.pdf</ref>\n\n===Military establishments===\n[[File:Sitabuldi fort gate.JPG|thumb|Sitabuldi fort is home to [[Indian Army]]'s 118th infantry battalion.]]\nNagpur is an important city for the Indian armed forces. [[Maintenance Command, Indian Air Force|Maintenance Command]] of [[Indian Air Force]] has its current headquarters at Vayusena Nagar in Nagpur. It houses [[Mi-8]] helicopters and the IAF carriers [[IL-76]] and handles the [[maintenance, repair, and operations]] of all aircraft, helicopters and other equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianairforce.nic.in/show_command.php?pg_id=31&page_type=command&comm_id=7|title=MAINTENANCE COMMAND|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe ordnance factory and staff college of ordnance factory Ambajhari and National Academy of Defence Production for Group A officer of ordnance factories are in the western part of the city. [[Sitabuldi Fort]] is managed by the 118th infantry battalion of the [[Indian Army]] and citizens are allowed to visit the premises on certain days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/sitabuldi-fort-open-for-public-on-maharashtra-day/04241813|title=Sitabuldi Fort open for public on Maharashtra Day|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 'raison d'\u00eatre' for Kamptee, the military cantonment, is still operational. [[Kamptee]] Cantonment houses the Officers Training Academy for [[National Cadet Corps (India)|National Cadets Corps]], which is the only one of its kind. It is also the home of one of the oldest and most respected regiments in the Indian Army, the [[Brigade of the Guards]]. Guards, located at Kamptee, are the only group in the Indian Army which have won two PVC ([[Param Veer Chakra]]), the highest gallantry awarded to soldiers for wartime operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbkamptee.org/|title=Cantonment Board Kamptee|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> There are also other important units such as the Institute of Military Law and a well equipped military hospital to care for the health of the soldiers. The Army Postal Service centre is also operational in the cantonment since 1948, to provide training to personnel of Department of Post who volunteer themselves for the Army. Nagpur's [[National Civil Defence College]] provides civil defence and disaster management training to pupils from all over India and abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdcnagpur.nic.in/institute.htm|title=NATIONAL CIVIL DEFENCE COLLEGE|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Indian Air Force's IL-76 transport planes nicknamed \"Gajraj\" are also based in Nagpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dqweek.com/nagpur-the-orange-city-set-to-shine-as-investment-hub/|title=You are being redirected...|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n=== Population ===\n{{IndiaCensusPop\n|title= Nagpur population\n|1981= 1219500\n|1991= 1664000\n|2001= 2129500\n|2011= 2405665\n|estimate=\n|estyear=\n|estref=\n|footnote= Source: [[Census of India]] \n}}\n\n{{As of|2011|alt=As of the}} [[2011 census of India|2011 census]], Nagpur municipality has a population of 2,405,665. The total population constitute, 1,225,405 males and 1,180,270 females. The total children (ages 0\u20136) are 247,078, of whom 128,290 are boys and 118,788 are girls. Children form 10.27% of total population of Nagpur. The total number of slums number 179,952, in which 859,487 people reside. This is around 35.73% of the total population of Nagpur. The municipality has a [[human sex ratio|sex ratio]] of 963 females per 1,000 males and child sex ratio of 926 girls per 1,000 boys. 1,984,123 people are literate, of whom 1,036,097 are male and 948,026 are female. Average literacy rate of Nagpur city are 91.92%. Men are 94.44% and women are 89.31% literate.<ref name=\"census\" />\n\n=== Religion and language ===\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Nagpur\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|59.46}}\n{{bar percent|[[Buddhist]]|gold|25.57}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|11.95}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|dodgerblue|1.15}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|0.90}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhism|Sikhs]]|darkkhaki|0.68}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.30}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes People with no particular religion.</small>\n}}\n[[Hinduism]] is majority religion in Nagpur city with 59.46% followers. [[Buddhism]] is second most popular religion in Nagpur city with 25.57% following it. In Nagpur city, [[Islam]] is followed by 11.95%, [[Christianity]] by 1.15%, [[Jainism]] by 0.90% and [[Sikhism]] by 0.68%. Around 0.10% stated 'Other Religion' and approximately 0.20% stated 'No Particular Religion'.\n\nIn Nagpur, [[Marathi language|Marathi]] is the official and most spoken language. [[Hindi]] and [[Varhadi dialect|Varhadi]] (a dialect of Marathi) are also spoken in and around the city. In addition, the Marathi spoken in the city is quite distinct that from western Maharashtra. [[English language|English]], Hindi and Marathi are used for the transaction of business in the Legislature of the State.<ref name=\"whitelight.in\">{{cite web|url=http://whitelight.in/dci-india/nagpur.pdf |title=Nagpur \u2013 Orange City |website=Whitelight.in |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bombayhighcourt.nic.in/libweb/acts/1965.05.PDF |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402225839/http://bombayhighcourt.nic.in/libweb/acts/1965.05.PDF |archivedate= 2 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\nNagpur is an emerging metropolis. In 2004, it was ranked the fastest-growing city in India in terms of the number of households with an annual income of \u20b91 crore (10 million) or more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.co.in/money/2004/jul/15rich.htm |title=Nagpur, fastest growing crorepati city |publisher=Rediff.co.in |date=15 July 2004 |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> Nagpur has been the main centre of commerce in the region of [[Vidarbha]] since its early days and is an important trading location. Although, Nagpur's economic importance gradually declined relative to [[Mumbai]] and [[Pune]] after the merging of [[Vidarbha]] into Maharashtra because of a period of neglect by the state government, the city's economy later recovered.<ref name=\"Economic Overview Of Nagpur\">{{Cite news|url=http://travelspedia.com/news/South-Asia/India/Maharashtra/Nagpur/Economic-Overview-Of-Nagpur.html|title=Economic Overview of Nagpur|date=31 December 2007|publisher=travelspedia.com|accessdate=3 July 2008}}</ref> \n[[File:Sitabuldi Market.JPG|thumb|Sitabuldi Market, one of the busiest commercial areas of Nagpur]]\n\n[[File:Nagpur Reserve Bank.JPG|left|thumb|Nagpur branch of the [[Reserve Bank of India]]]]\n\nNagpur city had attracted \u20b95000 crore worth of investment in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpur.in/nagpur-economy/ |title=Nagpur Economy and Industry \u2013 Nagpur Economic Boom |publisher=Nagpur.in |date= |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Investment in Nagpur in 2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2003/jun/13investment.htm|title=Bangalore top investment destination|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=4 July 2006}}</ref> Its per capita income was {{INR convert|123610}} in 2015 and its [[GDP]] was estimated to be $15.10 billion in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/nagpur-turns-city-of-lakhpatis-in-survey-but-with-darker-side-as-well/04031807|title=Nagpur turns city of \"Lakhpatis\" in survey but with darker side as well|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> The city is important for the banking sector as it hosts the regional office of [[Reserve Bank of India]], which was opened on 10 September 1956. The Reserve Bank of India has two branches in Nagpur, one of which houses India's entire gold assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbi.org.in/regionalbranch/nagpur/profile.aspx |title=Reserve Bank of India |publisher=Rbi.org.in |date=|accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> [[Sitabuldi]] market in central Nagpur, known as the heart of the city, is the major commercial market area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amritt.com/india-business-guide/doing-business-in-nagpur/|title=Doing business in Nagpur \u2013 Major cities in India|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nNagpur is home to ice-cream manufacturer Dinshaws,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/hjKuKrUJlZd2mQsDmsJdNN/Dinshaws-Dairy-plans-to-raise-100-million-from-PE-funds.html|title=Dinshaw's Dairy plans to raise $100 million from PE funds|first=Reghu|last=Balakrishnan|date=1 October 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Indian dry food manufacturer [[Haldiram's]], Indian ready-to-cook food manufacturer Actchawa, [[spice]] manufacturer Suruchi International<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suruchiinternational.com/contact-us.php|title=Suruchi Spices Pvt. Ltd.|author=|date=|website=www.suruchiinternational.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> and [[Ayurvedic]] products company [[Vicco Group|Vicco]] and [[Baidyanath group|Baidyanath]].<ref name=\"Prominent companies of Nagpur\">{{cite web|url=http://nagpur.nic.in/htmldocs/Welcome_to_Orange_City.pdf|title=Welcome to Orange City|publisher=National Informatics Centre, Nagpur|accessdate=26 June 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060928090744/http://nagpur.nic.in/htmldocs/Welcome_to_Orange_City.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 28 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nFor centuries, Nagpur has been famous for its orange gardens in the country, hence the name \"Orange City\". Orange cultivation has been expanding and it is the biggest marketplace for oranges in the country.<ref name=\"whitelight.in\"/> The Maharashtra Agro Industrial Development Corporation has its multi fruit processing division called Nagpur Orange Grower's Association (NOGA) which has an installed capacity of 4,950&nbsp;MT of fruits per annum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maidcmumbai.com/processed_foods_noga/about_noga|title=About NOGA|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Orange is also exported to various regions in the country as well to other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/nagpur-orange-set-for-export-first-consignment-for-sri-lanka/|title=Nagpur orange set for export, first consignment for Sri Lanka|date=17 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/article/markets/commodities/three-government-agencies-join-hands-to-promote-exports-of-nagpur-oranges/139876/|title=Three government agencies join hands to promote exports of Nagpur oranges|date=23 September 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Nagpur-student-to-help-orange-export-to-Netherlands/articleshow/39577218.cms|title=Nagpur student to help orange export to Netherlands |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Nagpur is also famous for the cotton and silk which is woven by its large Koshti population of handloom weavers which are around 5,000.<ref name=\"whitelight.in\"/>\n\nNagpur and the [[Vidarbha]] region have a very prominent power sector as compared to the rest of Maharashtra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/nagpur-a-new-attraction-for-highly-skilled-professionals/07161249|title=Nagpur \u2013 A New Attraction for Highly Skilled Professionals|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Koradi Thermal Power Station]] and [[Khaparkheda Thermal Power Station]] are two major [[thermal power station]]s located near Nagpur and operated by [[MSPGCL]]. [[NTPC Limited|NTPC]] has a super thermal power plant called [[Mauda Super Thermal Power Station]] in [[Mauda]] around 40&nbsp;km from Nagpur and Vidarbha Industries Power Limited (a subsidiary of Reliance Power) is situated at [[Butibori]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Category: Maharashtra Thermal Projects |url=http://thermalpower.industry-focus.net/maharashtra-thermal-projects/89-vidarbha-industries-power-to-set-up-300-mw-2x150-mw-group-captive-thermal-power-project-at-butibori-vidarbha-industries-power-to-set-up-300-mw-2x150-mw-group-captive-thermal-power-project-at-butibori.html |title=Vidarbha Industries Power to set up 300 MW (2x150 MW) Group Captive Thermal Power Project at Butibori |publisher=Thermalpower.industry-focus.net |date= |accessdate=12 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TCS Nagpur Campus.jpg|thumb|TCS Campus in MIHAN Nagpur]]\nThe [[Multi-modal International Cargo Hub and Airport at Nagpur|Multi-modal International Hub Airport at Nagpur]] (MIHAN) is an ongoing project for the [[Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar International Airport]], Nagpur. The government of Maharashtra formed a [[special purpose entity]], [[Maharashtra Airport Development Company]], for the development of [[MIHAN]]. \n[[File:IT Park.JPG|thumb|left|Persistent Campus at IT Park, Parsodi]]\n\nProminent [[Information Technology]] companies such as [[Tata Consultancy Services|TCS]], [[Mahindra Satyam|Tech Mahindra]], [[HCL Technologies|HCL]], [[GlobalLogic]], [[Persistent Systems]] and [[Hexaware]] are located at various IT parks in Nagpur .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/mihan-fact-vs-fiction-or-why-this-will-be-the-states-first-genuine-smart-city/04132047|title=MIHAN Fact vs Fiction; Why this will be the state's first genuine Smart City|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Mihans-non-starter-companies-want-money-back/articleshow/50358473.cms|title=Mihan's non-starter companies want money back |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Infosys]] has commenced its construction work for its Nagpur campus at [[MIHAN]] [[Special Economic Zone]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infosys.com/newsroom/press-releases/Pages/commences-work-nagpur-campus.aspx|title=Infosys Commences Work on its Third Campus in Maharashtra|author=Infosys Limited|publisher=|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>  [http://www.tata.com/company/profile.aspx?sectid=EMJQ4hnQSrY= TAL Manufacturing Solutions] has its facility in the [[Special Economic Zone|SEZ]] for manufacturing structural components for Boeing's 787 Dreamliner aeroplane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tal.co.in/about-us/about-tal.html|title=TAL Mfg Solutions :: Home|publisher=}}</ref> [[Air India]] has its MRO Facility in the [[Special Economic Zone|SEZ]] which was constructed by [[Boeing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/air-indias-mihan-workshop-to-be-flagged-off-next-year/article25711710.ece|title=Air India's Mihan workshop to be flagged off next year |first=Rahul|last=Wadke |date=|website=@businessline|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-08-16/news/65525458_1_the-mro-nagpur-mro-air-india-engineering-services |title=Boeing says it's formally handed over Nagpur MRO facility to Air India |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/air-indias-nagpur-mro-ready-for-commercial-operation/article7211164.ece|title=Air India's Nagpur MRO ready for commercial operation|first=Lalatendu|last=Mishra|date=15 May 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Dassault Reliance Aerospace Limited (DRAL) has its manufacturing facility in [[MIHAN]] where it is manufacturing [[Dassault Falcon 2000|Falcon jets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/dassult-to-roll-out-falcon-2000-business-jets-from-nagpur-in-three-years/story/318140.html|title=Inside the Reliance-Dassault factory that's making Falcon 2000 jets in Nagpur|author=|date=|website=www.businesstoday.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/dassault-reliance-starts-production-says-rafale-not-part-of-immediate-plan/videoshow/67904336.cms|title=Nagpur Dassault unit starts Falcon production amid Rafale heat|first1=ET Online &#124; 08|last1=Feb 2019|first2=11:46 Pm|last2=Ist|via=economictimes.indiatimes.com}}</ref> Pharmaceutical company [[Lupin Limited|Lupin]] also has its facility in the SEZ.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/usfda-completes-inspection-of-lupins-nagpur-facility-no-adverse-observations-4309551.html|title=USFDA completes inspection of Lupin's Nagpur facility, no adverse observations|website=Moneycontrol}}</ref>\n\nApart from [[MIHAN]] [[Special Economic Zone|SEZ]] the city has three prominent [[MIDC]] areas nearby.<ref>http://dcmsme.gov.in/dips/nagpur%20dips%2012-13.pdf</ref> The [[Butibori]] industrial area is one of the largest in Asia in terms of area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnb.co.in/SME_cluster_series2012_Nagpur/PDF/Cluster_Overview.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=31 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192351/https://www.dnb.co.in/SME_cluster_series2012_Nagpur/PDF/Cluster_Overview.pdf |archivedate= 4 March 2016 }}</ref> The estate's largest unit is Indo Rama Synthetics, which manufactures synthetic polyester yarn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indoramaindia.com/reachus.php|title=Reach Us \u2013 IndoRama|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Other units in Butibori include the power transmission company Gammon India Limited (T & D),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transrailltd.com/contacts.html|title=Associated Transrail Structures|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Gammon India Ltd. (Infra), KEC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kecrpg.com/manufacturing/towermanufactuting|title=Towermanufacturing|first=KEC International Ltd -|last=India|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Calderys|Calderys India]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calderys.com/contact-us/find-an-office|title=CALDERYS INDIA|publisher=|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> Unitech Power Transmissions Limited,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitech-power.com/network.html|title=Power Transmission Systems|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> ACC Nihon Castings Ltd<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalogs.infobanc.com/accnihon/contact-us.htm|title=ACC-Nihon Castings Ltd.|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Electrolux]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.midcindia.org/Pages/IndustrialPage.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=23 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100902172536/http://www.midcindia.org/Pages/IndustrialPage.aspx |archivedate= 2 September 2010 }}</ref> [[CEAT Tyres]] has its [[Tire|tyre]] manufacturing plant in [[Butibori]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/ceat-commissions-new-unit-at-nagpur-plant-116032901087_1.html|title=Ceat commissions new unit at Nagpur plant|first=Press Trust of|last=India|date=29 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=25 April 2019|via=Business Standard|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref> The [[Hingna]] industrial estate on the western fringes of the city is made up of around 900 small and medium industrial units.<ref>http://mpcb.gov.in/images/pdf/surveystatushingna.pdf</ref> The major ones among them are the tractor manufacturing plant of [[Mahindra and Mahindra]], casting units of NECO Ltd.,<ref name=\"Neco in nagpur and largest Indian group...\">{{cite web |url=http://www.necoindia.com/corporate_overview.htm |title=Corporate Overview of Neco|publisher=Neco Group of Industries|accessdate=26 June 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060201055548/http://necoindia.com/corporate_overview.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 February 2006}}</ref> [[Candico]]<ref name=\"Candico plant largest confectionary plant in India\">{{cite web|url=http://www.candicoindia.com/production.html|title=Candico plant in Nagpur|publisher=Candico Ltd.|accessdate=4 July 2006}}</ref>), Bharat Containers making aluminium aerosol cans<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bharatcontainers.com/contact_us.html|title=Bharat Containers|author=|date=|website=www.bharatcontainers.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Pix Transmissions,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pixtrans.com/contact_us/PIX-Transmissions-Ltd.html|title=PIX-Transmissions|author=|date=|website=www.pixtrans.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> and Sanvijay Rolling & Engineering Ltd. (SREL).<ref name=\"Sanvijay largest...Central India\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanvijay.com/company-overciew.html|title=Sanvijay Group website homepage|publisher=Sanvijay Group Ltd.|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> [[Kalmeshwar]] MIDC has 164 industrial plots. JSW Steel,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsw.in/steel/kalmeshwar-works|title=JSW Steel|author=|date=|website=jsw.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> KTM Textile, ESAB India Ltd,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vccircle.com/lt-to-sell-welding-products-unit-to-uks-esab-for-80-mn|title=L&T to sell welding products unit to UK's ESAB for $80 mn|date=12 October 2017|website=VCCircle}}</ref> ZIM Pharma Ltd, Metlok Pvt. Ltd., Unijuels life sciences, Chemfield Pharmaceuticals Private Ltd., Minex Injection Product Private Ltd., Minex Metallurgical Co.Ltd.<ref>http://www.minexindia.com/contact-us.php</ref> and Porohit Textile are a few big names.\n\nOwing to rich natural resources in the region, mining is a major activity. Several government organisations related to the mining industry are based in Nagpur, which includes [[Western Coalfields|Western Coalfields Limited]] (one of the eight fully owned subsidiaries of [[Coal India]] Limited), [[MOIL (company)|MOIL]] and Indian Bureau of Mines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibm.nic.in/index.php?c=pages&m=index&id=97&mid=18824|title=Controller General -|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of educational institutions in Nagpur}}\n[[File:RSTM Nagpur University.jpg|thumb|left|RSTM Nagpur University Campus]]\n[[File:College of Agriculture, Nagpur.jpg|thumb|College of Agriculture, Nagpur]]\n\nNagpur is a major education hub in Central India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lokmat.com/nagpur/nagpur-became-hub-high-and-technical-education/|title=\u0928\u093e\u0917\u092a\u0942\u0930 \u092c\u0928\u0932\u0947 \u0909\u091a\u094d\u091a \u0906\u0923\u093f \u091f\u0947\u0915\u094d\u0928\u093f\u0915\u0932 \u0936\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0923\u093e\u091a\u0947 \u0939\u092c|last=author/lokmat-news-network|date=3 April 2019|website=Lokmat|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere are two types of schools in the city. [[Nagpur Municipal Corporation|NMC]] (Government) run schools and private schools run by trusts. These schools follow the [[10+2+3 plan|10+2+3/4 plan]] (15 years of schooling leading to the first degree), the first ten years constituting school education consisting of four years primary level, three years of upper primary level and three years of high school level with a public examination at the end of tenth class and 12th class constituting the Secondary and Higher Secondary Board Examination respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mpsp.maharashtra.gov.in/SITE/Information/elementaryEducation.aspx?ID=1 |title=Welcome to MPSP |website=Mpsp.maharashtra.gov.in |date= |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> This is followed by either a general degree course in a chosen field of study or a professional degree course, such as law, engineering and medicine. These schools are governed by either of the following boards: [[Maharashtra State Board of Secondary and Higher Secondary Education]], [[Central Board of Secondary Education|Central Board for Secondary Education]] (CBSE), [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] (ICSE) and The [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB).\n\nAdmission to professional graduation colleges in Nagpur is through [[Maharashtra Health and Technical Common Entrance Test|MHT-CET]], [[Joint Entrance Examination \u2013 Main|JEE(Main)]], [[Common Admission Test|CAT]], [[Common Law Admission Test|CLAT]], [[Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering|GATE]], [[Common Management Admission Test|CMAT]], [[Graduate Management Admission Test|GMAT]] and [[National Eligibility and Entrance Test|NEET]].\n\nNagpur has four state universities: [[Rashtrasant Tukadoji Maharaj Nagpur University]] (founded in 1923 as Nagpur University, one of the oldest in the country<ref name=\"one of the oldest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rcert.ac.in/nag-uni.htm|title=Nagpur University|publisher=Rajiv Gandhi College of Engineering, Research, and Technology website|accessdate=12 August 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060907150954/http://www.rcert.ac.in/nag-uni.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 7 September 2006}}</ref> and having more than 600 affiliated colleges),<ref name=\"Colleges Affiliated to Nagpur University\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpuruniversity.org/links/affiliated_colleges.htm |title=Colleges Affiliated to Nagpur University |publisher=www.nagpuruniversity.org/links/affiliated_colleges.htm |date= |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> [[Maharashtra Animal and Fishery Sciences University]], [[Kavikulaguru Kalidas Sanskrit University]] and [[Maharashtra National Law University, Nagpur|Maharashtra National Law University]].\n\n[[Vasantrao Naik Government Institute of Arts and Social Sciences]] (established in 1885 as Morris college) is an old college in the city. College of Agriculture<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pdkv.ac.in/|title=College of Agriculture, Nagpur eg|accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> is another old college in the city, founded in 1906 by the then British Government. It is one of the first five agriculture colleges in the country.\n\nNagpur has four government medical colleges: [[Government Medical College (Nagpur)|Government Medical College]], [[Indira Gandhi Government Medical College, Nagpur]], Government Dental College and Government Ayurvedic College, and also a private MBBS institute, N. K. P. Salve Institute of Medical Sciences and Research Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nkpsims.edu.in/|title=NKP Salve Institute Of Medical Sciences And Research Center|author=|date=|website=nkpsims.edu.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dmer.org/dmer/vidharbha/nagpur/nagpur-mbbs.html|title=Medical Colleges In Nagpur|accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> Medical colleges in the city are affiliated to [[Maharashtra University of Health Sciences]]. [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences, Nagpur|All India Institute of Medical Sciences]] has been established in 2018 and it has started its classes from [[Government Medical College (Nagpur)|GMCH]] campus temporarily till its own campus gets constructed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/4-yrs-on-aiims-classes-to-begin-at-gmch-from-august/articleshow/64429834.cms|title=NRLC: 4 yrs on, AIIMS classes to begin at GMCH from August |first1=Vaibhav |last1=Ganjapure |date=3 June 2018 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nMost [[engineering]] colleges in the city are affiliated with [[Rashtrasant Tukadoji Maharaj Nagpur University]]. [[Laxminarayan Institute of Technology]] (established 1942) is a chemical engineering and technology institute located in Nagpur and managed directly by [[Rashtrasant Tukadoji Maharaj Nagpur University]]. [[Government Polytechnic, Nagpur]] (established 1914) is one of the oldest polytechnic in India. [[Visvesvaraya National Institute of Technology]], located in the city, is the only [[National Institutes of Technology|NIT]] in Maharashtra. [[Indian Institute of Information Technology, Nagpur|Indian Institute of Information Technology]] has been established as a PPP with [[Tata Consultancy Services|TCS]] and Ceinsys (erstwhile ADCC Infocad) as industry partners in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Ngp-Pune-IIITs-fees-fixed-at-Rs90k-per-yr/articleshow/51031539.cms |title=Ngp, Pune IIITs fees fixed at Rs90k per yr |first1=Vaibhav |last1=Ganjapure |date=18 February 2016 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/iiit-nagpur-gets-130-more-seats-for-new-session/articleshow/59276279.cms|title=IIIT-Nagpur gets 130 more seats for new session |first1=Vaibhav |last1=Ganjapure |date=23 June 2017 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Other prominent engineering colleges in the city include [[G. H. Raisoni College of Engineering Nagpur]], [[Shri Ramdeobaba College of Engineering and Management]], [[Yeshwantrao Chavan College of Engineering]] and [[Government College of Engineering, Nagpur|Government College of Engineering]], [[Cummins College of Engineering for Women, Nagpur|Cummins College Of Engineering For Women, Nagpur]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Govt-engg-college-to-start-this-session/articleshow/50445159.cms|title=Govt engg college to start this session &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/gs-college-first-commerce-institute-to-get-autonomy-in-region/articleshow/64485756.cms|title=GS College first commerce institute to get autonomy in region |first1=Sarfaraz |last1=Ahmed |date=7 June 2018 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nNagpur has two major management institutes, [[Indian Institute of Management Nagpur|Indian Institute of Management]] established in 2015 and [[Institute of Management Technology, Nagpur|Institute of Management Technology]], private management college, established in 2004. [[Symbiosis International University]] has its campus in the city which contains two of its institute namely Symbiosis Institute of Business Management and Symbiosis Law School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/nagpur-will-be-cambridge-of-east-symbiosys-founder/articleshow/70424364.cms|title=Nagpur will be Cambridge of East: Symbiosys founder &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ganjapure |first1=Vaibhav |title=Symbiosis opens its 2nd biggest campus in Ngp, to start classes from July {{!}} Nagpur News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/symbiosis-opens-its-2nd-biggest-campus-in-ngp-to-start-classes-from-july/articleshow/68981839.cms |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=22 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[G.S. College of Commerce and Economics]], established in 1945, is the first [[commerce]] [[institute]] in the region to get [[autonomous]] status.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahmed |first1=Sarfaraz |title=GS College first commerce institute to get autonomy in region {{!}} Nagpur News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/gs-college-first-commerce-institute-to-get-autonomy-in-region/articleshow/64485756.cms |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=7 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nNagpur also has other centrally funded institutes like [[National Power Training Institute]], [[Central Institute for Cotton Research]], [[Central Institute of Mining and Fuel Research]], [[Central Power Research Institute]], [[National Academy of Direct Taxes]], [[National Civil Defence College]], [[National Research Centre for Citrus]], [[Petroleum and Explosives Safety Organisation]], and [[National Environmental Engineering Research Institute]].\n\nGovernment Chitrakala Mahavidyalaya is also a premier institute in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://govtchitrakalamahavidyalayanagpur.com/|title=Welcome to Govt. Chitrakala Mahavidyala Nagpur|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Nagpur also has an [[IGNOU]] and [[YCMOU]] regional centre.<ref name=\"IGNOU Regional Center Nagpur\">{{cite web|url=http://rcnagpur.ignou.ac.in/ |title=Welcome to IGNOU Nagpur Regional Centre |publisher=Rcnagpur.ignou.ac.in |date= |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n=== Cultural events and literature ===\n\nThe city contains people from other Indian states as well as people belonging to the world's major faiths, and yet is known for staying calm during communal conflicts in India.<ref name=\"Peaceful Nagpur, hospitality/\"> {{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020317/spectrum/main5.htm|title=Celebrating a unique city|work=The Tribune |location=India|accessdate=1 June 2006}}</ref> Nagpur plays host to cultural events throughout the year. Cultural and literary societies in Nagpur include [[Vidarbha]] Sahitya Sangh (for development of [[Marathi language|Marathi]]), [[Vidarbha]] Rashtrabhasha Prachar Samiti (promotion and spreading [[Hindi]]) and [[Vidarbha]] [[Hindi]] Sahitya Sammelan (for promoting [[Hindi]]). [[Marathi Sahitya Sammelan]], the conference on [[Marathi language|Marathi]] Literature were held twice in Nagpur city. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.halbadarpan.com/|title=Halba Darpan|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Nagpur also hosts the annual Orange City Literature festival since 2019 and Vidarbha Literary Fest since 2020, featuring local and international authors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/orange-city-lit-festival-promises-treats-aplenty/articleshow/72355304.cms|title=Orange City Lit Festival promises treats aplenty |date=4 December 2019|first=Shreya |last=Tinkhede|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehitavada.com/Encyc/2020/2/9/-VLF-will-start-new-era-of-knowledge-First-Vidarbha-Literary-Festival-VLF-off-to-a-grand-start.html|title='VLF will start new era of knowledge' First Vidarbha Literary Festival (VLF) off to a grand start|website=www.thehitavada.com|language=en|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> Nagpur is the head office of Aadim Samvidhan Sanrakshan Samiti(working for the rights of scheduled tribes).\n\nThe [[South-Central Zone Cultural Centre]] also sponsors cultural events in Nagpur city, such as the Orange City Craft Mela and Folk Dance Festival, [[Vidarbha]] which is noted for its numerous folk-dances.<ref name=\"Cultural activities of the South Central Cultural Zone\">{{cite web|url=http://sczccnagpur.nic.in/majorprograms.htm|title=Major Programs during the year |publisher=The South Central Cultural Zone|accessdate=1 June 2006}}</ref> Newspapers are published from Nagpur in Marathi, English and Hindi. In addition, the [[Government of Maharashtra]] organises a week-long Kalidas Festival, a series of music and dance performances, by national level artists.<ref name=\"Kalidas festival in Nagpur\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maharashtratourism.net/festivals/kalidas-festival.html|title=The Kalidas Festival|publisher=Maharashtra Tourism Development Corporation}}</ref> [[Nagpur Municipal Corporation]] in partnership with [[Maharashtra Tourism Development Corporation]] organises Nagpur Mohotsav at Yeshwant Stadium, in which many distinguish artists participate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Cultural-feast-for-citizens-in-Nagpur-Mahotsav/articleshow/51146608.cms|title=Cultural feast for citizens in Nagpur Mahotsav |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>  The Nagpur Municipal Corporation also organises the Orange City International Film Festival (OCIFF) annually, in association with Saptak, Pune Film Foundation, Vidarbha Sahitya Sangh, and [[Rashtrasant Tukadoji Maharaj Nagpur University]] (RTMNU).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehitavada.com/Encyc/2020/2/2/4th-Orange-City-International-Film-Fest-from-6th.html|title=4th Orange City International Film Fest from 6th|website=www.thehitavada.com|language=en|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Nagpur Central Museum]] (est. 1863) maintains collections are mainly for Vidarbha region.\nThree brothers Ghulam Ali ([[Kotwal]]), Mohammad Saaduddin ([[Subedar]]) and Mohammad Saladuddin (Minister and [[Kotwal]]) from [[Jhajjar]] are remembered as great scholars of Urdu and Persian during the reign of Maharaja Senasaheb Subha Chhatrapati Raghuji Bapusaheb Bhonsle III. They founded 'Jhajjar Bagh' at Hansapuri (Now Mominpura). In this location, they built their residence 'Aina-e Mahal', a well and a Masjid (now Masjid Ahle Hadith). 'Jhajjar Bagh' also known as 'Subedar ka Bada' was located where nowadays Mohammad Ali Road at Mominpura, Jamia Masjid, Mohammad Ali Sarai and Furqania Madrasa are located.<ref>Nagpur ka Muslim Muashra (Gondwana aur Bhonsle Aihad [1700\u20131845]); Vol 2 by Dr. M. Sharfuddin Sahil, Salman Fine Arts, Nagpur, 1996</ref>\n\nThe state government has approved a new [[safari park]] of international standards besides [[Gorewada Lake]]. In 2013 NMC erected the gigantic [[Namantar Shahid Smarak]] in memory of [[Namantar Andolan]] martyrs.<ref name=Namantar>{{cite news|title=NMC, other prominent leaders salute Bhim Sainiks who laid down their lives for 'Namantar' Movement|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/nmc-other-prominent-leaders-salute-bhim-sainiks-who-laid-down-their-lives-for-namantar-movement/|accessdate=27 July 2013|newspaper=Nagpur Today|date=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Orange City LGBT Pride March|Orange City LGBTQ Pride March]] is also held annually in Nagpur, along with the [[Nagpur LGBT Queer Carnival]] during the pride month<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/nagpur/nagpur-youngsters-celebrate-rainbow-pride-and-diversity/articleshow/64808513.cms|title=Nagpur youngsters celebrate rainbow pride and diversity |website=The Times of India |access-date=2 May 2019 |author= Vinita Chaturvedi|date=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Religious places and festivals ===\n[[File:Diksha Bhumi.jpg|thumb|Deeksha Bhoomi]]\n[[Deekshabhoomi]], the largest hollow [[stupa]] or the largest dome shaped monument and an important place of the [[Dalit Buddhist movement|Buddhist movement]] is,  located in Nagpur.<ref name=\"Deekshabhoomi largest hollow stupa\">{{cite web| url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020317/spectrum/main5.htm|title=Celebrating a unique city|work=The Tribune |location=India|accessdate=1 June 2006}}</ref> Every year on the day of [[Vijayadashami]], i.e. Dussehra, followers of Dr. [[B. R. Ambedkar|Babasaheb Ambedkar]] visit Deekshabhoomi to mark the conversion ceremony of Ambedkar and his followers in Nagpur into [[Buddhism]] that took place on 14 October 1956.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sangharakshita.org/_books/Ambedkar_and_Buddhism.pdf |title=Ambedkar.vp |website=Sangharakshita.org |date= |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref> It has been given 'A' grade tourist place status by Maharashtra Government in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/maha-govt-approves-grade-a-status-to-deekshabhoomi-at-nagpur-116030700854_1.html|title=Maha govt approves grade 'A' status to Deekshabhoomi at Nagpur|first=Press Trust of|last=India|date=7 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016|via=Business Standard|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref> 14 April, which is the birthdate of Dr. Ambedkar, is celebrated as [[Ambedkar Jayanti]].\n\n[[Jainism]] has a good presence in Nagpur. There are nearly 30 Jain temples. The old ones are Sengan Jain temple Ladpura, Parwarpura Jain temple, Kirana oli Jain temple, and Juna oli Jain temple. In west Nagpur Shri 1008 Shantinath Digamber Bhagwan temple is situated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jaintemple.in/temples/india/nagpur|title=Digamber Jain Temples in Nagpur - Nagpur Digamber Jain Temples -Digamber Jain Mandir in Nagpur|author=|date=|website=www.jaintemple.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Gonesh..jpg|left|thumb|Shri Ganesh]]\n[[File:ShriGanpatiBappa.jpg|thumb]]\nThe most famous temple in Nagpur is [[Tekdi Ganesh Mandir]], and is said to be one of the [[Swayambhu]] (\"self-manifested\") temples in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpuronline.co.in/tekdi-ganpati.php|title=Tekdi Ganpati Temple of Lord Ganesha|first=Nagpur Hotels \u2013 Cheap Hotels in Nagpur|last=India|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Sri Poddareshwar Ram Mandir and Shri Mahalaxmi Devi temple of Koradi are important Hindu temples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/koradi-navratri-yatra-begins-sea-of-devotees-throng-on-first-day-for-darshan-of-jagdamba/10052200|title=Nagpur wakes up to greet Divine Koradi Devi|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nReligious events are observed in the city throughout the year. [[Ram Navami]] is celebrated in Nagpur with ''shobha yatra'' with a procession of floats depicting events from the [[Ramayana]].<ref name=\"Ram Mandir shobhayatra\">{{cite web|url=http://www.poddareshwarrammandir.com/shobha.htm |title=About Shobha Yatra |publisher=Sri Poddareshwar Ram Mandir Website}}</ref> Processions are also held on important festivals of other religions such as Dhamma Chakra Pravartan Din, Vijayadashami, [[Eid-e-Milad|Eid E Milad]], [[Guru Nanak Jayanti]], [[Mahavir Jayanti]], [[Durga puja]], [[Ganesh Chaturthi]] and [[Moharram]]. Like the rest of India, Nagpurkars celebrate major Hindu festivals like [[Diwali]], [[Holi]] and [[Navrati|Dussera]] with enthusiasm. Celebrations lasting for several days are held on [[Ganesh Chaturthi]] and [[Durga]] [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]] festivals in virtually every small locality in the city.\n\n[[File:Tajdin.jpg|thumb|Dargah Baba Tajuddin]]\nThe city also contains a sizeable Muslim population, and famous places of worship for Muslims include the Jama Masjid-Mominpura and Bohri Jamatkhana-Itwari. The most famous shrine ''(dargah)'' of [[Tajuddin Muhammad Badruddin]] is at Tajabad. Annual Urs is celebrated in great enthusiasm and unity on 26th of [[Muharram]]. Nagpur Is also called as Tajpur as the holy shirine of Sufi Saint Baba Tajuddin.\n\nThe St. Francis De Sales Cathedral is located in Sadar as well as the All Saints Cathedral church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mh-31.com/nagpur/nagpur-places/religious-places/466-cathedral-nagpur|title=All Saints' Cathedral, VCA, Nagpur|first=Malvika|last=Sohaney|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> There are many south Indian temples in Nagpur like Sarveshwara Devalayam, where all south Indian festivals are celebrated like Sitarama Kalyanam, Radha Kalyanam Dhanurmasa celebration with Andal Kalyanam, Balaji temple in seminary hills where every year Bramhotsavam to Lord Balaji and Lord Kartikeya is celebrated here. There are 2 Ayyapa temples, one at Ayyapa Nagar and the other at Harihara Nagar, Raghvendraswami Mutt, Murugananda Swami Temple at Mohan Nagar, Nimishamba Devi temple Subramanyiam devastanam at Sitabuldi and many more such south Indian temples are here in Nagpur as there is quite a good populations of south Indians in Nagpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mh-31.com/nagpur/nagpur-places/religious-places/454-sarveshwar-devalayam-nagpur|title=Sarveshwar Devalayam|first=Malvika|last=Sohaney|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seminary Hill.jpg|thumb|Seminary Hill of Nagpur]]\n\nMarbat Festival is a unique festival for Nagpur and is organised every year a day after the bullock festival of 'Pola'. The tradition of taking out the Marbat processions of 'kali' (black) and 'pivli' (yellow) Marbats (idols), started in 1880 in the eastern part of the city. A number of 'badgyas' (mascots), representing contemporary symbols of evil, comprise another feature of the annual processions. This festival dates back to the 19th century when the Bhonsla dynasty ruled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2007sep11/nagpur_keeps_alive_its_unique_marbat_tradition.html#.VoSVkvl97IU|title=Nagpur keeps alive its unique 'Marbat' tradition |website=TwoCircles.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Marbat-badgya-organizers-worried-over-potholes/articleshow/15498200.cms|title=Marbat, badgya organizers worried over potholes |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere is a [[Parsi]] [[Zoroastrian]] Agiary (Dar-e-Meher) in Nagpur, where the Parsi New Year is celebrated by the Parsi community in Nagpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bombayparsipunchayet.com/file/040610314221_celebrations.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=31 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043253/http://bombayparsipunchayet.com/file/040610314221_celebrations.pdf |archivedate= 4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Arts and crafts===\nThe tradition of painting in Nagpur was patronised by the royal house of the Bhonsales as well as common people. Illustrated manuscripts, including of the Bhagavat, Jnaaneshwari, Shakuntala, and Geeta, and the folk patachitras related to some festivals are available besides murals. The community of artists was called chitaris (painters), and this community has today turned to sculpt.\n\nTextile was once an important industry in Nagpur. Good quality cotton was produced in abundant quantities thanks to a suitable soil and climate. With the introduction of the railways, cotton sales and goods transport flourished. Besides cotton textiles, silk and wool weaving was also practised in the district. Silk sarees and pagota, patka, dhoti, and borders were woven with the silk thread.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maharashtratourism.gov.in/destination/nagpur-city |title=Archived copy |accessdate=10 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203123857/http://www.maharashtratourism.gov.in/destination/nagpur-city |archivedate= 3 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cuisine ===\n{{See also|Haldiram's}}\nThe [[Vidharbha]] region has its own distinctive cuisine known as the Varhadi cuisine or [[Saoji]] cuisine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://food.manoramaonline.com/food/around-the-world/2018/08/06/nagpur-saoji-secret-recipe.html |title=Nagpur's 'saoji' recipe - a secret revealed|author=|date=|website=OnManorama|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Saoji or Savji cuisine was the main cuisine of the Savji community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2018/aug/18/saoji-curries-vidarbhas-spiciest-cuisine-1859153.html|title=Saoji Curries: Vidarbha's spiciest cuisine|author=|date=|website=The New Indian Express|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> This traditional food is famous for its spicy taste.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asianage.com/life/food/110818/relish-the-real-taste-of-vidarbha.html|title=Relish the real taste of Vidarbha |first=Kasturi |last=Gadge|date=11 August 2018|website=The Asian Age|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> The special spices used in the gravy include black pepper, dry coriander, bay leaves, grey cardamom, [[cinnamon]], [[cloves]], and ample use of [[poppy seed]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/sunday-chronicle/epicuriosity/130817/on-a-spice-trail.html|title=On a spice trail|first=Gaurav|last=Gidwani|date=13 August 2017 |website=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Non-vegetarian food especially chicken and [[mutton]] are commonly eaten in Saoji establishments in Nagpur. There are numerous ''Savji bhojanalays''<ref>{{cite web |title=Saoji food in Nagpur |url=http://nagpur.joiye.com/restaurants/saoji/ |work=Joiye |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830171227/http://nagpur.joiye.com/restaurants/saoji |archivedate=30 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Restaurants in Nagpur |url=http://www.nagpuronline.co.in/dining.php |work=Nagpuronline |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213150713/http://www.nagpuronline.co.in/dining.php |archive-date=13 February 2015}}</ref> in Nagpur which are so popular in Maharashtra that the renowned Indian chef [[Sanjeev Kapoor]] once featured Savji mutton on one of his TV shows and the recipe is listed on his website.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saoji Mutton |url=http://sanjeevkapoor.com/saoji-mutton.aspx |work=Sanjeev Kapoor |url-status= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101230851/http://sanjeevkapoor.com/saoji-mutton.aspx |archive-date=1 January 2014}}</ref> Nagpur is also famous for its oranges, which have some typical qualities have recently begun to attract international attention. Numerous beverages are made out of the oranges.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://food52.com/recipes/15643-nagpur-s-famous-orange-burfi |title=Nagpur's Famous Orange Burfi |website=Food52 |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Santra Barfi is also a famous dish, arising from [[Orange (fruit)|orange]] which is produced locally in Nagpur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/sunday-herald/sweet-taste-of-india-723525.html|title=Sweet taste of India|author=|date=17 March 2019|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Mominpura is a majority [[Muslim]] area of the city and it is famous for its [[Mughlai cuisine|Mughal]] dishes and [[Biryani]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Mouthwatering-Mominpura/articleshow/50337029.cms |title=Mouthwatering Mominpura |first1=Barkha |last1=Mathur |date=27 December 2015 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.holidify.com/pages/street-food-in-nagpur-355.html |title=11 Must-try Street Food Of Nagpur |author=Divyanshu Abhineet |date=|website=Holidify |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> The city is also famous for rare black chickens called [[Kadaknath|''Kadaknath Chicken'']] which are cooked in varhadi style.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai-news/nagpur-a-land-of-rare-black-chickens-and-an-unusual-love-of-besan/story-cbCEup8SewbLbNMXyLN6FL.html |title=Nagpur: A land of rare black chickens and an unusual love of besan |first=Kunal |last=Vijayakar |date=14 December 2018|website=Hindustan Times |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nNagpur is also famous for ''tarri poha'', a variety of [[flattened rice]], and has many food joints; each having their own way of preparing and serving it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/food/food-reviews/The-most-popular-pohawalas-of-Nagpur/articleshow/28510414.cms |title=The most popular pohawalas of Nagpur |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhaskar.com/news/MH-PUN-nagpur-pohe-tarri-vendor-rupam-sakhre-at-kasturchand-park-4866725-PHO.html|title=\u0938\u0921\u093c\u0915 \u0915\u093f\u0928\u093e\u0930\u0947 \u0932\u0917\u093e\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u092a\u094b\u0939\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0926\u0941\u0915\u093e\u0928, \u0915\u092e\u093e\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u0932\u093e\u0916\u094b\u0902, \u0939\u0930 \u0938\u093e\u0932 \u091c\u093e\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u0935\u0930\u094d\u0932\u094d\u0921 \u091f\u0942\u0930|date=9 January 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Samosa|''Samosas'']] are also famous in Nagpur and is available at many restaurants and food spots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/food/food-reviews/The-most-popular-samosawalas-and-pakodewalas-of-Nagpur/articleshow/28519136.cms |title=The most popular samosawalas and pakodewalas of Nagpur |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Another famous food is ''Patodi and [[Kadhi]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/No-more-patodi-kadhi-at-Tehsil-office/articleshow/8256071.cms|title=No more patodi & kadhi at Tehsil office |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Schematic Tourist Map- Nagpur.png|thumb|upright=2|Schematic Tourist Map of Nagpur city]]\n\n=== Tiger reserves ===\nNagpur is surrounded by many tiger reserves and acts as a gateway, hence called Tiger capital of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reacho.in/nagpur/local/nagpur-tiger-capital-of-india|title=Here's Why We Call Nagpur- The Tiger Capital Of India!|first=Shruti|last=Mendulkar|date=29 July 2017|website=Reacho|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Tiger reserves such as [[Pench Tiger Reserve]] is situated around 100&nbsp;km from the city and can be reached through NH44 in Nagpur [[Jabalpur]] road. [[Tadoba National Park]] is situated south of the city and is around 141&nbsp;km from the city. [[Umred Karhandla Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Bor Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Navegaon National Park]], [[Melghat|Melghat Tiger Reserve]] and [[Kanha Tiger Reserve]] are the other tiger reserves which are located at a radius of 200&nbsp;km from the city. The city has its own reserved forest area at Seminary Hills and [[Gorewada Zoo|Gorewada]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/No-boundary-wall-to-protect-Seminary-Hills-reserve-forest-in-Nagpur/articleshow/47871779.cms|title=No boundary wall to protect Seminary Hills |first1=Times News Network|last1=June 2015|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>http://www.mahaforest.nic.in/managementpdf/1442219594Nagpur%20Vol%20I.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/over-3000-year-old-dagger-bangles-found-in-gorewada/articleshow/67315259.cms |title=Over 3,000-year-old dagger, bangles found in Gorewada |first1=Vijay |last1=Pinjarkar |date=31 December 2018 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/archaeology-theme-park-to-come-up-in-gorewada/articleshow/67745591.cms |title=Archaeology theme park to come up in Gorewada |first1=Vijay |last1=Pinjarkar |date=30 January 2019 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Zoos, Gardens and Lakes ===\n[[Maharajbagh zoo]] is an existing zoo which is located in the heart of the city near [[Sitabuldi]] and consists of a variety of animals. The zoo is going through fund crunches and does not have a proper plan for which the [[Central Zoo Authority]] had derecognised the zoo on November 2018. Its recognition has since been extended under the directions from [[Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Change|MoEFCC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/govt-apathy-pushing-125-yr-old-maharajbagh-zoo-towards-death/articleshow/65677084.cms|title=Govt apathy pushing 125-yr-old Maharajbagh zoo towards death &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/recognize-maharajbagh-zoo-cza-told/articleshow/68382245.cms|title=Recognize Maharajbagh Zoo, CZA told |first1=Vijay |last1=Pinjarkar |date=13 March 2019 |website=The Times of India |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loksatta.com/nagpur-news/maharaj-bagh-zoo-plan-approved-by-central-zoo-authority-1856558/|title=\u092e\u0939\u093e\u0930\u093e\u091c\u092c\u093e\u0917 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0923\u093f\u0938\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0939\u093e\u0932\u092f\u093e\u0932\u093e \u091c\u0940\u0935\u0926\u093e\u0928|author=|date=13 March 2019 |website=loksatta.com|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> [[Gorewada Zoo]] is an upcoming international [[zoo]] project which is being setup beside [[Gorewada Lake]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/bjp-sena-will-win-all-seats-in-vid-mungantiwar/articleshow/68661500.cms|title=BJP-Sena will win all seats in Vid: Mungantiwar |first1=Ashish |last1=Roy |first2=Vijay |last2=Pinjarkar |date=1 April 2019 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> It is being jointly developed by Forest Development Corporation of Maharashtra and [[Essel Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/gorewada-zoo-to-be-developed-by-essel-group-jv/articleshow/63703249.cms|title=Gorewada zoo to be developed by Essel Group JV &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nThe city consist of various natural and man made lakes. [[Khindsi Lake]], [[Ambazari Lake]] and [[Gorewada Lake]] are the natural lakes of the city while [[Futala Lake]], [[Shukrawari Lake]], Sakkardara Lake, Zilpi Lake and Sonegaon lake are the man made lakes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nagpur.gov.in/tourist-place/lake-garden-sakkardara/|title=Lake garden Sakkardara: - District Nagpur,Government of Maharashtra |author=|date= |website=nagpur.gov.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>https://indiabiodiversity.org/biodiv/content/documents/document-584195f8-18f1-4374-a564-3004796caa25/167.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/The-curse-of-Sonegaon-lake/articleshow/16360263.cms|title=The curse of Sonegaon lake |first1=Barkha |last1=Mathur |date=12 September 2012 |website=The Times of India |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> The city also has various gardens which consist of [[Ambazari Lake|Ambazari Garden]], Telankhedi Garden,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehitavada.com/Encyc/2019/3/28/Of-debris-that-hurts.html |title=Of debris that hurts deep, dirty|author=|date=|website=www.thehitavada.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/residents-oppose-commercialization-of-telangkhedi-garden/06301444,%20https://www.nagpurtoday.in/residents-oppose-commercialization-of-telangkhedi-garden/06301444|title=Residents oppose commercialization of Telangkhedi garden |first=Nagpur |last=News |date= |website=www.nagpurtoday.in |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Satpuda Botanical Garden,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nagpur.gov.in/tourist-place/satpuda-botanical-garden/|title=Satpuda Botanical Garden - District Nagpur,Government of Maharashtra|author=|date=|website=nagpur.gov.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Japanese Garden<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nagpurinfo.in/nagpursafaris/amusement-parks/japanesegarden|title=Japanese Garden|website=www.nagpurinfo.in|accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref> and Children's Traffic Park.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mysuru/childrens-traffic-park-reopens-to-public/articleshow/65014812.cms|title=Children's Traffic Park reopens to public |date=17 July 2018 |website=The Times of India |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Religious places ===\nNagpur boosts for many religious structures which are important for respective religious beliefs. [[Deekshabhoomi]] and [[Dragon Palace ]] are important religious places for [[Buddhists]] across [[India]] and the [[world]]. [[Deekshabhoomi]] is the place where [[Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar]] with millions of his followers embraced [[Buddhism]] in the year 1956.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/kumbhare-wants-gadkari-as-pm/articleshow/68553245.cms|title=Sulekha Kumbhare wants Gadkari as PM &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> [[Dragon Palace Temple]] is situated at [[Kamptee]] which is around 15&nbsp;km from the city. It also has a state of the art [[Vipassana]] centre which was inaugurated by [[President of India]] [[Ram Nath Kovind]] on 22 September 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/state-of-the-art-vipassana-centre-to-put-city-on-radar-of-intl-visitors/articleshow/60798723.cms|title=State-of-the-art Vipassana Centre to put city on radar of international visitors &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Other prominent religious structures include [[Ramtek|Ramtek Fort Temple]] at [[Ramtek]] which is a temple built inside a fort and is 55&nbsp; km away from Nagpur, Adasa Ganpati Temple located near [[Savner]] is one of the eight Ashta Vinayaks in [[Vidarbha]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/citizen-reporter/stories/adasa-temple/crshow/59855486.cms|title=Adasa temple |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> [[Tajuddin Muhammad Badruddin|Baba Tajjuddin Dargah]], Shri Shantinath Digambar Jain Mandir at [[Ramtek]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jain24.com/jain-temples/maharashtra/maharashtra-teerth-places/ramtek-maharashtra/|title=Ramtek, Maharashtra|first=Neeraj|last=Jain|date=28 April 2015|website=jain24.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Shree Ganesh Mandir Tekdi, located near [[Nagpur Railway Station]] and one of the [[Swayambhu]] temple of [[Lord Ganesha]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/the-history-of-ganesh-mandir-tekdi-in-one-minute/09062055,%20https://www.nagpurtoday.in/the-history-of-ganesh-mandir-tekdi-in-one-minute/09062055|title=The History Of Ganesh Mandir Tekdi In One Minute|first=Nagpur|last=News|date=|website=www.nagpurtoday.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Sai Baba Mandir at Wardha road,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/sai-mandir-to-have-all-gold-platform-for-idol/articleshow/58634764.cms|title=Sai Mandir in Nagpur to have all-gold platform for idol |first1=Barkha |last1=Mathur |date=12 May 2017 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Telankhedi Hanuman Temple,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/telangkhedi-temple-chhota-tajbagh-to-be-beautified/articleshow/64196582.cms|title=Telangkhedi temple, Chhota Tajbagh to be beautified |first1=Ashish |last1=Roy |date=17 May 2018 |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> [[List of Swaminarayan temples|Swaminarayan Temple]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baps.org/Global-Network/India/Nagpur.aspx|title=BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir, Nagpur |author=|date=|website=BAPS|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Koradi Temple, located at Koradi,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reacho.in/nagpur/local/koradi-temple-explore-nagpur|title=Explore Nagpur: The Lesser Known History Of Koradi Temple, City's Popular Shrine!|first=Manali|last=Kulkarni|date=11 October 2018|website=Reacho|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Shri Poddareshwar Ram Temple,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reacho.in/nagpur/local/explore-nagpur-you-need-sri-poddareshwar-ram-mandir|title=Explore Nagpur: All That You Need To Know About Sri Poddareshwar Ram Mandir|first=Mandar|last=Pandhare|date=4 April 2017 |website=Reacho|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Balaji Temple,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/balaji-temple-abuzz-with-sri-skanda-shashti-events-rituals/articleshow/66560861.cms |title=Balaji temple abuzz with Sri Skanda Shashti events, rituals |first1=Barkha |last1=Mathur |date=10 November 2018|website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> All Saints Cathedral<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allsaintscathedralnagpur.in/#/ |title=All Saints' Cathedral Nagpur |author=|date=|website=www.allsaintscathedralnagpur.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> and Gurudwara Guru Nanak Darbar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/sikh-brethren-of-city-celebrate-547th-gurunanak-jayanti-with-devotional-fervour/11251958,%20https://www.nagpurtoday.in/sikh-brethren-of-city-celebrate-547th-gurunanak-jayanti-with-devotional-fervour/11251958|title=Sikh brethren of city celebrate 547th GuruNanak Jayanti with devotional fervour |first=Nagpur|last=News|date=|website=www.nagpurtoday.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\n[[File:Nagpur Central Museum, Painting Gallery, Oct 2019.jpg|thumb|Nagpur Central Museum]]\nThe city also has some museums which are [[Nagpur Central Museum]] and Narrow Gauge Rail Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtdc.co.in/tourist/narrow-gauge-rail-museum/|title=Narrow Gauge Rail Museum|author=|date=|website=Maharastra Bhraman|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> [[Raman Science Centre]] is a premium Science Centre of Central India, that has of late become a must see feature on the city's tourist landscape with many scientific experimental edutainment installations which also has a planetarium and a unique facility called the [[Science on a Sphere]] inside. Amusement parks such as Fun N Food Village,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.funnfood.com/nagpur/water-park.php|title=Water Park - Fun N Food Village Nagpur|author=|date=|website=www.funnfood.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> High Land Park,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.highlandparknagpur.com/highlp/index.html|title=High Land Park Nagpur|website=www.highlandparknagpur.com}}</ref> Fun Planet<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fun-planet-water-park.business.site/|title=Fun Planet - Best Water Park In Nagpur|author=|date=|website=fun-planet-water-park.business.site|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> and Dwarka River Farms and Amusement Park<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dwarkapark.com/|title=DwarkaPark \u2013 Welcome To Dwarka Park|author=|date=|website=dwarkapark.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> are located in the city.\n\n==Sports==\n{{See also|Vidarbha cricket team}}\n{{wide image|Panoramic view of VCA stadium,nagpur.jpg|1200px|<center>Panoramic view of VCA stadium, Nagpur</center>}}\n[[File:NPLNagpur.jpg|right|thumb|A view at NPL starting ceremony]]\nNagpur is a big center for cricket in Vidarbha owing to the presence of the [[Vidarbha Cricket Association]]. [[Vidarbha Cricket Association]] (VCA) is the governing body of [[cricket]] activities in the [[Vidarbha]] region in Maharashtra. It is affiliated to the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]]. Nagpur is one of the few Indian cities that has more than one international cricket stadium,<ref name=\"Nagpur's new stadium ready to debut\">{{Cite news|url=http://search.rediff.com/cricket/2008/nov/04nagpur.htm|title=Nagpur's new stadium ready to debut|date=4 November 2008|publisher=[[Rediff]]|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Cricket matches on VCA\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.rleague.com/odi/venues/66.html|title=One day Internationals, Vidarbha Cricket Ground|publisher=National Rugby League of Australia|accessdate=22 June 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060503155746/http://stats.rleague.com/odi/venues/66.html<!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=3 May 2006}}</ref> the older one being the [[Vidarbha Cricket Association Ground]] situated in Civil Lines, and the new one, the [[Vidarbha Cricket Association Stadium]], inaugurated in 2008 is situated in Jamtha, Wardha Road on the outskirts of the city.<ref name=\"VCA ground in Nagpur\">{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/india/content/ground/58344.html| title=Vidarbha Cricket Association Ground in Nagpur|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=21 June 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[Vidarbha Cricket Association Stadium]] has been built on Wardha road with a [[seating capacity]] of 45,000 people at a cost of {{INRConvert|75|c}}. It is one of the fifteen test cricket venues in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/75757/board-of-control-for-cricket-in-india-bcci-adds-six-new-test-venues|title=BCCI adds six additional Test venues|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Vidarbha Cricket Association Ground]] has been the venue for the [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987 Reliance World Cup]] and [[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996 Wills World Cup]]. [[Vidarbha Cricket Association Stadium]] has been the venue for the [[2011 Cricket World Cup]] and [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2015/media-releases/91068/icc-world-twenty20-india-2016-schedule-announced|title=ICC World T20 schedule announced (India, 2016)|date=11 December 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> The stadium also hosts certain matches of the [[Indian Premier League]] and had been the home city for the now defunct [[Deccan Chargers]] in the [[2010 Indian Premier League|2010 season]] and was also the home city for [[Kings XI Punjab]] along with [[Mohali]] in the [[2016 Indian Premier League|2016 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/ipl/news/Kings-XI-Punjab-may-play-3-IPL-matches-in-Nagpur/articleshow/51227495.cms |title=King's XI Punjab may play 3 IPL matches in Nagpur |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/cricketnext/news/ipl-gives-deccans-home-games-to-nagpur-mumbai-563921.html|title=IPL gives Deccan's home games to Nagpur, Mumbai|date=15 February 2010|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Vidarbha Cricket Association]] also has a cricket academy at the main centre in [[Vidarbha Cricket Association Ground]] and three more centres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vca.co.in/cricket-academy/|title=Cricket Academy \u2013 Vidarbha Cricket Association|author=|date=|website=vca.co.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> It also has its own cricket teams which play in various formats as mandated by [[Board of Control for Cricket in India|BCCI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vca.co.in/teams/|title=VCA Teams \u2013 Vidarbha Cricket Association|author=|date=|website=vca.co.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> The [[Vidarbha cricket team]] had won the [[Ranji Trophy]] and [[Irani Cup]] consecutively in [[2017\u201318 Ranji Trophy|2017-18]] and [[2018\u201319 Ranji Trophy|2018-19]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/india-domestic/ranji-trophy/vca-announces-rs-3-crore-prize-money-for-victorious-ranji-team/articleshow/67886146.cms|title=VCA announces Rs 3 crore prize money for victorious Ranji team |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nVidarbha Hockey Association is a body governing [[hockey]] in the [[Vidarbha|Vidarbha Region]] and is affiliated to [[Hockey India]] as an associate member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/hockey/news/209005-hockey-india-inducts-vidarbha-hockey-association-in-its-fold|title=Hockey India inducts Vidarbha Hockey Association in its fold \u2013 NDTV Sports|last=NDTVSports.com|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> [[Vidarbha Hockey Association Stadium]] is the hockey ground owned and managed by Vidarbha Hockey Association.\n\n[[Western India Football Association]] is the state governing body for [[association football|football]] in Maharashtra, and is affiliated with the [[All India Football Federation]], the national sports governing body. The Nagpur District Football Association is a district level football body and conducts various matches among the schools and clubs. It has its own league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/nagpur-district-football-association-ndfa-league-to-kick-off-in-june/05061025|title=Nagpur District Football Association (NDFA) league to kick off in June|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Lokmat NPL (Nagpur Premier League), another football tournament, was held at Nagpur annually since 2010 till 2014 by [[Lokmat]] Group in Yeshwant Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/sports/football/lokmat-nagpur-premier-league-soccer-starts-on-sunday_777409.html|title=Lokmat Nagpur Premier League soccer starts on sunday|date=4 January 2014|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>   Nagpur FC and YMFC are renowned football clubs in the city. Other clubs include, Rabbani Club, Rahul Club, City Police, South East Central Railway, Qidwai Club, SRPF, New Globe and City Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/YMFC-to-hold-All-India-football-tournament-from-Sunday/articleshow/50781551.cms|title=YMFC to hold All India football tournament from Sunday |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Nagpur FC has its own Football Academy in Dhanwate National College, Congress Nagar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Eyeing-2017-U-17-WC-Nagpur-FC-to-start-football-academy/articleshow/35618939.cms|title=Eyeing 2017 U-17 WC Nagpur FC to start football academy |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Slum Soccer is a social initiative started by [[Vijay Barse]] for young runaways and former drug addicts to rehabilitate them through football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/videos/india/rh-vijay-448505.html|title=Real Hero Vijay's 'slum soccer' transforms lives|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Badminton]] tournaments in the city are organised by Nagpur District Badminton Association (NDBA) which is affiliated to Maharashtra Badminton Association which in turn is a member of [[Badminton Association of India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/badminton/double-crown-for-hriday-ameya-in-nagpur-district-badminton-tournament/articleshow/70439696.cms|title=Double crown for Hriday, Ameya in Nagpur District Badminton tournament - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/badminton/ndba-declares-junior-district-squad-for-maharashtra-badminton-championship/articleshow/65655162.cms|title=NDBA declares junior district squad for Maharashtra Badminton Championship - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Nagpur District Table Tennis Association organises [[table tennis]] [[tournaments]] at district level and is affiliated to Maharashtra Table Tennis Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/others/nagpur-to-host-state-ranking-table-tennis-tournament-from-july-21/articleshow/59672114.cms|title=Nagpur to host State Ranking Table Tennis tournament from July 21 - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/more-sports/others/mallikas-european-style-tt-helps-her-seal-second-state-crown/articleshow/59732669.cms|title=Mallika's European style TT helps her seal second state crown - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The city also has a divisional sports complex which consist of Indoor stadium and other [[gymnastic]] facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/hc-form-panel-with-sportspersons-to-manage-stadium/articleshow/66155141.cms|title=HC: Form panel with sportspersons to manage stadium &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/explain-holding-marriages-in-divn-sports-complex-hc/articleshow/65329139.cms|title=Explain holding marriages in divn sports complex: HC &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nThe city also has various running events, for general public, organised by various institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://0milemarathon.com|title=Zero Mile Nagpur Marathon |website=Zero Mile Nagpur Marathon |access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mahamarathon.com/nagpur/|title=Nagpur Maha Marathon|access-date=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\n''[[The Hitavada]]'' is the largest selling broadsheet [[English language|English]] daily newspaper of Central India. It was founded in 1911 by freedom fighter [[Gopal Krishna Gokhale]] in Nagpur. Other English dailies circulated in the city include ''[[The Times of India]]'', ''[[The Indian Express]]'', ''[[The Economic Times]]'' and ''Lokmat Times''. ''[[Lokmat]]'' is the largest circulated [[Marathi language|Marathi]] newspaper in Nagpur, and has its administrative office in the city. ''[[Tarun Bharat]]'', ''Deshonatti'', ''[[Maharashtra Times]]'', ''Punya Nagari'', ''Lokshahi Varta'', ''[[Sakal]]'', ''Divya Marathi'' and ''[[Loksatta]]'' are other Marathi dailies available. [[Hindi]] newspapers such as ''Yugdharma'', ''[[Nava Bharat]]'', ''[[Dainik Bhaskar]]'' and ''Lokmat Samachar'' are also circulated. Employment ''News'', which is published weekly, is also circulated in Hindi, English and Urdu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://employmentnews.gov.in/about_us.asp|title=Welcome to Employment News ::- Govt. Jobs, Jobs in India, Vacancy in Govt. Sector, Career in Govt. Sector|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[All India Radio]] is the oldest radio broadcaster in the city and has its office in the Civil Lines area. [[Vividh Bharati]], the entertainment radio station, and [[Gyan Vani]], the educational radio station, are the FM radio stations of [[All India Radio]] and are available in the frequency 100.6 FM & 107.8 FM respectively.<ref>http://allindiaradio.gov.in/Oppurtunities/Tenders/Documents/VIVIDH%20BHARATI%20FM%20Service.pdf</ref> Other private FM broadcasting channels with their frequencies include [[Radio City (Indian radio station)|Radio City]] at 91.1 FM, [[Red FM 93.5|Red FM]] at 93.5 FM, [[My FM]] at 94.3 FM, [[Radio Mirchi]] at 98.3 FM, [[Radio Mirchi|Mirchi Love FM]] at 91.9 FM and [[Big FM (Indian radio station)|Big FM]] at 92.7 FM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fmstations.bharatiyamobile.com/Indian-FM-Stations-Statewise.php?state=Maharashtra%20&location=Nagpur|title=FM Radio Stations in Nagpur, Maharashtra|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nTelevision broadcasting in Nagpur began on 15 August 1982 with the launch of [[Doordarshan]], the Government of India's public service broadcaster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddkmumbai.org/?page_id=283|title=About Us \u2013 Sahyadri|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> It transmits [[DD National]] and [[DD News]], which are free-to-air terrestrial television channels and one regional satellite channel called [[DD Sahyadri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddsahyadri.in/about-us-10|title=DD \u2013 Sahyadri about|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Private satellite channels started in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://download.nos.org/srsec335new/ch13.pdf |title=Gm13c |website=Download.nos.org |date= |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>{{rp|6}} [[Lord Buddha TV]] and [[Awaaz India TV]] are [[Free-to-air]] [[television]] which are based in the city and are available in various [[cable operators]] and [[Satellite television|DTH platforms]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Lord-Buddha-TVs-Slumdog-Millionaire-rise/articleshow/16897512.cms|title=Lord Buddha TV's Slumdog Millionaire rise |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://buddhistentrepreneurs.com/Bussiness/Nagpur/AWAAZ-INDIA-TV-CHANNEL/50|title=AWAAZ INDIA TV CHANNEL Nagpur-Media , Television|website=buddhistentrepreneurs.com|access-date=16 June 2018}}</ref> Satellite TV channels are accessible via [[Cable television|cable subscription]], [[Direct-broadcast satellite|direct-broadcast satellite services]] or [[IPTV|internet-based television]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html#top|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trai.gov.in/WriteReadData/BandCS/List_of_Permitted_TV_Channels_on_30-06-2015.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122170527/http://www.trai.gov.in/WriteReadData/BandCS/List_of_Permitted_TV_Channels_on_30-06-2015.pdf |archivedate=22 January 2016 }}</ref> Cable TV operators or multi system operators in the city include UCN cable network, GTPL, In cable, BCN and Diamond cable network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trai.gov.in/WriteReadData/BandCS/List-of-MSOs-with-Permanent_registration_on_14.08.2015.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=5 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302180837/http://www.trai.gov.in/WriteReadData/BandCS/List-of-MSOs-with-Permanent_registration_on_14.08.2015.pdf |archivedate= 2 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurorange.com/govt-yet-to-receive-a-single-cable-viewers-form/|title=Govt yet to receive a single cable viewer's form \u2013 Nagpur Orange|date=3 July 2013|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> All the [[List of DTH Operators in India|DTH operators in the country]] are available in the city viz. [[Airtel digital TV]], [[DD Free Dish]], [[Dish TV]], [[Sun Direct]], [[Reliance Digital TV]], [[D2h]], and [[Tata Sky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Which-DTH-service-provider-tops-with-most-channels-and-best-picture-quality/articleshow/9597942.cms|title=Which DTH service provider tops with most channels and best picture quality |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nBroadband Internet service is available in the city and is provided by various [[Internet service provider]]s. [[Wi-Fi]] is available in major [[educational institutions]] and certain areas in the city, including [[government institutions]] under [[Smart City]] plan by NSSCDCL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/nmc-doesnt-use-jios-and-own-free-internet-pays-lakhs-for-it/articleshow/68801834.cms|title=NMC doesn't use Jio's and own free Internet, pays lakhs for it &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Currently [[3G]] services in the city are provided by [[BSNL]], [[Airtel]], [[Vodafone Idea Limited]], and [[4G]] services in the city are provided by [[Airtel]], [[Jio]], [[Vodafone Idea Limited]] and [[BSNL]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.komparify.com/nagpur-1743-city|title=Komparify allows you to find the best packs and recharge them. Why Komplify? Komparify|last=Komparify.com|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Nagpur-cell-users-can-go-3G-by-July-end/articleshow/6052716.cms|title=Nagpur cell users can go 3G by July end |website=The Times of India|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airtel.in/about-bharti/media-centre/bharti-airtel-news/mobile/airtel-4g-comes-to-nagpur|title=Airtel 4G comes to Nagpur|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/idea-launches-world-class-high-speed-lte-services-in-maharashtra-and-goa/03161948|title=Idea launches world-class, high-speed LTE services in Maharashtra and Goa|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://telecomtalk.info/bsnl-customers-2gb-free-4g-sim/183867/|title=BSNL Customers to Get 2GB of Free Data on 4G SIM Upgrade - Telecom Talk|author=|date=|website=telecomtalk.info|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n{{Main|Transport in Nagpur}}\n[[File:Nagpur Railway Station Stitch.jpg|thumb|upright=2|Nagpur Junction Railway Station building]]\n\n===Rail===\nRailways started in Nagpur way back in 1867 when portion of Bombay-Bhusaval-Nagpur line was opened for traffic and train service from Nagpur to Calcutta was started in 1881.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cr.indianrailways.gov.in//view_section.jsp?id=0,6,1191,1196,1683 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091150/http://www.cr.indianrailways.gov.in//view_section.jsp?id=0%2C6%2C1191%2C1196%2C1683 |title=About Nagpur Division of CENTRAL RAILWAY |website=Central Railway |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=5 May 2019}}<br />{{cite web |title=Division at a Glance: (as on 01.03.2019) |website=Central Railway |url=https://cr.indianrailways.gov.in//view_section.jsp?id=0,6,1191,1196,1683 |access-date=5 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nagpurtoday.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nagpurtoday.in/90-years-of-nagpur-station-building/01142300|title=90 years of Nagpur station Building|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> Today, a total of 260 trains stop at Nagpur railway station. These include passenger, express, mail, [[Duronto]], [[Rajdhani Express|Rajdhani]], [[Garib Rath Express|Garib Rath]] trains. Of these 65 are daily trains and 26 terminate/originate from Nagpur. Almost 1.6 [[lakh]] passengers board/leave Nagpur Railway Station<ref>{{cite web |title=Here's what the free Wi-Fi commitment to Indian Railways probably costs Google |first=Nash |last=David |date=29 September 2015 |url=https://www.firstpost.com/tech/news-analysis/heres-what-the-free-wi-fi-commitment-to-indian-railways-probably-costs-google-3671957.html |website=Tech2 |access-date=5 May 2019}}</ref> [[Nagpur Junction railway station|Nagpur railway station]], one of the oldest and busiest Stations of India was inaugurated in its present from on 15 January 1925 by the then Governor Sir Frank.<ref name=\"nagpurtoday.in\"/> Apart from the [[Nagpur Junction railway station|Nagpur railway station]], [[Ajni railway station|Ajni Railway Station]] and [[Itwari railway station|Itwari Railway Station]] are the important stations of the city. Other railway stations in the city include Motibagh, Kalamna and Godhani. Nagpur-Ajni rail route which is just 3&nbsp;km long, is the shortest train run in [[Indian Railways]] primarily meant for crew to travel from Nagpur station to the workshop at Ajni.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/indian-railways-10-interesting-facts_789718.html |title=Indian Railways \u2013 10 Interesting Facts |date=25 July 2012 |website=Zee News |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe city is the divisional headquarters for the [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]] and [[South East Central Railway]] [[Indian Railways#Railway zones|Zone]] of [[Indian Railways]]. Nagpur is a city with two divisional headquarters, a rare distinction it shares with Lucknow, which has headquarters for two different divisions in [[Northern Railway Zone (India)|Northern Railway zone]] and [[North Eastern Railway (India)|North Eastern Railway zone]].\n\n===Nagpur Metro Rail===\nThe [[Nagpur Metro]] project was announced by the state government of Maharashtra with the expenses of [[Indian rupee|INR]] 4,400 Cr and 3,800 Cr for its first phase which consists of two corridors \u2013 North-South corridor and East-West corridor of 39.4&nbsp;km.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-22/nagpur/30545964_1_metro-rail-project-prithviraj-chavan-bullet-train \"Nagpur metro rail project report to be ready in 6 months: Prithviraj Chavan\"]. ''Times of India'', 22 December 2011</ref><ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-23/nagpur/30550709_1_metro-projects-metro-route-nagpur-metro \"Part of Nagpur metro may be along road\"]. ''Times of India'', 23 December 2011</ref>\n\nThe site inspection began in March 2012 with initiatives from [[Nagpur Improvement Trust]]. The project is executed by a SPV called [[Maharashtra Metro Rail Corporation Limited]] (erstwhile Nagpur Metro Rail Corporation Ltd.).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/cmrs-nagpur-metro-project-visit-now-on-april-9/04042059|title=CMRS Nagpur Metro Project visit now on April 9|website=www.nagpurtoday.in|language=en-US|access-date=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/personal-finance/cabinet-approves-phase-1pune-metro-project-917276.html|title=Cabinet approves phase-1 of Pune Metro project|author=|date=|website=Moneycontrol|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/nagpur-metro-site-inspection-begins/919348 \"Nagpur metro site inspection begins\"]. ''Indian Express'', 3 March 2012</ref> In July 2015, the project was approved by the [[government of Maharashtra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Nagpur-Pune-Metro-projects-get-central-nod/articleshow/30429113.cms|title=Nagpur, Pune Metro projects get central nod|work=The Times of India|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Metro-rail-bhoomipuja-on-March-1-or-2/articleshow/30537188.cms|title=Metro rail bhoomipuja on March 1 or 2|work=The Times of India|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] inaugurated operations on Nagpur Metro on 7 March 2019 via video conferencing along with Maharashtra Chief Minister [[Devendra Fadnavis]] and Union Cabinet Minister [[Nitin Gadkari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ANI/status/1103633939569262592|title=Delhi: Prime Minister Narendra Modi flags-off Nagpur Metro via video conferencing.pic.twitter.com/0n6ohgcok3|last=ANI|date=7 March 2019|website=@ANI|language=pt|access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latestly.com/india/news/nagpur-metro-flagged-off-by-pm-narendra-modi-to-be-open-for-public-from-march-8-681132.html|title=Nagpur Metro Flagged Off by PM Narendra Modi, To Be Open For Public From March 8|date=7 March 2019|website=Latestly|language=en|access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Nagpur Broad Gauge Metro Rail ===\nThe [[Nagpur Broad Gauge Metro]] is a commuter rail project planned Nagpur and extending up to adjacent districts of [[Wardha]] and [[Bhandara]]. The project is estimated to cost [[Indian rupee|INR]] 418 Cr and consists of four routes, each originating from Nagpur and terminating at [[Narkhed]], [[Ramtek]], [[Wardha]] and [[Bhandara]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urbantransportnews.com/nagpur-broad-gauge-metro-project-information-tenders-routes-updates/|title=Nagpur Broad Gauge Metro: Project information, tenders, routes & updates|website=Urban Transport News|language=en-US|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Road===\n[[File:MakeInIndia-NMPL-Scania-Ethanol.jpg|alt=|thumb|Green Bus in Nagpur]]\nNagpur is a major junction for roadways as India's two major [[Indian Highways|national highways]], Srinagar-Kanyakumari ([[National Highway 44 (India)|National Highway 44]]) and Mumbai-Kolkata ([[National Highway 53 (India)|NH 53(Ecconomic Corridor1(EC1)]]) pass through the city.<ref name=index04052006>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/story/3713.html |title=Nagpur stakes claim to lead boomtown pack |last=Deshpande |first=Vivek |work=The Indian Express |location=India |date=4 May 2006 |accessdate=22 June 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929125003/http://www.indianexpress.com/story/3713.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> [[National Highway 47 (India)|National Highway 47]] connects Nagpur to Bamanbore in Gujrat. Nagpur is at the junction of two [[Asian Highway Network|Asian Highways]] namely [[AH43]] [[Agra]] to [[Matara, Sri Lanka]] and [[AH46]] connecting [[Kharagpur, West Bengal|Kharagpur]], India to [[Dhule]], India. The new state highway, [[Mumbai\u2013Aurangabad\u2013Nagpur highway]], built on the national highway basis is also sanctioned by the state and central government. This highway significantly reduces the distance travelled by [[National Highway 6 (India)|NH 6]] and [[National Highway 3 (India)|NH 3]] between two cities. The new proposed [[Mumbai\u2013Nagpur Expressway]] between Nagpur and Mumbai will be 800&nbsp; km and projected to cost {{INRConvert|30000|c}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/maharashtra-plans-800km-mumbainagpur-expressway/article7490494.ece|title=Maharashtra plans 800-km Mumbai-Nagpur expressway|date=2 August 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> In 2009, [[NHAI]] announced the extension of the existing [[NH 204]] to Nagpur via [[Kolhapur]]-[[Sangli]]- [[Solapur]]-[[Tuljapur]]-[[Latur]]-[[Nanded]]-[[Yavatmal]]-[[Wardha]] and connecting it to the [[National Highway 7 (India)(old numbering)|NH-7]] at [[Butibori]] near Nagpur. The entire NH 204 highway has been included in the national highway mega projects for upgradation to 4-lane.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lokmat.com/kolhapur/nagpur-ratnagiri-highway-three-storied-shoot-out-land-acquisition-kolhapur/|title=\u092d\u0942\u0938\u0902\u092a\u093e\u0926\u0928\u093e\u091a\u093e \u0924\u093f\u0922\u093e \u0938\u0941\u091f\u0947\u0928\u093e \u0928\u093e\u0917\u092a\u0942\u0930-\u0930\u0924\u094d\u0928\u093e\u0917\u093f\u0930\u0940 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u092e\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0917 : \u0926\u0940\u0921 \u0935\u0930\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0924 \u0915\u094b\u0932\u094d\u0939\u093e\u092a\u0941\u0930\u093e\u0924 \u0917\u0941\u0902\u0920\u093e\u092d\u0930\u0939\u0940 \u091c\u092e\u093f\u0928\u0940\u091a\u093e \u0924\u093e\u092c\u093e \u0928\u093e\u0939\u0940|last=author/lokmat-news-network|date=13 October 2018|website=Lokmat|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> One more national highway [[National Highway 547 (India)|NH-547]] [[Savner]]-[[Chhindwara]]-[[Narsinghpur]] has connected with [[National Highway 47 (India)|NH 47]] at Savner near Nagpur providing another optional connectivity with the northern part of India.\n\nMaharashtra State road transport Corporation ([[MSRTC]]) runs cheaper transport service for intercity, interstate, and intrastate travel. It has two bus stations in Nagpur: Nagpur Bus Sthanak (CBS-1) at Ganeshpeth and MorBhawan (CBS-2) at Jhansi Rani Square, Sitabuldi. It operates 1600 daily services from CBS-1 to long and short distances within the state and to places in other surrounding states. It also operates 750 daily services from CBS-2 to short distances within [[Vidarbha]].\n\nThe [[Nagpur Municipal Corporation|civic body]] through its bus operators (three red and one green) plies 487 buses by which over 1.60 lakh people commute. The city bus operation is named as [[Nagpur Mahanagar Parivahan Limited|Aapli Bus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Now-commuters-can-track-NMC-buses-through-app/articleshow/55777364.cms|title=Now, commuters can track NMC buses through app &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The operators consist of [[diesel fuel|diesel]], [[ethanol]] and [[CNG]] run buses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/nagpur-nitin-gadkari-rolls-out-citys-first-cng-bus/articleshow/68232563.cms|title=Nitin gadkari: Nagpur: Nitin Gadkari rolls out city's first CNG bus &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>  A total of 5500 trips of 123 routes are covered by city buses. A common mobility card called MAHA-CARD has also been issued which will help people commute with buses and upcoming metro rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-24/nagpur/29468719_1_bus-operator-corporators-vansh-nimay-infratech |work=The Times of India |location=India | title=NMC refuses action against city bus operator |date=24 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://urbantransportnews.com/maha-cm-unveils-common-mobility-card-maha-card-in-nagpur/|title=Maha CM unveils common mobility card 'MAHA-CARD' in Nagpur|first=Urban Transport|last=News|date=28 February 2019}}</ref> A Green bus project featuring India's first [[ethanol]]-powered buses was established in August 2014.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/global-warming/Nagpur-gets-Indias-first-ethanol-run-bus/articleshow/40858005.cms |title=Nagpur gets India's first ethanol-run bus |website=The Times of India|date=24 August 2014 |accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Autorickshaws]] and private taxi operators under [[Ola Cabs]] and [[Uber]] also ply in city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/autowallahs-families-accuse-gadkari-of-giving-free-run-to-app-based-taxis/articleshow/68841124.cms|title=Autowallahs, families accuse Gadkari of giving free run to app-based taxis &#124; Nagpur News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n===Air transport===\n[[File:NagpurAirport.JPG|thumb|left|Nagpur [[Multi-modal International Cargo Hub and Airport at Nagpur|International Airport]] has the busiest air traffic control room in India.]]\n\n[[Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar International Airport]] {{airport codes|NAG|VANP}} is operated by [[MIHAN|Mihan India Private Limited (MIPL)]] and owned by [[Airports Authority of India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nagpurtoday.in/nagpur-airport-fully-taken-over-by-mihan-india/09021100,%20https://www.nagpurtoday.in/nagpur-airport-fully-taken-over-by-mihan-india/09021100|title=Nagpur airport fully taken over by Mihan India|first=Nagpur|last=News|date=|website=www.nagpurtoday.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nNagpur's [[Air Traffic Control]] (ATC) is the busiest in India, with more than 300 flights flying over the city every day in 2004.<ref name=ibef29052004>{{cite web |url=http://www.india-now.org/artdisplay.aspx?cat_id=391&art_id=2434|title=Nagpur: South Asia's emergent hub|publisher=The India Brand Equity Foundation|accessdate=4 July 2006}}</ref> In October 2005, Nagpur's Sonegaon Airport was declared an international airport and was renamed [[Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar International Airport]].<ref name=hindu15102005>{{Cite news|url= http://www.hindu.com/2005/10/15/stories/2005101517631500.htm|title= Nagpur Airport being renamed|newspaper= [[The Hindu]]|date= 15 October 2005|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140204035816/http://www.hindu.com/2005/10/15/stories/2005101517631500.htm|archivedate= 4 February 2014|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nNagpur is well connected by daily direct flights to [[Mumbai]], [[Delhi]], [[Hyderabad]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Kolkata]], [[Bangalore]], [[Pune]], [[Chennai]], [[Kochi]], [[Indore]], [[Ahmedabad]] and [[Raipur]] operated by [[Air India]], [[IndiGo]] and [[GoAir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/aviation/go-air-offers-international-connecting-flights-for-as-low-as-rs-7000-check-out-details/story/335566.html|title=Go Air offers international connecting flights for as low as Rs 7,000; check out details|author=|date=|website=www.businesstoday.in|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/2018/oct/27/kochi-gets-air-connectivity-to-eight-more-cities-1890555.html|title=Kochi gets air connectivity to eight more cities|author=|date=|website=The New Indian Express|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u0905\u0939\u092e\u0926\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926\u0938\u093e\u0920\u0940 \u0928\u093e\u0917\u092a\u0941\u0930\u093e\u0924\u0942\u0928 \u0926\u094b\u0928 \u0909\u0921\u094d\u0921\u093e\u0923\u0947 |url=https://www.lokmat.com/nagpur/two-flights-nagpur-ahmedabad/ |accessdate=10 August 2019 |work=Lokmat |date=1 August 2019}}</ref> [[Air Arabia]] operates a 4 times a week to and fro flight between Nagpur and [[Sharjah (city)|Sharjah]] and [[Qatar Airways]] operates a daily direct flight to and from [[Doha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anna.aero/2015/12/07/qatar-airways-resumes-nagpur-service-near-seven-year-hiatus/|title=Qatar Airways resumes Nagpur service near seven-year hiatus|first=George|last=Says|date=7 December 2015|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Nagpur Airport has received Special Achievement Award 2012\u20132013 from [[Airports Authority of India]]. Nagpur became the first airport in India to commission the INDRA system and also has [[Automatic dependent surveillance-broadcast|ADS-B]] system. No other airport in the country had commissioned INDRA yet.<ref>{{cite web |title=AAI achievement award for Nagpur airport |first=Aparna |last=Nair |date=3 April 2013 |website=The Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/AAI-achievement-award-for-Nagpur-airport/articleshow/19370637.cms?referral=PM |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> Nagpur airport became the first airport in the country to receive an [[ISO 27000]] certificate. In fact, Nagpur is not only the first in India but also the first in world to be certified for [[Air navigation service provider]] (ANSP). There are seven airports in the world which have ISO 27000, but none of them have it for ANSP.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nagpur AAI officials to train Mumbai and Delhi staff for acquiring ISO 27000 |first=Aparna |last=Nair |date=16 April 2013 |website=The Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Nagpur-AAI-officials-to-train-Mumbai-and-Delhi-staff-for-acquiring-ISO-27000/articleshow/19582681.cms?referral=PM |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nNagpur is currently witnessing an economic boom as the [[Multi-modal International Cargo Hub and Airport at Nagpur]] (MIHAN) is under development. [[MIHAN]] will be used for handling heavy cargo coming from south east Asia and the Middle East. The project will include {{INRConvert|10000|c}} [[Special Economic Zone]] (SEZ)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/story/3713.html |title=Nagpur stakes claim to lead boomtown pack |work=The Indian Express |location=India |accessdate=1 June 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929125003/http://www.indianexpress.com/story/3713.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> for information technology (IT) companies.\n\nThe [[government of India]] has identified Nagpur airport as one of the safe airports for diverted flights and [[emergency landing]]. In fact, many flights have used the airport during emergencies. This is because all international and domestic airlines had already been informed by the government to go to Nagpur during emergencies. The availability of excellent fire fighting equipment, air traffic control equipment and the latest radar, and being a city with good hospitals and hotels, made the airport a good choice during emergencies.<ref>{{cite web |title=In emergency, head to Nagpur airport |website=The Times of India |first=Sachin |last=Dravekar |date=16 December 2008 |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/In-emergency-head-to-Nagpur-airport/articleshow/3848281.cms?referral=PM |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nNagpur Airport has an annual capacity of 10 lakh passengers, but it handled 19 lakh passengers in 2016-17 and 21 lakh passengers in 2017-18 which is an increase of 14% year on year.<ref name=\"financialexpress.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/airlines-aviation/nagpur-airport-expansion-contract-to-be-awarded-soon/1176196/|title=Nagpur airport expansion contract to be awarded soon|author=|date=22 May 2018 |website=financialexpress.com|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Airport expansion and improvement of service is in the cards and privatisation of the [[airport]] was proposed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://reacho.in/nagpur/local/nagpur-airport-privatisation|title=Bidding For Nagpur Airport Privatisation Starts; GMR Is The Highest Bidder|first=Sumaiya|last=Sheikh|date=1 October 2018|website=Reacho|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> Under privatisation, [[GMR Group|GMR Airport Ltd.]] has been selected for the development, operations and management of the airport<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/gmr-emerges-highest-bidder-for-nagpur-airport-project/article25094078.ece|title=GMR emerges highest bidder for Nagpur airport project|last=PTI|date=|website=@businessline|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Nagpur}}\n\n==Twin towns and sister cities==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-4}}\n* {{flagicon|PRC}} [[Jinan]], [[China]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nagpur/Nagpur-and-Chinas-Jinan-are-now-sister-cities/articleshow/52842062.cms|title=Nagpur and China's Jinan are now sister cities|date=21 June 2016|access-date=21 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[MIHAN]]\n* [[Nagpur Metro]]\n* [[Nagpur District]]\n* [[Make In Maharashtra]]\n* [[List of Maratha dynasties and states]]\n* [[List of forts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Americana Poster|year=1920}}\n{{Commons category|Nagpur}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{CathEncy|wstitle=Nagpur}}\n* {{Cite NSRW|wstitle=Nagpur}}\n\n{{Nagpur}}\n{{vidarbha}}\n{{Maharashtra}}\n{{Million-plus cities in India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nagpur| ]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Nagpur district]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Vidarbha]]\n[[Category:Cities in Maharashtra]]\n", "name_user": "Parikpanchal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReligious places:grammatical fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagpur"}
{"title_page": "The Alienist", "text_new": "{{About||the 1881\u20131882 novella \"The Alienist\" by Machado de Assis|O alienista|the 1970 Brazilian comedy film|The Alienist (film)|the 2018 U.S. television series|The Alienist (TV series)}}\n\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name           = The Alienist\n| image          = Alienist-thumb.jpg\n| caption  = First edition cover\n| author         = [[Caleb Carr]]\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| cover_artist   =\n| series         =\n| publisher      = [[Random House]]\n| release_date   = 1994\n| media_type     = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages          = 496\n| isbn           = 0-679-41779-6\n| dewey= 813/.54 20\n| congress= PS3553.A76277 A44 1994\n| oclc= 28798086\n| followed_by    = ''[[The Angel of Darkness]]''\n}}\n'''''The Alienist''''' is a crime novel by [[Caleb Carr]] first published in 1994 and is the first book in the [[Kreizler series]]. It takes place in New York City in 1896, and includes appearances by many famous figures of New York society in that era, including [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and [[J. P. Morgan]]. The sequel to the novel is ''[[The Angel of Darkness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 29, 1997|title='The Angel of Darkness': Pursuing a Mysterious Kidnapper in Old New York|authorlink=Christopher Lehmann-Haupt|first=Christopher|last=Lehmann-Haupt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/09/28/daily/angel-book-review.html}}</ref> The story follows Roosevelt, then [[New York City police commissioner]], and Dr. Laszlo Kreizler, as their investigative team attempts to solve gruesome murders through new methods including fingerprinting and psychology. The first murder victim investigated is a 13-year-old immigrant who has had his eyes removed, his genitals removed and stuffed in his mouth, and other injuries. The investigators deal with various interest groups that wish to maintain the status quo regarding the poor immigrant population in New York City.\n\nThe book made best-sellers lists of ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' the month it was published, and film rights to the story were purchased by producer [[Scott Rudin]] and [[Paramount Pictures]]. The film studio has since moved the rights over to its television division, where a 10-part event [[The Alienist (TV series)|TV series adaptation]] began its run on January 22 on TNT.<ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/cary-fukunaga-anonymous-content-the-alienist-paramount-true-detective-forrest-gump-1201409741/|title=Cary Fukunaga Behind Event TV Series 'The Alienist' Reteaming With Anonymous Content & Paramount|accessdate=December 12, 2015|date=April 14, 2015|first=Ali|last=Jaafar|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref><ref name=\"McLehman\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/alienist-jakob-verbruggen-replaces-cary-fukunaga-director-tnt-pilot/|title=The Alienist: Jakob Verbuggen Replaces Cary Fukunaga as Director of TNT Series|accessdate=September 30, 2016|date=September 26, 2016|first=Cindy|last=McLehman|work=TVseriesfinale.com}}</ref>''The Alienist'' received generally positive reception. ''[[Booklist]]'' described it as \"superbly atmospheric and compelling\",<ref name=\"hooper\" /> ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' called the work a \"fascinating, fast-paced spine-tingler\",<ref name=\"forbes\" /> and author Paul Levine wrote in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' \"at the end the reader thirsts for another tale of Dr. Laszlo Kreizler\".<ref name=\"levine\" /> ''[[The Houston Chronicle]]'' characterized it \"an out-and-out page-turner\",<ref name=\"bergin\" /> and ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' noted \"Carr brings the dual sensibilities of historian and novelist to the story.\"<ref name=\"ament\" />\n\n== Plot summary ==\nNarrated from the [[First person narration|first-person perspective]] of John Moore, a crime reporter for ''[[The New York Times]]'', the novel begins on January 8, 1919, the day that [[Theodore Roosevelt]] is buried. Moore has dinner with Laszlo Kreizler, the famous [[alienist]]. Kreizler is surrounded by those he has rescued, including his black servant, Cyrus Montrose, and a boy named Stevie \"Stevepipe\" Taggert. (Mary Palmer, another patient and Kreizler's housekeeper, is deceased by the time of this dinner.) Together, they reminisce about their times with Roosevelt, but they focus on one moment: the spring of 1896 and their efforts to catch a serial killer on the [[Lower East Side]] of [[Manhattan]]. The novel is narrated in retrospect, with Moore commenting on the events and how they impacted later history.\n\nAt 2 AM on March 3, 1896, Moore is awakened by one of Kreizler's servants banging incessantly on his door. Stevie, a young boy whom Kreizler had saved from being institutionalized and who is dedicated to Kreizler, brings Moore to the scene of a crime that Kreizler wants Moore to see. Roosevelt, the police commissioner, is already at the scene. When Moore sees the nature of the brutal murder, he is appalled. The victim, Georgio \"Gloria\" Santorelli, is a 13-year-old boy who prostituted himself by dressing up as a girl; the boy's wrists are tied behind his back, and he is kneeling with his face pressed on the steel walkway where he was found. Though makeup paint and powder on his face are still intact, his eyes are gouged out, his right hand is chopped off, his genitals are cut off and stuffed between his jaws, he has huge gashes across his entire body, his throat has been slashed, and his buttocks are \"shorn off\". The policeman at the scene, Detective Sergeant Connor, makes it clear that murders of such victims are usually ignored.\n\n{{Quote box |width=25em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |halig=left | salign=right|quote=\"Prior to the twentieth century, persons suffering from mental illness were thought to be 'alienated,' not only from the rest of society but from their own true natures. Those experts who studied mental pathologies were known as 'alienists'.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014\"Note\" at the beginning of the novel<ref name=Carr>{{cite book |last= Carr |first= Caleb |title= The Alienist |publisher= Random House |year= 1994 |location= New York |pages= [https://archive.org/details/alienist000carr/page/ \"Note\"] |isbn= 0-679-41779-6 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/alienist000carr/page/ }}</ref>}}\nAt Roosevelt's request, Moore, Kreizler, and he meet the following morning in Roosevelt's office to discuss the case. Kreizler has examined the body and disagrees with the official coroner's report. He connects the Santorelli killing to that of a second case in which two children, Benjamin and Sofia Zweig, were killed and had their eyes gouged out. Roosevelt announces that there are two more murders that match the pattern. Roosevelt decides to investigate, but because Kreizler has such a dubious reputation as an alienist, and because the investigation will become politically difficult, he establishes a base of operations for them outside the police precinct. Politically, Roosevelt cannot afford to be associated with the investigation and is not involved with the day-to-day operations.\n\nKreizler asks for some young detectives who are open to new methods and receives the help of Sara Howard, the first woman to be hired by the police department, and Marcus and Lucius Isaacson, two Jewish brothers who were hired when Roosevelt began removing corrupt police officers from the force. The Isaacsons bring sophisticated methods, such as the [[Bertillon system]] and fingerprinting, to the investigation, although these were not popular in New York City police departments at the time nor accepted in courts of law.\n\nThe group begins to investigate the victims, hoping to understand the mind of the murderer by understanding his victims. They interview Georgio Santorelli's mother and discover, for example, that there was discord in his family. Georgio's parents had learned of his being manipulated into performing sexual acts for older boys in school, and the father's response was to try to beat it out of the boy. Georgio eventually left home and lived on the streets as a male-for-male prostitute. They also read the emerging science of psychology, such as the works of [[William James]]. Another body is discovered, and the evidence suggests that the victim knew his attacker. The team also deduces that the killer's agility on rooftops suggests that he is familiar with mountain- or rock-climbing.\n\nKreizler, Roosevelt, Moore, and Howard must deal with various interest groups during their investigation who wish to maintain society's status quo, including a corrupt police force, which takes bribes from owners of the brothels whose prostitutes include poor immigrants; the Catholic Church, which is wary of the potential power of an organized immigrant population; the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]]; and [[J. P. Morgan]].\n\n== Characters ==\n;John Moore: a freelance reporter and the narrator of the novel;\n;Dr. Laszlo Kreizler: the titular alienist of the novel;\n;Sara Howard: Moore's longtime friend, now a secretary at NYPD headquarters;\n;Stevie Taggert: Kreizler's teenage groom and carriage driver;\n;Cyrus Montrose: Kreizler's valet and bodyguard;\n;Mary Palmer: Kreizler's housemaid;\n;Marcus and Lucius Isaacson: twin brother Detective Sergeants with the NYPD;\n\n=== Historical figures ===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Thomas F. Byrnes]]\n* [[Anthony Comstock]]\n* [[Michael Corrigan]]\n* [[James T. Ellison|James \"Biff\" Ellison]]\n* [[H. H. Holmes]] (mentioned only)\n* [[William James]]\n* [[Paul Kelly (criminal)|Paul Kelly]]\n* [[Jack McManus]]\n* [[Adolf Meyer (psychiatrist)|Adolf Meyer]]\n* [[J. P. Morgan]]\n* [[Jesse Pomeroy]]\n* [[Henry C. Potter]]\n* [[Jacob Riis]]\n* [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n* [[Lincoln Steffens]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Composition and biographical background==\n\n[[File:Bellevue Hospital Ambulance, New York Times, 1895.JPG|thumb|Ambulance standing outside [[Bellevue Hospital|Bellevue]], a psychiatric hospital, in [[New York City]] in 1895]]\n''The Alienist'' is set in the neighborhood where Carr lives, and he has spent hours wandering around it. He also spent a lot of time researching his book at the [[The Morgan Library & Museum|J. P. Morgan Library]].<ref name=Capuzzo/> Carr pitched the book as non-fiction, because he was afraid his agent and editor would not accept a fiction book from a non-fiction author. Only when the publisher was on the verge of buying the book did he reveal the truth.<ref name=Purdy>{{cite news|last=Purdy|first=Matthew|title=Writing to Flee the Past|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 19, 1994}}</ref>\nThe novel \"allowed him to exorcise some of his demons, mostly centered on his relationship with his father, which was stormy and sometimes violent.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/> Carr will not reveal specific details of his family history, but he has said, \"It's safe to assume that I know something about family violence....\" and he told ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, \"I'm the only kid in my family who never tried to kill himself...I kind of figured somebody else was going to kill me anyway.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\nCarr's natural father, [[Lucien Carr]], was a writer, who in the 1940s was at the center of a group of as-yet unknown writers ([[Jack Kerouac]], [[Allen Ginsberg]], and [[William Burroughs]]). In the summer of 1944, he killed his former scoutmaster, a man who was enamored with him. One night, the scoutmaster supposedly made a move on Lucien Carr, and Carr stabbed him in the chest with his boy scout knife. Carr disposed of the body in the [[Hudson River]], and together he and Kerouac got rid of the knife. Carr was sentenced to two years' jail time and Kerouac a few days.<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\nCaleb Carr was \"fascinated with the psychology of killers, who were subliminally acting out the pain of being controlled by monstrous parents by controlling and killing victims, seeking a release that would never come.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/> As he explains, \"For me it began in New York with the [[Son of Sam]] killings while I was in college...I think I can understand some of the kind of rage that's behind what they do. I can't understand the major portion of it because that's what leads to the violence they commit. But I can understand the germ of it.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\n==Genre and style==\n\n''The Alienist'' has been called a detective novel, an historical novel, and a mystery novel.<ref name=levine/> It is set in 1896, \"the moment in history when the modern idea of the serial killer became available\", eight years after the [[Jack the Ripper]] case, and at a time when the word \"psychopath\" was new to scientists.<ref name=Begley>{{cite news|last=Begley|first=Adam|title=Tracking a Serial Killer In Victorian New York|work=[[Newsday]]|date=March 31, 1994}}</ref> Like [[E. L. Doctorow]]'s ''[[Ragtime (novel)|''Ragtime'']]'', the novel combines fact with fiction.<ref name=levine/> Historical figures such as [[Lincoln Steffens]], [[Jacob Riis]], [[Anthony Comstock]], and [[J. Pierpont Morgan]] appear briefly in the novel and interact with the fictional characters.<ref name=Levins>{{cite news|last=Levins|first=Harry|title=On the trail of a murderer - thriller unfolds in 19th-century|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=May 1, 1994}}</ref> Carr includes period details, such as descriptions of \"sumptuous meals of turtle soup au clair, Creole eggs, broiled squab, saddle of lamb a la Colbert and 'a liter of smooth, dark Wurzburger (beer) that had a head as thick as whipped cream'\".<ref name=levine/>\n\n==Themes==\n{{Quote box |width=25em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |halig=left | salign=right|quote=\"The biggest challenge was to study the psychological literature of that day, so that none of my characters would know any more than they *could* have known about psychology.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014Caleb Carr<ref name=\"chollet\" />}}\nIn an interview with ''[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]'', Carr stated he wanted to entertain the reader, while also staying faithful to the time period.<ref name=\"chollet\" /> Carr, a historian by training, wanted to find a form of writing where he could meld his interest in fiction with his knowledge of history.<ref name=\"chollet\" /> \"The one thing I wanted to show was that people back then are a lot more like people today than we realize,\" said Carr.<ref name=\"chollet\" /> Carr researched the science and literature of the time period and noted, \"The biggest challenge was to study the psychological literature of that day so that none of my characters would not know more than they could have known in terms of psychology. We're talking about a time when [[Sigmund Freud]] had just published his first book.\"<ref name=\"chollet\" />\n\nAuthor Paul Levine compares Kreizler to [[Sherlock Holmes]] and [[Sigmund Freud]].<ref name=\"levine\" /> He likens ''The Alienist'' to ''[[Ragtime (novel)|Ragtime]]'' by [[E.L. Doctorow]]; both stories fuse historical fiction with real characters from the time period.<ref name=\"levine\" /> Levine notes the story serves as a \"painless history lesson\", and comments that the juxtaposition of J.P. Morgan's lifestyle with \" the teeming tenements where police dare not enter\", serve as \"reminders that crime and class distinction are hardly new\".<ref name=\"levine\" />\n\nCarr has said that \"The Alienist is about how violent behavior is perpetuated from one generation to the next.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\n''The Alienist'' \"explores the causes of insanity and criminality, and ultimately the nature of evil\".<ref name=LehmannHaupt>{{cite news|last=Lehmann-Haupt|first=Christopher|title=Of an Erudite Sleuth Tracking a Madman|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 29, 1994}}</ref>\n\nAnother theme is destiny, and the novel investigates New York City's destiny, \"saying its basic character and problems have endured over history\".<ref name=Purdy/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Sales and marketing===\nRandom House paid Carr an advance of $60,000 for the book.<ref name=\"blush\">{{cite news | work =New York Times News Service | title ='Alienist' Makes Publisher Blush In Paperback Profits | via =[[The Deseret News]] | page =E5 |date =June 26, 1994}}</ref> Paperback rights were sold at auction to Bantam for $1,001,000.<ref name=\"blush\" /> The book made ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> list of best-sellers in April 1994,<ref>{{cite news |  title =Publishers Weekly best-sellers | work =[[The Cincinnati Post]] | page =3D | date =April 9, 1994}}</ref> and during the summer of 1994 reached between no. 4 and no. 7 on [[New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref name=Capuzzo>{{cite news|title=Author feeds his romantic, sinister image|last=Capuzzo|first=Mike|work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=August 25, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =New York Times Best Sellers List | work =[[Austin American-Statesman]] | page =6 | date =April 17, 1994 }}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\n{{Quote box |width=25em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |halig=left | salign=right|quote=\"The story feels like a Sherlock Holmes tale, reads like a modern thriller, and is historically accurate.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014''[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]''<ref name=\"chollet\" />}}\nThe book has received generally favorable reviews; \"while most critics found it entertaining, some said it was sometimes flabby with historical detail and its prose was less than literature.\"<ref name=Purdy/>\nIn a review published in ''[[Booklist]]'', Brad Hooper calls ''The Alienist'' and Caleb Carr's sequel, ''The Angel of Darkness'', \"superbly atmospheric and compelling\".<ref name=\"hooper\">{{cite journal | last = Hooper | first = Brad | title = The Alienist (Book review) | journal = [[Booklist]] | volume = 96 | issue = 15 | page = 1442 | date = April 1, 2000}}</ref> A review of ''The Alienist'' in ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' comments: \"Wonderfully evocative of the age, this fascinating, fast-paced spine-tingler never flags.\"<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite magazine|  title =The Alienist | magazine =[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] | volume =158 | issue =9 | page =28 | date =October 14, 1996 }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]'', Laurence Chollet notes: \"The story feels like a Sherlock Holmes tale, reads like a modern thriller, and is historically accurate.\"<ref name=\"chollet\">{{cite news | last =Chollet | first =Laurence | title =Authenticity Fills a Novel | work =[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]] | page =E05 | publisher =Bergen Record Corp. | date =April 10, 1994 }}</ref> In his review in [[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|''The Gazette'']] of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], Victor Greto wrote: \"Through his research into the New York of the late 19th century, [Carr] has also fleshed out an atmosphere and a time that, on the one hand, seems grimly real and unapproachably evil, but, on the other, is within our intellectual grasp.\"<ref name=\"greto\">{{cite news | last =Greto | first =Victor | title =19th century New York comes to life - 'The Alienist' fleshes out a city where decay, indifference coexist | work =[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)]] | page =3 | date =April 10, 1994}}</ref> In her review for ''[[Tulsa World]]'', Patricia Ann Jones wrote that the novel \"breaks new ground on several fronts. As a historical novel it paints an unrivaled picture of New York. As a thriller it sets a new pace. But as a psychological study it stands completely on its own. The writing is quite simply, superb.\"<ref name=Jones>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Patricia|title='The Alienist ' Is Best Seller With Reason - Superb Thriller Explores Mental Illness in 1890s|work=[[Tulsa World]]|date=May 22, 1994}}</ref>\n\nIn his review of the book for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[Mortal Sin (book)|Mortal Sin]]'' author [[Paul Levine]] writes: \"the long story never becomes tedious, and at the end the reader thirsts for another tale of Dr. Lazlo Kreizler\".<ref name=\"levine\">{{cite news | last =Levine | first =Paul | title =Psychology Yesterday - A Period Mystery Introduces Modern Sleuthing to 1896 | work =[[Chicago Tribune]] | page =4 | date =April 17, 1994}}</ref> Kathye Self of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' characterizes the work as \"an out-and-out page-turner about the first time a 'psychological profile' was used to track down a serial murderer\".<ref name=\"bergin\">{{cite news | last =Bergin | first = Kathye Self|title =Hunting the 'imaginary man': Compelling thriller tracks 1890s serial killer with early psychological profile | work =[[Houston Chronicle]] | page =23 | date = April 24, 1994}}</ref> Christopher Lehmann-Haupt writes in ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'': \"Carr has lovingly evoked not only a physical sense of old New York but the spirit of the time as well, when the powers in charge were worried about unrest among the masses of cheap immigrant labor.\"<ref name=\"haupt\">{{cite news | last =Lehmann-Haupt | first =Christopher | title =Murder and philosophy | work =[[The Tampa Tribune]] | page =6 | publisher = The Tribune Co. | date =May 1, 1994}}</ref> In a review for ''[[The Seattle Times]]'', Deloris Tarzan Ament comments: \"A contributing editor to Military History Quarterly, Carr brings the dual sensibilities of historian and novelist to the story.\"<ref name=\"ament\">{{cite news | last =Ament | first =Deloris Tarzan | title =Murder, He Wrote - 'The Alienist' Crackles With History, Colorful Characters | work =[[The Seattle Times]] | page =M2 | date =May 1, 1994 }}</ref> In his review for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', novelist [[Jack Katzenbach]] argued that Carr's impeccable research and rich detail hindered the work's pace but rewarded readers by portraying \"the excitement of a world on the verge of change, where invention was the stuff of daily miracle,\" specifically when it came to forensics.<ref name=Katzenbach>{{cite news|last=Katzenbach|first=Jack|title=Ragtime Ripper|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 27, 1994}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"the only real weakness of the book lies in the stringent rationality of Kreizler's investigation. The more his logic makes sense the less threatening his quarry seems, at least to the reader....The story's fatalism grows tedious....Nor does it help that throughout most of the story none of the major characters are directly threatened by the killer. Of course, it is deplorable that children are being murdered. But none of them figure strongly enough in the story to arouse the reader's visceral identification.\"<ref name=LehmannHaupt/> Scott Eyman of ''[[The Palm Beach Post]]'' was critical of the \"flaccid dialogue\" and \"vague characters\".<ref name=Eyman>{{cite news|last=Eyman|first=Scott|title=Tedious 'Alienist' has no place on best-seller list|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|date=May 15, 1994}}</ref> Hary Levins from the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' noted that the novel does include a few notable anachronisms. For example, the \"heroes display an early (and highly improbable) political correctness toward blacks and homosexuals. And his detective team anticipates the feminist movement by enlisting a tough-minded career woman who's unafraid to pack a pistol and spout a bit of scatological English.\"<ref name=Levins/>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Film===\nCarr told ''[[The Orange County Register]]'' he had envisioned a film adaptation of his work while writing the story.<ref name=\"takahama\">{{cite news | last =Takahama | first =Valerie | title ='Alienist' author is no stranger to films - Profile: Caleb Carr had a movie in mind when he wrote his book _ and now Hollywood has picked up on the idea | work =[[The Orange County Register]] | page =e28 | date =July 3, 1994 }}</ref> \"I was always aware that if done correctly, this could end up being a great movie. I grew up with the movies. I've written scripts. Movies are something I've always loved,\" he said.<ref name=\"takahama\" /> Carr thought of [[Emma Thompson]] to play Sara, and [[Anthony Hopkins]] or [[Sam Neill]] to play Kreizler.<ref name=\"takahama\" />\n\nBefore the book was published, [[film producer]] [[Scott Rudin]] purchased the film rights to the novel for $500,000.<ref name=\"chollet\" /><ref name=\"takahama\" /> In June 1993, [[Paramount Pictures]] bought the film rights to the novel for $750,000.<ref name=\"ament\" /><ref name=\"steer\" />\n\nIn January 1995, ''[[The River Wild]]'' director [[Curtis Hanson]] was reported to have been in the process of final negotiations with Scott Rudin and Paramount Pictures to direct ''The Alienist''.<ref name=\"steer\">{{cite news\n | last =Busch | first =Anita M. ([[Variety magazine]]) | title ='River Wild' Director Set to Steer 'Alienist' | work =[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | page =32| date =January 18, 1995 }}</ref> By May 1995, Hanson was signed on as the film's director.<ref name=\"scouts\" /> ''[[Variety magazine|Variety]]'' reported that the film's producers planned for filming to start in Spring 1995, with an intended Christmas release date in mind.<ref name=\"steer\" /> [[Tony Award]]-winning playwright [[David Henry Hwang]] adapted the book for film.<ref name=\"steer\" /> Scouts for the film visited [[Philadelphia]] in May 1995 to consider location shooting in the city.<ref name=\"scouts\">{{cite news | last =Rea | first =Steven | title = \"Alienist\" scouts take look at Philadelphia | work =[[The Tampa Tribune]] | page =6 | publisher =The Tribune Co. | date =May 3, 1995 }}</ref> Film scouts for ''The Alienist'' were particularly interested in Philadelphia's [[Academy of Music (Philadelphia)|Academy of Music]], [[Eastern State Penitentiary]], and [[Fairmount Water Works|Waterworks]].<ref name=\"scouts\" />\n\nParamount Pictures was concerned with the film's budget, which reportedly was almost $50 million.<ref name=\"pressure\" /> By 1997, multiple script drafts from three writers brought costs to approximately $2 million.<ref name=\"pressure\">{{cite news | title =Pressure Applied To 'Alienist' Team | work =[[San Jose Mercury News]] | page =12E | date =January 1, 1997}}</ref> After delays in production, Paramount Pictures told the group behind the film they had two months to set the project up at another studio.<ref name=\"pressure\" /> In a review of Carr's sequel ''[[The Angel of Darkness]]'', Malcolm L. Johnson of ''[[The Hartford Courant]]'' cited concerns over how to depict the mutilation of the murdered prostitutes in the film, writing: \"Questions about how to treat this gruesome element has perhaps delayed the film of ''The Alienist.''\"<ref name=\"fallsshort\">{{cite news | last =Johnson | first =Malcolm L. | title =Carr's 'Angel' Falls Short of Chilling 'Alienist' | work =[[The Hartford Courant]] | page =G3| date =September 14, 1997}}</ref> When in a 1999 online chat with fans, set up by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and [[Yahoo!]], Carr was asked if there were film plans for ''The Alienist'' or ''The Angel of Darkness'', he responded: \"Only 'The Alienist,' and the attempts have been so bad that I have not yet sold 'Angel' to the movies. What happened was that a producer bought the rights and then decided he had to completely change the characters in the book. We got into a huge conflict, one that is actually ongoing.\"<ref name=\"webtranscript\">{{cite web | title =Novelist Caleb Carr - Transcript from Nov. 3, 1999 | series =Visions of the 21st Century | work =[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date =November 3, 1999 | url =http://www.time.com/time/community/transcripts/1999/110399carr.html | accessdate = 2009-05-27 }}</ref>\n\n===TV series===\n{{main|The Alienist (TV series)}}\nIn April 2015, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that [[Paramount Television]] had decided to use a three-year, first-look production deal they made with [[Anonymous Content]] productions to adapt ''The Alienist'' as an event TV series.<ref name=\"Deadline\"/> [[Jakob Verbruggen]] was chosen to serve as director after [[Cary Fukunaga]]<ref name=\"McLehman\"/> had to withdraw.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bergmann, Ina, \"Jack the Ripper's American Cousins: Representations of Good and Evil in Historical Crime Fiction,\" ''Representations of Evil in Fiction and Film'', Anglistik \u2013 Amerikanistik \u2013 Anglophonie, vol. 11, ed. Jochen Achilles and Ina Bergmann (Trier: WVT, 2009) 137\u201356.\n* Link, Alex, \"City Limits: Fixing New York in Caleb Carr's ''The Alienist'',\" ''CLUES: A Journal of Detection'' 23.3 (Spring 2005): 31\u201341.\n* Tallack, Douglas, \"Caleb Carr: Running Away from the Darkness,\" ''The Detective as Historian: History and Art in Historical Crime Fiction'', ed. Ray B. Browne and Lawrence A. Kreiser, Jr. (Bowling Green: Bowling Green State U Popular P, 2000) 251\u201364.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Books|Psychology}}\n* [http://www.17thstreet.net 17th Street] Comprehensive site dedicated to ''The Alienist'' and ''The Angel of Darkness''\n* [http://www.blackhatworld.com/blackhat-seo/blackhat-lounge/736115-book-reccomendation-alienist.html Discussion BHW] The book ''The Alienist'' discussed in detail on a popular forum.\n{{Caleb Carr novels}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alienist, The}}\n[[Category:American crime novels]]\n[[Category:American historical novels]]\n[[Category:1994 American novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Caleb Carr]]\n[[Category:Novels about American prostitution]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1896]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Anthony Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:Random House books]]\n[[Category:American mystery novels]]\n[[Category:Grand Prix de Litt\u00e9rature Polici\u00e8re winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the 1881\u20131882 novella \"The Alienist\" by Machado de Assis|O alienista|the 1970 Brazilian comedy film|The Alienist (film)|the 2018 U.S. television series|The Alienist (TV series)}}\n\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name           = The Alienist\n| image          = Alienist-thumb.jpg\n| caption  = First edition cover\n| author         = [[Caleb Carr]]\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| cover_artist   =\n| series         =\n| publisher      = [[Random House]]\n| release_date   = 1994\n| media_type     = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages          = 496\n| isbn           = 0-679-41779-6\n| dewey= 813/.54 20\n| congress= PS3553.A76277 A44 1994\n| oclc= 28798086\n| followed_by    = ''[[The Angel of Darkness]]''\n}}\n'''''The Alienist''''' is a crime novel by [[Caleb Carr]] first published in 1994 and is the first book in the [[Kreizler series]]. It takes place in New York City in 1896, and includes appearances by many famous figures of New York society in that era, including [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and [[J. P. Morgan]]. The sequel to the novel is ''[[The Angel of Darkness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 29, 1997|title='The Angel of Darkness': Pursuing a Mysterious Kidnapper in Old New York|authorlink=Christopher Lehmann-Haupt|first=Christopher|last=Lehmann-Haupt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/09/28/daily/angel-book-review.html}}</ref> The story follows Roosevelt, then [[New York City police commissioner]], and Dr. Laszlo Kreizler, as their investigative team attempts to solve gruesome murders through new methods including fingerprinting and psychology. The first murder victim investigated is a 13-year-old immigrant who has had his eyes removed, his genitals removed and stuffed in his mouth, and other injuries. The investigators deal with various interest groups that wish to maintain the status quo regarding the poor immigrant population in New York City.\n\nThe book made best-sellers lists of ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' the month it was published, and film rights to the story were purchased by producer [[Scott Rudin]] and [[Paramount Pictures]]. The film studio has since moved the rights over to its television division, where a 10-part event [[The Alienist (TV series)|TV series adaptation]] began its run on January 22 on TNT.<ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/cary-fukunaga-anonymous-content-the-alienist-paramount-true-detective-forrest-gump-1201409741/|title=Cary Fukunaga Behind Event TV Series 'The Alienist' Reteaming With Anonymous Content & Paramount|accessdate=December 12, 2015|date=April 14, 2015|first=Ali|last=Jaafar|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref><ref name=\"McLehman\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/alienist-jakob-verbruggen-replaces-cary-fukunaga-director-tnt-pilot/|title=The Alienist: Jakob Verbuggen Replaces Cary Fukunaga as Director of TNT Series|accessdate=September 30, 2016|date=September 26, 2016|first=Cindy|last=McLehman|work=TVseriesfinale.com}}</ref>''The Alienist'' received generally positive reception. ''[[Booklist]]'' described it as \"superbly atmospheric and compelling\",<ref name=\"hooper\" /> ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' called the work a \"fascinating, fast-paced spine-tingler\",<ref name=\"forbes\" /> and author Paul Levine wrote in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' \"at the end the reader thirsts for another tale of Dr. Laszlo Kreizler\".<ref name=\"levine\" /> ''[[The Houston Chronicle]]'' characterized it \"an out-and-out page-turner\",<ref name=\"bergin\" /> and ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' noted \"Carr brings the dual sensibilities of historian and novelist to the story.\"<ref name=\"ament\" />\n\n== Plot summary ==\nNarrated from the [[First person narration|first-person perspective]] of John Moore, a crime reporter for ''[[The New York Times]]'', the novel begins on January 8, 1919, the day that [[Theodore Roosevelt]] is buried. Moore has dinner with Laszlo Kreizler, the famous [[alienist]]. Kreizler is surrounded by those he has rescued, including his black servant, Cyrus Montrose, and a boy named Stevie \"Stevepipe\" Taggert. (Mary Palmer, another patient and Kreizler's housekeeper, is deceased by the time of this dinner.) Together, they reminisce about their times with Roosevelt, but they focus on one moment: the spring of 1896 and their efforts to catch a serial killer on the [[Lower East Side]] of [[Manhattan]]. The novel is narrated in retrospect, with Moore commenting on the events and how they impacted later history.\n\nAt 2 AM on March 3, 1896, Moore is awakened by one of Kreizler's servants banging incessantly on his door. Stevie, a young boy whom Kreizler had saved from being institutionalized and who is dedicated to Kreizler, brings Moore to the scene of a crime that Kreizler wants Moore to see. Roosevelt, the police commissioner, is already at the scene. When Moore sees the nature of the brutal murder, he is appalled. The victim, Georgio \"Gloria\" Santorelli, is a 13-year-old boy who prostituted himself by dressing up as a girl; the boy's wrists are tied behind his back, and he is kneeling with his face pressed on the steel walkway where he was found. Though makeup paint and powder on his face are still intact, his eyes are gouged out, his right hand is chopped off, his genitals are cut off and stuffed between his jaws, he has huge gashes across his entire body, his throat has been slashed, and his buttocks are \"shorn off\". The policeman at the scene, Detective Sergeant Connor, makes it clear that murders of such victims are usually ignored.\n\n{{Quote box |width=25em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |halig=left | salign=right|quote=\"Prior to the twentieth century, persons suffering from mental illness were thought to be 'alienated,' not only from the rest of society but from their own true natures. Those experts who studied mental pathologies were known as 'alienists'.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014\"Note\" at the beginning of the novel<ref name=Carr>{{cite book |last= Carr |first= Caleb |title= The Alienist |publisher= Random House |year= 1994 |location= New York |pages= [https://archive.org/details/alienist000carr/page/ \"Note\"] |isbn= 0-679-41779-6 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/alienist000carr/page/ }}</ref>}}\nAt Roosevelt's request, Moore, Kreizler, and he meet the following morning in Roosevelt's office to discuss the case. Kreizler has examined the body and disagrees with the official coroner's report. He connects the Santorelli killing to that of a second case in which two children, Benjamin and Sofia Zweig, were killed and had their eyes gouged out. Roosevelt announces that there are two more murders that match the pattern. Roosevelt decides to investigate, but because Kreizler has such a dubious reputation as an alienist, and because the investigation will become politically difficult, he establishes a base of operations for them outside the police precinct. Politically, Roosevelt cannot afford to be associated with the investigation and is not involved with the day-to-day operations.\n\nKreizler asks for some young detectives who are open to new methods and receives the help of Sara Howard, the first woman to be hired by the police department, and Marcus and Lucius Isaacson, two Jewish brothers who were hired when Roosevelt began removing corrupt police officers from the force. The Isaacsons bring sophisticated methods, such as the [[Bertillon system]] and fingerprinting, to the investigation, although these were not popular in New York City police departments at the time nor accepted in courts of law.\n\nThe group begins to investigate the victims, hoping to understand the mind of the murderer by understanding his victims. They interview Georgio Santorelli's mother and discover, for example, that there was discord in his family. Georgio's parents had learned of his being manipulated into performing sexual acts for older boys in school, and the father's response was to try to beat it out of the boy. Georgio eventually left home and lived on the streets as a male-for-male prostitute. They also read the emerging science of psychology, such as the works of [[William James]]. Another body is discovered, and the evidence suggests that the victim knew his attacker. The team also deduces that the killer's agility on rooftops suggests that he is familiar with mountain- or rock-climbing.\n\nKreizler, Roosevelt, Moore, and Howard must deal with various interest groups during their investigation who wish to maintain society's status quo, including a corrupt police force, which takes bribes from owners of the brothels whose prostitutes include poor immigrants; the Catholic Church, which is wary of the potential power of an organized immigrant population; the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]]; and [[J. P. Morgan]].\n\n== Characters ==\n;John Moore: a freelance reporter and the narrator of the novel;\n;Dr. Laszlo Kreizler: the titular alienist of the novel;\n;Sara Howard: Moore's longtime friend, now a secretary at NYPD headquarters;\n;Stevie Taggert: Kreizler's teenage groom and carriage driver;\n;Cyrus Montrose: Kreizler's valet and bodyguard;\n;Mary Palmer: Kreizler's housemaid;\n;Marcus and Lucius Isaacson: twin brother Detective Sergeants with the NYPD;\n\n=== Historical figures ===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Thomas F. Byrnes]]\n* [[Anthony Comstock]]\n* [[Michael Corrigan]]\n* [[James T. Ellison|James \"Biff\" Ellison]]\n* [[H. H. Holmes]] (mentioned only)\n* [[William James]]\n* [[Paul Kelly (criminal)|Paul Kelly]]\n* [[Jack McManus]]\n* [[Adolf Meyer (psychiatrist)|Adolf Meyer]]\n* [[J. P. Morgan]]\n* [[Jesse Pomeroy]]\n* [[Henry C. Potter]]\n* [[Jacob Riis]]\n* [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n* [[Lincoln Steffens]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Composition and biographical background==\n\n[[File:Bellevue Hospital Ambulance, New York Times, 1895.JPG|thumb|Ambulance standing outside [[Bellevue Hospital|Bellevue]], a psychiatric hospital, in [[New York City]] in 1895]]\n''The Alienist'' is set in the neighborhood where Carr lives, and he has spent hours wandering around it. He also spent a lot of time researching his book at the [[The Morgan Library & Museum|J. P. Morgan Library]].<ref name=Capuzzo/> Carr pitched the book as non-fiction, because he was afraid his agent and editor would not accept a fiction book from a non-fiction author. Only when the publisher was on the verge of buying the book did he reveal the truth.<ref name=Purdy>{{cite news|last=Purdy|first=Matthew|title=Writing to Flee the Past|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 19, 1994}}</ref>\nThe novel \"allowed him to exorcise some of his demons, mostly centered on his relationship with his father, which was stormy and sometimes violent.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/> Carr will not reveal specific details of his family history, but he has said, \"It's safe to assume that I know something about family violence....\" and he told ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, \"I'm the only kid in my family who never tried to kill himself...I kind of figured somebody else was going to kill me anyway.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\nCarr's natural father, [[Lucien Carr]], was a writer, who in the 1940s was at the center of a group of as-yet unknown writers ([[Jack Kerouac]], [[Allen Ginsberg]], and [[William Burroughs]]). In the summer of 1944, he killed his former scoutmaster, a man who was enamored with him. One night, the scoutmaster supposedly made a move on Lucien Carr, and Carr stabbed him in the chest with his boy scout knife. Carr disposed of the body in the [[Hudson River]], and together he and Kerouac got rid of the knife. Carr was sentenced to two years' jail time and Kerouac a few days.<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\nCaleb Carr was \"fascinated with the psychology of killers, who were subliminally acting out the pain of being controlled by monstrous parents by controlling and killing victims, seeking a release that would never come.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/> As he explains, \"For me it began in New York with the [[Son of Sam]] killings while I was in college...I think I can understand some of the kind of rage that's behind what they do. I can't understand the major portion of it because that's what leads to the violence they commit. But I can understand the germ of it.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\n==Genre and style==\n\n''The Alienist'' has been called a detective novel, an historical novel, and a mystery novel.<ref name=levine/> It is set in 1896, \"the moment in history when the modern idea of the serial killer became available\", eight years after the [[Jack the Ripper]] case, and at a time when the word \"psychopath\" was new to scientists.<ref name=Begley>{{cite news|last=Begley|first=Adam|title=Tracking a Serial Killer In Victorian New York|work=[[Newsday]]|date=March 31, 1994}}</ref> Like [[E. L. Doctorow]]'s ''[[Ragtime (novel)|''Ragtime'']]'', the novel combines fact with fiction.<ref name=levine/> Historical figures such as [[Lincoln Steffens]], [[Jacob Riis]], [[Anthony Comstock]], and [[J. Pierpont Morgan]] appear briefly in the novel and interact with the fictional characters.<ref name=Levins>{{cite news|last=Levins|first=Harry|title=On the trail of a murderer - thriller unfolds in 19th-century|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=May 1, 1994}}</ref> Carr includes period details, such as descriptions of \"sumptuous meals of turtle soup au clair, Creole eggs, broiled squab, saddle of lamb a la Colbert and 'a liter of smooth, dark Wurzburger (beer) that had a head as thick as whipped cream'\".<ref name=levine/>\n\n==Themes==\n{{Quote box |width=25em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |halig=left | salign=right|quote=\"The biggest challenge was to study the psychological literature of that day, so that none of my characters would know any more than they *could* have known about psychology.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014Caleb Carr<ref name=\"chollet\" />}}\nIn an interview with ''[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]'', Carr stated he wanted to entertain the reader, while also staying faithful to the time period.<ref name=\"chollet\" /> Carr, a historian by training, wanted to find a form of writing where he could meld his interest in fiction with his knowledge of history.<ref name=\"chollet\" /> \"The one thing I wanted to show was that people back then are a lot more like people today than we realize,\" said Carr.<ref name=\"chollet\" /> Carr researched the science and literature of the time period and noted, \"The biggest challenge was to study the psychological literature of that day so that none of my characters would not know more than they could have known in terms of psychology. We're talking about a time when [[Sigmund Freud]] had just published his first book.\"<ref name=\"chollet\" />\n\nAuthor Paul Levine compares Kreizler to [[Sherlock Holmes]] and [[Sigmund Freud]].<ref name=\"levine\" /> He likens ''The Alienist'' to ''[[Ragtime (novel)|Ragtime]]'' by [[E.L. Doctorow]]; both stories fuse historical fiction with real characters from the time period.<ref name=\"levine\" /> Levine notes the story serves as a \"painless history lesson\", and comments that the juxtaposition of J.P. Morgan's lifestyle with \" the teeming tenements where police dare not enter\", serve as \"reminders that crime and class distinction are hardly new\".<ref name=\"levine\" />\n\nCarr has said that \"The Alienist is about how violent behavior is perpetuated from one generation to the next.\"<ref name=Capuzzo/>\n\n''The Alienist'' \"explores the causes of insanity and criminality, and ultimately the nature of evil\".<ref name=LehmannHaupt>{{cite news|last=Lehmann-Haupt|first=Christopher|title=Of an Erudite Sleuth Tracking a Madman|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 29, 1994}}</ref>\n\nAnother theme is destiny, and the novel investigates New York City's destiny, \"saying its basic character and problems have endured over history\".<ref name=Purdy/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Sales and marketing===\nRandom House paid Carr an advance of $60,000 for the book.<ref name=\"blush\">{{cite news | work =New York Times News Service | title ='Alienist' Makes Publisher Blush In Paperback Profits | via =[[The Deseret News]] | page =E5 |date =June 26, 1994}}</ref> Paperback rights were sold at auction to Bantam for $1,001,000.<ref name=\"blush\" /> The book made ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> list of best-sellers in April 1994,<ref>{{cite news |  title =Publishers Weekly best-sellers | work =[[The Cincinnati Post]] | page =3D | date =April 9, 1994}}</ref> and during the summer of 1994 reached between no. 4 and no. 7 on [[New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref name=Capuzzo>{{cite news|title=Author feeds his romantic, sinister image|last=Capuzzo|first=Mike|work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=August 25, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =New York Times Best Sellers List | work =[[Austin American-Statesman]] | page =6 | date =April 17, 1994 }}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\n{{Quote box |width=25em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |halig=left | salign=right|quote=\"The story feels like a Sherlock Holmes tale, reads like a modern thriller, and is historically accurate.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014''[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]''<ref name=\"chollet\" />}}\nThe book has received generally favorable reviews; \"while most critics found it entertaining, some said it was sometimes flabby with historical detail and its prose was less than literature.\"<ref name=Purdy/>\nIn a review published in ''[[Booklist]]'', Brad Hooper calls ''The Alienist'' and Caleb Carr's sequel, ''The Angel of Darkness'', \"superbly atmospheric and compelling\".<ref name=\"hooper\">{{cite journal | last = Hooper | first = Brad | title = The Alienist (Book review) | journal = [[Booklist]] | volume = 96 | issue = 15 | page = 1442 | date = April 1, 2000}}</ref> A review of ''The Alienist'' in ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' comments: \"Wonderfully evocative of the age, this fascinating, fast-paced spine-tingler never flags.\"<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite magazine|  title =The Alienist | magazine =[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] | volume =158 | issue =9 | page =28 | date =October 14, 1996 }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]]'', Laurence Chollet notes: \"The story feels like a Sherlock Holmes tale, reads like a modern thriller, and is historically accurate.\"<ref name=\"chollet\">{{cite news | last =Chollet | first =Laurence | title =Authenticity Fills a Novel | work =[[The Record (Bergen County)|The Record]] | page =E05 | publisher =Bergen Record Corp. | date =April 10, 1994 }}</ref> In his review in [[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|''The Gazette'']] of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], Victor Greto wrote: \"Through his research into the New York of the late 19th century, [Carr] has also fleshed out an atmosphere and a time that, on the one hand, seems grimly real and unapproachably evil, but, on the other, is within our intellectual grasp.\"<ref name=\"greto\">{{cite news | last =Greto | first =Victor | title =19th century New York comes to life - 'The Alienist' fleshes out a city where decay, indifference coexist | work =[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)]] | page =3 | date =April 10, 1994}}</ref> In her review for ''[[Tulsa World]]'', Patricia Ann Jones wrote that the novel \"breaks new ground on several fronts. As a historical novel it paints an unrivaled picture of New York. As a thriller it sets a new pace. But as a psychological study it stands completely on its own. The writing is quite simply, superb.\"<ref name=Jones>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Patricia|title='The Alienist ' Is Best Seller With Reason - Superb Thriller Explores Mental Illness in 1890s|work=[[Tulsa World]]|date=May 22, 1994}}</ref>\n\nIn his review of the book for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[Mortal Sin (book)|Mortal Sin]]'' author [[Paul Levine]] writes: \"the long story never becomes tedious, and at the end the reader thirsts for another tale of Dr. Lazlo Kreizler\".<ref name=\"levine\">{{cite news | last =Levine | first =Paul | title =Psychology Yesterday - A Period Mystery Introduces Modern Sleuthing to 1896 | work =[[Chicago Tribune]] | page =4 | date =April 17, 1994}}</ref> Kathye Self of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' characterizes the work as \"an out-and-out page-turner about the first time a 'psychological profile' was used to track down a serial murderer\".<ref name=\"bergin\">{{cite news | last =Bergin | first = Kathye Self|title =Hunting the 'imaginary man': Compelling thriller tracks 1890s serial killer with early psychological profile | work =[[Houston Chronicle]] | page =23 | date = April 24, 1994}}</ref> Christopher Lehmann-Haupt writes in ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'': \"Carr has lovingly evoked not only a physical sense of old New York but the spirit of the time as well, when the powers in charge were worried about unrest among the masses of cheap immigrant labor.\"<ref name=\"haupt\">{{cite news | last =Lehmann-Haupt | first =Christopher | title =Murder and philosophy | work =[[The Tampa Tribune]] | page =6 | publisher = The Tribune Co. | date =May 1, 1994}}</ref> In a review for ''[[The Seattle Times]]'', Deloris Tarzan Ament comments: \"A contributing editor to Military History Quarterly, Carr brings the dual sensibilities of historian and novelist to the story.\"<ref name=\"ament\">{{cite news | last =Ament | first =Deloris Tarzan | title =Murder, He Wrote - 'The Alienist' Crackles With History, Colorful Characters | work =[[The Seattle Times]] | page =M2 | date =May 1, 1994 }}</ref> In his review for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', novelist [[Jack Katzenbach]] argued that Carr's impeccable research and rich detail hindered the work's pace but rewarded readers by portraying \"the excitement of a world on the verge of change, where invention was the stuff of daily miracle,\" specifically when it came to forensics.<ref name=Katzenbach>{{cite news|last=Katzenbach|first=Jack|title=Ragtime Ripper|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 27, 1994}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"the only real weakness of the book lies in the stringent rationality of Kreizler's investigation. The more his logic makes sense the less threatening his quarry seems, at least to the reader....The story's fatalism grows tedious....Nor does it help that throughout most of the story none of the major characters are directly threatened by the killer. Of course, it is deplorable that children are being murdered. But none of them figure strongly enough in the story to arouse the reader's visceral identification.\"<ref name=LehmannHaupt/> Scott Eyman of ''[[The Palm Beach Post]]'' was critical of the \"flaccid dialogue\" and \"vague characters\".<ref name=Eyman>{{cite news|last=Eyman|first=Scott|title=Tedious 'Alienist' has no place on best-seller list|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|date=May 15, 1994}}</ref> Hary Levins from the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' noted that the novel does include a few notable anachronisms. For example, the \"heroes display an early (and highly improbable) political correctness toward blacks and homosexuals. And his detective team anticipates the feminist movement by enlisting a tough-minded career woman who's unafraid to pack a pistol and spout a bit of scatological English.\"<ref name=Levins/>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Film===\nCarr told ''[[The Orange County Register]]'' he had envisioned a film adaptation of his work while writing the story.<ref name=\"takahama\">{{cite news | last =Takahama | first =Valerie | title ='Alienist' author is no stranger to films - Profile: Caleb Carr had a movie in mind when he wrote his book _ and now Hollywood has picked up on the idea | work =[[The Orange County Register]] | page =e28 | date =July 3, 1994 }}</ref> \"I was always aware that if done correctly, this could end up being a great movie. I grew up with the movies. I've written scripts. Movies are something I've always loved,\" he said.<ref name=\"takahama\" /> Carr thought of [[Emma Thompson]] to play Sara, and [[Anthony Hopkins]] or [[Sam Neill]] to play Kreizler.<ref name=\"takahama\" />\n\nBefore the book was published, [[film producer]] [[Scott Rudin]] purchased the film rights to the novel for $500,000.<ref name=\"chollet\" /><ref name=\"takahama\" /> In June 1993, [[Paramount Pictures]] bought the film rights to the novel for $750,000.<ref name=\"ament\" /><ref name=\"steer\" />\n\nIn January 1995, ''[[The River Wild]]'' director [[Curtis Hanson]] was reported to have been in the process of final negotiations with Scott Rudin and Paramount Pictures to direct ''The Alienist''.<ref name=\"steer\">{{cite news\n | last =Busch | first =Anita M. ([[Variety magazine]]) | title ='River Wild' Director Set to Steer 'Alienist' | work =[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | page =32| date =January 18, 1995 }}</ref> By May 1995, Hanson was signed on as the film's director.<ref name=\"scouts\" /> ''[[Variety magazine|Variety]]'' reported that the film's producers planned for filming to start in Spring 1995, with an intended Christmas release date in mind.<ref name=\"steer\" /> [[Tony Award]]-winning playwright [[David Henry Hwang]] adapted the book for film.<ref name=\"steer\" /> Scouts for the film visited [[Philadelphia]] in May 1995 to consider location shooting in the city.<ref name=\"scouts\">{{cite news | last =Rea | first =Steven | title = \"Alienist\" scouts take look at Philadelphia | work =[[The Tampa Tribune]] | page =6 | publisher =The Tribune Co. | date =May 3, 1995 }}</ref> Film scouts for ''The Alienist'' were particularly interested in Philadelphia's [[Academy of Music (Philadelphia)|Academy of Music]], [[Eastern State Penitentiary]], and [[Fairmount Water Works|Waterworks]].<ref name=\"scouts\" />\n\nParamount Pictures was concerned with the film's budget, which reportedly was almost $50 million.<ref name=\"pressure\" /> By 1997, multiple script drafts from three writers brought costs to approximately $2 million.<ref name=\"pressure\">{{cite news | title =Pressure Applied To 'Alienist' Team | work =[[San Jose Mercury News]] | page =12E | date =January 1, 1997}}</ref> After delays in production, Paramount Pictures told the group behind the film they had two months to set the project up at another studio.<ref name=\"pressure\" /> In a review of Carr's sequel ''[[The Angel of Darkness]]'', Malcolm L. Johnson of ''[[The Hartford Courant]]'' cited concerns over how to depict the mutilation of the murdered prostitutes in the film, writing: \"Questions about how to treat this gruesome element has perhaps delayed the film of ''The Alienist.''\"<ref name=\"fallsshort\">{{cite news | last =Johnson | first =Malcolm L. | title =Carr's 'Angel' Falls Short of Chilling 'Alienist' | work =[[The Hartford Courant]] | page =G3| date =September 14, 1997}}</ref> When in a 1999 online chat with fans, set up by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and [[Yahoo!]], Carr was asked if there were film plans for ''The Alienist'' or ''The Angel of Darkness'', he responded: \"Only 'The Alienist,' and the attempts have been so bad that I have not yet sold 'Angel' to the movies. What happened was that a producer bought the rights and then decided he had to completely change the characters in the book. We got into a huge conflict, one that is actually ongoing.\"<ref name=\"webtranscript\">{{cite web | title =Novelist Caleb Carr - Transcript from Nov. 3, 1999 | series =Visions of the 21st Century | work =[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date =November 3, 1999 | url =http://www.time.com/time/community/transcripts/1999/110399carr.html | accessdate = 2009-05-27 }}</ref>\n\n===TV series===\n{{main|The Alienist (TV series)}}\nIn April 2015, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that [[Paramount Television]] had decided to use a three-year, first-look production deal they made with [[Anonymous Content]] productions to adapt ''The Alienist'' as an event TV series.<ref name=\"Deadline\"/> [[Jakob Verbruggen]] was chosen to serve as director after [[Cary Fukunaga]]<ref name=\"McLehman\"/> had to withdraw.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bergmann, Ina, \"Jack the Ripper's American Cousins: Representations of Good and Evil in Historical Crime Fiction,\" ''Representations of Evil in Fiction and Film'', Anglistik \u2013 Amerikanistik \u2013 Anglophonie, vol. 11, ed. Jochen Achilles and Ina Bergmann (Trier: WVT, 2009) 137-56.\n* Link, Alex, \"City Limits: Fixing New York in Caleb Carr's ''The Alienist'',\" ''CLUES: A Journal of Detection'' 23.3 (Spring 2005): 31-41.\n* Tallack, Douglas, \"Caleb Carr: Running Away from the Darkness,\" ''The Detective as Historian: History and Art in Historical Crime Fiction'', ed. Ray B. Browne and Lawrence A. Kreiser, Jr. (Bowling Green: Bowling Green State U Popular P, 2000) 251-64.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Books|Psychology}}\n* [http://www.17thstreet.net 17th Street] Comprehensive site dedicated to ''The Alienist'' and ''The Angel of Darkness''\n* [http://www.blackhatworld.com/blackhat-seo/blackhat-lounge/736115-book-reccomendation-alienist.html Discussion BHW] The book ''The Alienist'' discussed in detail on a popular forum.\n{{Caleb Carr novels}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alienist, The}}\n[[Category:American crime novels]]\n[[Category:American historical novels]]\n[[Category:1994 American novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Caleb Carr]]\n[[Category:Novels about American prostitution]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1896]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Anthony Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:Random House books]]\n[[Category:American mystery novels]]\n[[Category:Grand Prix de Litt\u00e9rature Polici\u00e8re winners]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 137-56 \u2192 137\u201356 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Alienist"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Henday Drive", "text_new": "{{short description|Freeway that encircles Edmonton, Alberta, Canada}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox road\n|province=AB\n|type=Fwy\n|route=216\n|name=Anthony Henday Drive\n|alternate_name= Highway 216\n|maint=Volker Stevin, Carmacks, Lafarge{{efn|name=del|Various consortiums were awarded [[public\u2013private partnership]] (P3) contracts for construction of the southeast, northwest, and northeast legs of Anthony Henday Drive. For the duration of the contracts, a maintenance subcontractor of each consortium is responsible for the highway. Lafarge Infrastructure is responsible for the southwest and southeast quadrants,<ref name=Lafarge/> Volker Stevin the northeast section,<ref name=Volker/> and Carmacks Enterprises the northwest section.<ref name=carmacks/>  The southwest leg was not constructed via a P3 contract, so maintenance is directly contracted by Alberta Transportation to Lafarge.<ref name=mx/>}}\n|map=Anthony Henday Drive Map.png\n|map_alt=Anthony Henday Drive surrounds the city of Edmonton, Alberta.\n|map_notes=The [[Edmonton Metropolitan Region]] with Anthony Henday Drive highlighted in red\n|length_km=77.23\n|length_ref={{efn|The 2016 Provincial Highway 1-216 Progress Chart states an official length of 77.23&nbsp;km, a number derived from the assumed highway centerline.<ref name=length/> Several other Alberta Transportation documents, including the highway's overview page and the press release signifying the completion of the freeway, state a rounded figure of 80&nbsp;km.<ref name=NEdone/><ref name=abringopen/>}}\n|history=1990 (construction begins)<br/>1992 (first segment open)<br/>2016 (ring completed)\n|ring_road=Edmonton\n|allocation=[[File:Alberta Highway 216.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] Highway 216{{efn|The entire freeway is designated as Highway 216. There are two short concurrencies with Highways 2 and 14, both of which are unsigned. In west Edmonton, Anthony Henday Drive is designated as Highway&nbsp;2 (in addition to 216) between Whitemud Drive and Yellowhead Trail (exits 18-25). In Strathcona County east of Edmonton, Anthony Henday Drive is designated as Highway 14 between Whitemud Drive and Highway 14 (exits 64-67).<ref name=length/><ref name=overmap/>}}\n| junction ={{plainlist|\n*[[File:Alberta Highway 2.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] [[Calgary Trail & Gateway Boulevard|Calgary Tr]] / [[Calgary Trail & Gateway Boulevard|Gateway Blvd]]\n*[[File:Alberta Highway 2.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] [[Whitemud Drive]]\n*[[File:Alberta Highway 16A.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] [[Alberta Highway 16A#Parkland Highway|Stony Plain Rd / 100 Ave]]\n*{{Jct|state=AB|Hwy|16}} near [[St. Albert, Alberta|St. Albert]]\n*[[File:Alberta Highway 2.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] [[St. Albert Trail]]\n*[[File:Alberta Highway 15.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] [[Alberta Highway 15|Hwy 15 / Manning Drive]]\n*{{Jct|state=AB|Hwy|16}} near [[Sherwood Park]]\n*:[[Sherwood Park Freeway]]\n*[[File:Alberta Highway 14.svg|18px|alt=|link=]] [[Whitemud Drive]]\n*{{Jct|state=AB|Hwy|14}} near Sherwood Park}}\n|cities=[[Edmonton]], [[St. Albert, Alberta|St. Albert]], [[Sherwood Park]]\n|rural_municipalities=[[Strathcona County]]\n|previous_type=Hwy\n|previous_route=201\n|next_type=Hwy\n|next_route=500\n}}\n[[File:AnthonyHendayDrive.JPG|thumb|Looking west on Henday toward Gateway Blvd from 91 Street. At the left, eastbound traffic from Highway 2 mixes with traffic destined to 91 Street before joining the freeway.]]\n'''Anthony&nbsp;Henday&nbsp;Drive''' ('''Highway&nbsp;216''') is a {{convert|77|km|mi|adj=on}} [[Controlled-access highway|freeway]] that [[ring road|encircles]] [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]]. It is a heavily travelled commuter and truck [[Bypass (road)|bypass]] route with the southwest quadrant serving as a portion of the [[CANAMEX Corridor]] that links Canada to the [[United States]] and [[Mexico]].  Henday is one of the busiest highways in [[Western Canada]], carrying over 108,000 [[Annual average daily traffic|vehicles per day]] near [[West Edmonton Mall]] in 2019.  Rush hour congestion is common on the four-lane section in southwest Edmonton where traffic levels have doubled Alberta Transportation estimates due to rapid suburban development. Alberta has committed to widening this section to six lanes by 2022; work on the $100&nbsp;million project was set to begin in fall 2019.\n\n[[Calgary Trail & Gateway Boulevard|Calgary Trail]] in south Edmonton is designated as the starting point of the ring, with exit numbers increasing clockwise as the freeway proceeds across the [[North Saskatchewan River]] to the [[Cameron Heights, Edmonton|Cameron Heights]] neighbourhood, then north past [[Whitemud Drive]], [[Stony Plain Road]] and [[Yellowhead Trail]] to [[St. Albert, Alberta|St.&nbsp;Albert]].  It continues east past [[97 Street, Edmonton|97&nbsp;Street]] to [[Alberta Highway 15#Manning Drive|Manning Drive]], then south across the North Saskatchewan River a second time.  Entering [[Strathcona County]], it again crosses Yellowhead Trail and Whitemud Drive, passing the community of [[Sherwood Park]].  Continuing south to [[Alberta Highway 14|Highway&nbsp;14]], the road re-enters southeast Edmonton and turns west to complete the ring.\n\nThe freeway was named after 18th&nbsp;century explorer [[Anthony Henday]], one of the first European men to explore central Alberta.  Its designation of 216 is derived from its bypass linkages to Edmonton's two major crossroads, Highways&nbsp;[[Alberta Highway 2|2]] and [[Alberta Highway 16|16]].  Constructed over 26&nbsp;years at a cost of $4.3&nbsp;billion, Henday became the first freeway to surround a major Canadian city when the final segment opened on October&nbsp;1, 2016.  Planning of the ring began in the 1950s, followed by design work and initial land acquisition in the 1970s, and construction of the first [[Limited-access road|expressway]] segment beginning in 1990.  Plans for Henday were developed in tandem with [[Stoney Trail]], a similar ring road freeway around [[Calgary]].\n\n== Route description ==\n===Overview===\nAlberta Transportation describes Anthony Henday Drive as a \"barrier-free, illuminated, high speed, free-flow, fully access controlled facility\" with a posted [[Speed limits in Canada|speed limit]] of {{cvt|100|km/h}} for its entire length around Edmonton,<ref name=Ramsay2/> the first ring road of its type in Canada.<ref name=Taylor/> The majority of [[Edmonton Capital Region|Capital Region]] residents reside within the approximate {{convert|20|km|adj=on}} diameter of the ring and there is extensive suburban development in close proximity to Henday.<ref name=delay/> By physical size, Edmonton is larger than both [[Toronto]] and [[Montreal]], but has a relatively low population density. Some have argued that the freeway is a significant contributor to [[urban sprawl]] in the region.<ref name=sprawl/> The city also lacks a free-flowing north&ndash;south route, further increasing traffic levels on Anthony Henday Drive.<ref name=overmap/>\n\nThe road travels primarily through [[suburb]]an residential areas in the south and west of the city, and rural farm lands and [[wetland]]s in the north.<ref name=NEenviro/>{{rp|i}}  The eastern section of the road separates the Sherwood Park portion of [[Refinery Row (Edmonton)|Refinery Row]] and other industrial and commercial developments in Edmonton to the west, from the balance of Sherwood Park to the east.<ref name=overmap/>  At its widest point east of Edmonton between Whitemud Drive and Sherwood Park Freeway, Anthony Henday Drive is eight total lanes wide which includes three main travel lanes in each direction plus a fourth lane allowing traffic to merge onto and exit from the roadway.  The highest number of through lanes is seven, between Aurum Road and 153&nbsp;Avenue in northeast Edmonton.<ref name=overmap/>  Most of the road is paved with [[asphalt]], except for an experimental {{cvt|14.4|km}} [[concrete]] segment in southwest Edmonton, the first of its type in the province.<ref name=concrete2/>  Alberta Transportation intended for the section to have lower long-term maintenance costs, but only six years after construction it required significant repairs.<ref name=concrete/> Concrete was not considered for subsequent sections of the road, but overall it was deemed to be a successful experiment that would net long term savings.<ref name=delay/>\n\n===West and north Edmonton===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right || direction = vertical\n| image1 = North Sask Bridge.jpg\n| alt1 = Anthony Henday Drive bridges over the North Saskatchewan River in southwest Edmonton, Alberta. The eastbound bridge includes a pedestrian walkway underneath the bridge.\n| image2 = Anthony Henday Bridge (20996202396).jpg\n| alt2 = Anthony Henday Drive bridges over the North Saskatchewan River in southwest Edmonton, Alberta. The eastbound bridge includes a pedestrian walkway underneath the bridge.\n| footer = Twin four-span bridge structures each carry two lanes of Anthony Henday Drive over the North Saskatchewan River in southwest Edmonton; each can be widened to four lanes on the existing piers.{{efn|A paper presented at the Annual Conference of the Transportation Association of Canada in 2005 has additional details of the bridge structures, and analyzed the construction process.<ref name=bridgepaper/>}}\n}}\nAlberta Transportation considers the starting point of Anthony Henday Drive to be at Calgary Trail / Gateway Boulevard in south Edmonton, with mileage increasing clockwise around the ring.<ref name=length/> At this major interchange, two westbound lanes of the freeway are joined by two lanes from northbound Gateway Boulevard and a third from southbound Calgary Trail.<ref name=overmap/> All five lanes merge into two over a short distance, creating congestion in the afternoon rush hour.<ref name=delay/> Two westbound lanes continue across [[Blackmud Creek]] past 111&nbsp;Street to 119&nbsp;Street. Curving slightly to the southwest through the suburbs of south Edmonton, Henday crosses [[Whitemud Creek]] to an interchange at Rabbit Hill Road. Veering back to the northwest, the freeway passes beneath [[Terwillegar Drive]] before descending to cross the North Saskatchewan River on twin {{convert|360|m|ft|adj=on}} bridges.<ref name=bridgestats/>{{Rp|191}}\n\n[[File:2019-05-30 Anthony Henday Drive south approaching Callingwood Road exit (exit 16) 9545.jpg|alt=Anthony Henday Drive south through west Edmonton, between the Callingwood Road exit and the Whitemud Drive interchange|thumb|Anthony Henday Drive south through west Edmonton, after the Whitemud Drive interchange. This four-lane section has reached above its designed capacity, and Alberta Transportation proposes widening the section from Calgary Trail to Whitemud Drive to six lanes.]]\n\nWest of the river, the four lane freeway passes Mask\u00eakosihk Trail and Cameron Heights Drive on its way to Lessard Road and Callingwood Road.  Curving north, traffic volume increases as the freeway reaches a major interchange at Whitemud Drive and widens to six lanes.<ref name=overmap/>  A northbound [[Local-express lanes|braided ramp]] helps reduce congestion between Whitemud Drive and 87&nbsp;Avenue, with which an interchange immediately follows. Henday continues north to major interchanges at Stony Plain Road and Yellowhead Trail, providing access to Spruce Grove and Jasper respectively, before curving northeast toward the city of [[St. Albert, Alberta|St.&nbsp;Albert]].<ref name=length/>  Between Whitemud Drive and Yellowhead Trail, Henday is officially concurrent with Highway&nbsp;2, but this is not indicated on any road signs.<ref name=overmap/>\n\nIn northwest Edmonton, Anthony Henday Drive first crosses Ray Gibbon Drive before continuing northeast to pass St.&nbsp;Albert to the southeast.<ref name=overmap/>  After Ray Gibbon Drive, the freeway serves as the boundary between the cities of Edmonton and St.&nbsp;Albert. The six lane road continues over 137&nbsp;Avenue and under 170&nbsp;Street to Campbell Road where it reduces from three lanes each way to two.<ref name=NWS18x/>  It continues curving east across 127&nbsp;Street to [[Alberta Highway 28|Highway&nbsp;28]], the most northerly point on the ring road. Now forming the approximate boundary between Edmonton and [[Sturgeon County]],<ref name=sconamap/> the freeway passes south of [[CFB Edmonton]] before reaching 66&nbsp;Street and a major interchange at Manning Drive/Highway&nbsp;15, the former terminus of the freeway until the final section was completed in 2016.<ref name=overmap/>\n\n===East and south Edmonton===\nAfter Manning Drive, the freeway widens to six lanes and continues clockwise through northeast Edmonton past 153&nbsp;Avenue to a second crossing of the North Saskatchewan River.<ref name=overmap/>  Four lanes cross the river southbound and three northbound on {{convert|304|m|ft|adj=on}} bridges.<ref name=NEnumbers/>  A pedestrian crossing was again included; it is slung underneath the southbound bridge and ties into the existing pathway system.<ref name=NEnumbers/> The seven lane freeway rises from the river valley into the Clover Bar area, crossing Aurum Road to a major interchange at Yellowhead Trail, crossing into Strathcona County.<ref name=sconamap/>\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | image1 = Anthony Henday Dr at Yellowhead Trail, Strathcona County.jpg\n | alt1 = Anthony Henday Drive interchange over Yellowhead Trail, Strathcona County immediately east of Edmonton, Alberta. Construction was completed in 2016.\n | image2 = Henday Yellowhead 2.jpg\n | alt2 = Anthony Henday Drive interchange over Yellowhead Trail, Strathcona County immediately east of Edmonton, Alberta. Construction was completed in 2016.\n | image3 = Henday Yellowhead 1.jpg\n | alt3 = Anthony Henday Drive interchange over Yellowhead Trail, Strathcona County immediately east of Edmonton, Alberta. Construction was completed in 2016.\n | footer = The interchange of Anthony Henday Drive Yellowhead Trail east of Edmonton is a hybrid design with braided ramps and high capacity third level flyovers}}\nIn Strathcona County, the fourth southbound lane is dropped and the six lane freeway immediately crosses over Petroleum Way en route to interchanges at Baseline Road and Sherwood Park Freeway, passing Refinery Row to the east.<ref name=overmap/>  South of Sherwood Park Freeway, Anthony Henday Drive forms the boundary between Strathcona County and the city of Edmonton.  The freeway continues to a second interchange at Whitemud Drive after which it is briefly concurrent with Highway&nbsp;14 until that route branches southeast {{cvt|2|km}} later.<ref name=overmap/>  Four lanes of Anthony Henday Drive re-enter the city of Edmonton and turns west toward the starting point of the loop.<ref name=sconamap/> Before straightening out to a westerly heading, the freeway interchanges with 17&nbsp;Street, then 50&nbsp;Street after which it returns to a six lane freeway, crosses 91&nbsp;Street, and returns to its starting point at Calgary Trail/Gateway Boulevard.<ref name=overmap/>\n\n===Interchange design===\nAlberta Transportation used several different [[interchange (road)|interchange]] designs for the freeway, the most common being the [[Partial cloverleaf interchange|partial cloverleaf]], with between four and six ramps.<ref name=overmap/> This type of interchange is ideal for connections between freeways and [[arterial road]]s; they have a higher capacity than [[diamond interchange]]s, but do not have the weaving and merging problems of full [[Cloverleaf interchange|cloverleaf]] interchanges.<ref name=parclo/> Loop ramps are also used to better conform to existing terrain or structures, or to increase merge/weave distances between closely spaced interchanges.<ref name=geometric/> For example, they were used at 91 Street to achieve at least {{cvt|600|m}} of separation to Gateway Boulevard, which would not have been possible with a conventional diamond.<ref name=SES18/>\n\nAnthony Henday Drive features several variations of the [[Interchange (road)#Cloverstack interchange|cloverstack]], a common name for hybrid designs that allow for high speed left turns on elevated directional ramps.<ref name=overmap/> They retain loop ramps for the lesser used left turn movements significantly reducing cost and overall size of the interchange because fourth level flyovers are not required as they are in a [[stack interchange]].<ref name=geometric2/> Henday features two three-level interchanges; the cloverstack at Calgary Trail / Gateway Boulevard was the first three-level interchange to be constructed in Alberta.<ref name=trellis/> Several of the bridges in this interchange use a \"Trellis Beam\" concept in which many perpendicular girders are used to carry the upper roadway at a high degree of skew.<ref name=trellis/><ref name=trellisview/> For Henday's junction with the Yellowhead Highway east of Edmonton, there was already an existing semi-directional ramp for the westbound to southbound movement prior to the completion of the northeast leg. It ran parallel to the railway line that bisects the interchange. It was retained, while the existing interchange was reconstructed into a cloverstack with two new two semi-directional flyovers and one loop ramp for the eastbound to northbound movement.\n\n===Traffic===\nThe busiest section of Anthony Henday Drive is in west Edmonton between 87&nbsp;Avenue and Stony Plain Road where it carried over 108,000&nbsp;vehicles per day in 2019,<ref name=aadt2/> second only to Whitemud Drive among Edmonton roadways.<ref name=aadt/>  The section carried over 115,000 vehicles per day during the [[Annual average daily traffic#Average summer daily traffic|summer months]] of 2019.<ref name=aadt2/>  The 4-lane section of the southwest quadrant between Calgary Trail and Whitemud Drive is significantly over capacity and sees major delays during peak periods.<ref name=overcap/>  A contributing factor is the close proximity of interchanges between the North Saskatchewan River and Yellowhead Trail, which creates a problem known as \"[[Grade separation#Weaving|weaving]]\" in which traffic is trying to simultaneously enter and exit within the same stretch of roadway.\n\nTraffic levels on Henday have risen much more quickly than anticipated.  Alberta Transportation concedes that in 2001 the southwest section was projected to reach 40,000 vehicles per day by 2020 but reached that mark in 2009.<ref name=delay/><ref name=SWwiden4/> {{as of|2019|lc=y}} it carries over 80,000 vehicles per day in the vicinity of 111&nbsp;Street,<ref name=aadt2/> and Alberta committed to widening the section to six lanes by 2022 with work planned to have begun in fall 2019.<ref name=SWwiden/><ref name=SWwiden4/> Prior to the announcement, project manager Bill van der Meer had stated that Henday is operating efficiently, aside from peak hour congestion.<ref name=delay/>  Alberta Transportation generally considers widening four lane highways when volumes reach between 30,000 and 50,000 cars per day.<ref name=widenparam/> With the exception of a section in north Edmonton between Highway&nbsp;28 and Manning Drive, by 2015, all four-lane sections of Henday each carried more than 40,000 vehicles per day.<ref name=aadt/>\n\nAlberta Transportation publishes yearly traffic volume data for provincial highways.<ref name=aadt/><ref name=aadt2/> The table below compares the average daily vehicle count over the span of a year ([[annual average daily traffic]], AADT) at several locations along Anthony Henday Drive using data from 2000, 2010 and 2015.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left; float:left\"\n|+ Traffic volumes<ref name=aadt/><ref name=aadt2/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 110px;\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\" | Edmonton\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" colspan=\"2\" | 