o two Old English prose riddles, surviving on folio 16v in the mid-eleventh-century [[psalter]] British Library, Cotton Vitellius E.xviii, made in Winchester, within a short text on secret codes, found among a collection of notes, charms, prayers, and computistical tables.<ref>Dieter Bitterli, 'Two Old English Prose Riddles of the Eleventh Century', in ''Words, Words, Words: Philology and Beyond: Festschrift for Andreas Fischer on the Occasion of his 65th Birthday'', edited by Sarah Chevalier and Thomas Honegger (T\u00fcbingen: Franke, 2012), pp. 1-11.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Riddles]]\n[[Category:Old English literature]]\n[[Category:Old English poetry]]\n", "name_user": "Alarichall", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Exeter Book Riddles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_riddles"}
{"title_page": "Heather Veitch", "text_new": "{{short description|American stripper turned Christian missionary}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Heather Veitch\n|image= Heather Veitch at 2006 AEE Thursday 1.jpg|\n|image caption= Veitch at the 2006 [[Adult Entertainment Expo]]\n|birth_date= {{birth based on age as of date|31|2005|December|5}}<ref name=telegraph/>\n|birth_place= United States\n|occupation= [[Minister (Christianity)|Christian minister]], [[missionary]]\n}}\n\n'''Heather Veitch''' (born in 1973/1974) is an American Christian missionary who worked previously as a [[stripper]] but now seeks to help women working in [[strip club]]s leave the [[adult entertainment industry]]. She is the founder of the [[Christian Ministry|Christian ministry]] [[JC's Girls]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Holy hottie delivers naked truth|first=Paula|last=Bustamante|url=http://lifestyle.iafrica.com/herlife/features/277740.htm |website=iafrica.com ([[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]) |date=2006-04-30|accessdate=2006-05-27 }}</ref> based out of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].\n\nVeitch is a frequent speaker, working with both secular and religious audiences throughout the United States. Her expertise and knowledge in reaching out to women working in strip clubs has been utilized throughout the world by organizations seeking to develop like-minded ministries.<ref name=telegraph/>\n\n== JC's Girls ==\n{{main|JC's Girls}}\n\nJC's Girls is an international, [[faith-based organization]] that offers spiritual support to women working in the [[sex industry]].<ref name=telegraph>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1504794/Former-stripper-takes-Gods-word-to-world-of-porn.html |title=Former stripper takes God's word to world of porn|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 December 2005|accessdate=17 August 2010}}</ref> Their primary focus includes visiting local strip clubs in order to extend an invitation to attend church. Their approach includes offering small gift packages along with ministry contact information. Additionally, the ministry participates in the annual [[AVN Adult Entertainment Expo]] held in Las Vegas. The organization has set up an exhibitor booth during the convention, presenting a message to entertainers and patrons with the message: ''\"There is nothing you have ever done that God would not forgive you for!\"''\n\nThe organization has developed chapter ministries across the United States. These chapters include JCs Girls of [[San Diego]]; JCs Girls of [[Austin, Texas]]; JCs Girls of Las Vegas; and JCs Girls of [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn 2007, Veitch began partnering with [[Annie Lobert]] of \"Hookers for Jesus\" on a joint media project entitled \"Saving Sex City\". However, the project was short lived and {{as of|November 2008}}, Veitch and Lobert were no longer producing new episodes.\n\n==''Pussycat Preacher'' documentary==\nIn 2007, Veitch's life and ministry were presented in a [[documentary]]. Directed by documentary filmmaker [[Bill Day (filmmaker)|Bill Day]], the film revealed the inside story of Veitch's life and her struggle to start a ministry for women in the sex industry. The film primarily focuses on Veitch, along with the team of Christian women who join her to become JC's Girls, and Pastor Matt Brown of [[Sandals Church]] in [[Riverside, California]]. The film highlights the pastor's efforts to support Veitch's endeavor, while facing opposition from his local congregation.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pussycatpreachers |title=Pussycatpreachers|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=23 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Private life ==\nVeitch was born in [[Los Angeles]] but grew up in [[Muscoy]], [[San Bernardino County]].<ref name=telegraph/> She has two children.<ref>{{cite web|author=  |title=The Stripper Who Found True Love|url=http://www.charismamag.com/site-archives/145-features/transformed-lives/2284-the-stripper-who-found-true-love |website=charismamag.com|date=30 June 2007|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* {{IMDb name|2323584|Heather Veitch}}\n* [http://www.sdrock.com/ministries/jcsgirls/ JC's Girls Ministry Website]\n* [https://variety.com/2008/film/reviews/the-pussycat-preacher-1200535857/ The Pussycat Preacher]\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=2673044&page=1 A Second Life After Sin]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/2006/mar/25/local/me-beliefs25 Ex-Stripper Spreads Gospel to Those in Sex Industry]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/2008/jan/20/entertainment/ca-vegas20 Now they bare their souls to minister to others]\n* {{cite book|author=Jud Wilhite|title=Eyes Wide Open: See and Live the Real You|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bkh-Hwb3tnUC&pg=PT90 |date=14 April 2009|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-60142-243-9|pages=90 & }}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/pussycatpreachers ''Pussycat Preacher'' YouTube channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veitch, Heather}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:American female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American Protestant missionaries]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in the United States]]\n[[Category:Converts to Protestantism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American stripper turned Christian missionary}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name= Heather Veitch\n|image= Heather Veitch at 2006 AEE Thursday 1.jpg|\n|image caption= Veitch at the 2006 [[Adult Entertainment Expo]]\n|birth_date= {{birth based on age as of date|31|2005|December|5}}<ref name=telegraph/>\n|birth_place= United States\n|occupation= [[Minister (Christianity)|Christian minister]], [[missionary]]\n}}\n\n'''Heather Veitch''' (born in 1973/1974) is an American Christian missionary who worked previously as a [[stripper]] but now seeks to help women working in [[strip club]]s leave the [[adult entertainment industry]]. She is the founder of the [[Christian Ministry|Christian ministry]] [[JC's Girls]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Holy hottie delivers naked truth|first=Paula|last=Bustamante|url=http://lifestyle.iafrica.com/herlife/features/277740.htm |website=iafrica.com ([[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]) |date=2006-04-30|accessdate=2006-05-27 }}</ref> based out of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].\n\nVeitch is a frequent speaker, working with both secular and religious audiences throughout the United States. Her expertise and knowledge in reaching out to women working in strip clubs has been utilized throughout the world by organizations seeking to develop like-minded ministries.<ref name=telegraph/>\n\n== JC's Girls ==\n{{main|JC's Girls}}\n\nJC's Girls is an international, [[faith-based organization]] that offers spiritual support to women working in the [[sex industry]].<ref name=telegraph>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1504794/Former-stripper-takes-Gods-word-to-world-of-porn.html |title=Former stripper takes God's word to world of porn|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=5 December 2005|accessdate=17 August 2010}}</ref> Their primary focus includes visiting local strip clubs in order to extend an invitation to attend church. Their approach includes offering small gift packages along with ministry contact information. Additionally, the ministry participates in the annual [[AVN Adult Entertainment Expo]] held in Las Vegas. The organization has set up an exhibitor booth during the convention, presenting a message to entertainers and patrons with the message: ''\"There is nothing you have ever done that God would not forgive you for!\"''\n\nThe organization has developed chapter ministries across the United States. These chapters include JCs Girls of [[San Diego]]; JCs Girls of [[Austin, Texas]]; JCs Girls of Las Vegas; and JCs Girls of [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn 2007, Veitch began partnering with [[Annie Lobert]] of \"Hookers for Jesus\" on a joint media project entitled \"Saving Sex City\". However, the project was short lived and {{as of|November 2008}}, Veitch and Lobert were no longer producing new episodes.\n\n==''Pussycat Preacher'' documentary==\nIn 2007, Veitch's life and ministry were presented in a [[documentary]]. Directed by documentary filmmaker [[Bill Day (filmmaker)|Bill Day]], the film revealed the inside story of Veitch's life and her struggle to start a ministry for women in the sex industry. The film primarily focuses on Veitch, along with the team of Christian women who join her to become JC\u2019s Girls, and Pastor Matt Brown of [[Sandals Church]] in [[Riverside, California]]. The film highlights the pastor's efforts to support Veitch's endeavor, while facing opposition from his local congregation.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pussycatpreachers |title=Pussycatpreachers|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=23 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Private life ==\nVeitch was born in [[Los Angeles]] but grew up in [[Muscoy]], [[San Bernardino County]].<ref name=telegraph/> She has two children.<ref>{{cite web|author=  |title=The Stripper Who Found True Love|url=http://www.charismamag.com/site-archives/145-features/transformed-lives/2284-the-stripper-who-found-true-love |website=charismamag.com|date=30 June 2007|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* {{IMDb name|2323584|Heather Veitch}}\n* [http://www.sdrock.com/ministries/jcsgirls/ JC's Girls Ministry Website]\n* [https://variety.com/2008/film/reviews/the-pussycat-preacher-1200535857/ The Pussycat Preacher]\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/2020/story?id=2673044&page=1 A Second Life After Sin]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/2006/mar/25/local/me-beliefs25 Ex-Stripper Spreads Gospel to Those in Sex Industry]\n* [http://articles.latimes.com/2008/jan/20/entertainment/ca-vegas20 Now they bare their souls to minister to others]\n* {{cite book|author=Jud Wilhite|title=Eyes Wide Open: See and Live the Real You|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bkh-Hwb3tnUC&pg=PT90 |date=14 April 2009|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-60142-243-9|pages=90 & }}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/pussycatpreachers ''Pussycat Preacher'' YouTube channel]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veitch, Heather}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:American female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American Protestant missionaries]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in the United States]]\n[[Category:Converts to Protestantism]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e''Pussycat Preacher'' documentary:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_Veitch"}
{"title_page": "Veronica Monet", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Peacock|date=September 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Veronica Monet\n| image         =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1960|04|01}}\n| residence     = [[Grass Valley, California]], United States\n| alma_mater    = [[Oregon State University]]\n| occupation    = {{comma separated entries|[[activist]]|[[author]]|[[therapist]]}}\n| website       = {{url|theshamefreezone.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Veronica Monet''' (born April 1, 1960) is an American author and [[activist]] for [[sex worker rights]].<ref name=\"SBSUN\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbsun.com/2008/03/20/escort-explains-sex-secrets-success/|publisher=The Sun|author=John Bogert|date=20 March 2008|accessdate=11 September 2019|title=Escort explains sex secrets, success}}</ref> Her early activism focused on debunking stereotypes about sex workers and advocating for the [[decriminalization]] of all sex work. From 1989 to 2004, she was a high-end escort and courtesan,<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.sbsun.com/2008/03/20/escort-explains-sex-secrets-success/|newspaper=San Bernardino Sun|title=Escort explains sex secrets, success|date=20 March 2008}}</ref> Monet's later work focuses on [[anger management]], healing shame, and helping couples integrate their sexuality with their spirituality.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Early life and education==\nVeronica Monet was born to working-class parents in the rural town of [[Prairie City, Oregon]]. \n\nShe was [[homeschooled]] and did not participate in public education until entering college in 1978, when she was granted Honors at Entrance at [[Oregon State University]]. In 1979, Monet left the denomination she was raised in, and in 1982 she graduated from Oregon State University with honors with a Bachelor of Science in Psychology and a minor in Business Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dce.oregonstate.edu/wgc/events/2010-2011-past-events/modern-sex-conference-wednesday-feb-15|title=Modern Sex Conference|date=15 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe first seven years after college, Monet was employed as an office manager, department manager, and marketing representative. She experienced on-the-job sexual harassment, as well as gender pay discrimination, and these negative experiences would influence her subsequent work trajectory.<ref name=\"Quad\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35804161/quadcity_times/|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|title=Former escort says sex is all in the mind|date=11 December 2005|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>{{acn|date=September 2019}}\n\nMonet's early adult life was complicated by a severe addiction to drugs and alcohol that led her to a [[twelve-step program]] in 1985. She has remained clean and sober ever since, and attributes her long-term sobriety to the twelve-step programs and ongoing therapy.<ref name=\"Salon\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2002/10/23/veronica/|author=Michael Castleman|title=The Two Worlds of Veronica Monet|publisher=Salon|date=23 October 2002|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMonet became a high-end [[call girl|escort]] in 1989, after four years of sobriety, and worked as a clean and sober high-end escort for fifteen years, as she described when she was profiled as a 'modern day courtesan' on A&E's Love Chronicles in the year 2000.<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\nThroughout her escorting career, Monet was married and helped to raise her husband's two young children.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Escort-s-hot-tip-It-s-not-just-about-the-sex-2593542.php|newspaper= San Francisco Gate|title=Escort's hot tip: It's not just about the sex, it's about the mind|date=23 November 2005}}</ref> In 2004, Monet divorced her husband of fourteen years due to his relapse around pain pills. That same year, she transitioned from escorting to relationship coaching and moved from the California Bay Area to the Sierra Nevada Mountains. She spent the next eight years living in a mountain cabin while touring major American cities to promote her first book, ''Sex Secrets of Escorts,'' published by Penguin in 2005.\n\nIn the Fall of 2000, the [[Kinsey Institute]] established The Veronica Monet Collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iucat.iu.edu/kinsey/3354059|title=Indiana University, Bloomington - Veronica Monet collection}}</ref>\n\nAcademics in the field of [[psychology]] have referenced Monet's expertise on the dynamics of sexual shame and porn addiction. She is cited in the late Christopher Kennedy Lawford's ''Recover to Live: Kick Any Habit Manage Any Addiction'' (pages 166-167)<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lawford |first=Christopher Kennedy |date=18 December 2012 |title=Recover to Live: Kick Any Habit Manage Any Addiction |publisher=BenBella |isbn=1936661969 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/recovertolivekic0000lawf }}</ref>, and Stanford professor Philip Zimbardo's ''Man (Dis)Connected'' (page 223).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Zimbardo |first=Philip |date=17 May 2015 |title=Man (Dis)Connected |publisher=Rider |isbn= 1846044847}}</ref>\n\nMonet became a Certified Sexologist through the American College of Sexologists in 2007 and an Anger Management Specialist through Century Anger Management<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/therapists/veronica-monet-grass-valley-ca/217145|title=Psychology Today}}</ref> and is also a graduate of [[San Francisco Sex Information]]<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lawford |first=Christopher |date=17 May 2015 |title=Recover to Live |publisher=BenBella |isbn= 1936661977}}</ref> and now works as a relationship therapist helping people heal trauma and shame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/therapists/sexual-addiction/ca/grass-valley/217145?sid=5ce369c4c2456&ref=4&tr=ResultsName|title=Psychology Today directory}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===Books===\n\n*{{Cite book|title=Veronica Monet's Sex Secrets of Escorts: What Men Really Want|last=Monet|first=Veronica|date=2005|publisher=DK Publishing|year=|isbn=9781440690778|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Sex de Luxe: Profi-Tipps f\u00fcr hei\u00dfe N\u00e4chte|last=Monet|first=Veronica|date=2009|publisher=Goldmann Verlag|year=|isbn=9783641017033|location=|pages=|language=de}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monet, Veronica}}\n[[Category:Women sexologists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American sex educators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sexologists]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in the United States]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:People from Grant County, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Peacock|date=September 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Veronica Monet\n| image         =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1960|04|01}}\n| residence     = [[Grass Valley, California]], United States\n| alma_mater    = [[Oregon State University]]\n| occupation    = {{comma separated entries|[[activist]]|[[author]]|[[therapist]]}}\n| website       = {{url|theshamefreezone.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Veronica Monet''' (born April 1, 1960) is an American author and [[activist]] for [[sex worker rights]].<ref name=\"SBSUN\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbsun.com/2008/03/20/escort-explains-sex-secrets-success/|publisher=The Sun|author=John Bogert|date=20 March 2008|accessdate=11 September 2019|title=Escort explains sex secrets, success}}</ref> Her early activism focused on debunking stereotypes about sex workers and advocating for the [[decriminalization]] of all sex work. From 1989 to 2004, she was a high-end escort and courtesan,<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.sbsun.com/2008/03/20/escort-explains-sex-secrets-success/|newspaper=San Bernardino Sun|title=Escort explains sex secrets, success|date=20 March 2008}}</ref> Monet's later work focuses on [[anger management]], healing shame, and helping couples integrate their sexuality with their spirituality.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Early life and education==\nVeronica Monet was born to working class parents in the rural town of [[Prairie City, Oregon]]. \n\nShe was [[homeschooled]] and did not participate in public education until entering college in 1978, when she was granted Honors at Entrance at [[Oregon State University]]. In 1979, Monet left the denomination she was raised in, and in 1982 she graduated from Oregon State University with honors with a Bachelor of Science in Psychology and a minor in Business Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dce.oregonstate.edu/wgc/events/2010-2011-past-events/modern-sex-conference-wednesday-feb-15|title=Modern Sex Conference|date=15 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe first seven years after college, Monet was employed as an office manager, department manager, and marketing representative. She experienced on-the-job sexual harassment, as well as gender pay discrimination, and these negative experiences would influence her subsequent work trajectory.<ref name=\"Quad\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35804161/quadcity_times/|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|title=Former escort says sex is all in the mind|date=11 December 2005|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>{{acn|date=September 2019}}\n\nMonet's early adult life was complicated by a severe addiction to drugs and alcohol that led her to a [[twelve-step program]] in 1985. She has remained clean and sober ever since, and attributes her long-term sobriety to the twelve-step programs and ongoing therapy.<ref name=\"Salon\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2002/10/23/veronica/|author=Michael Castleman|title=The Two Worlds of Veronica Monet|publisher=Salon|date=23 October 2002|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMonet became a high-end [[call girl|escort]] in 1989, after four years of sobriety, and worked as a clean and sober high-end escort for fifteen years, as she described when she was profiled as a 'modern day courtesan' on A&E's Love Chronicles in the year 2000.<ref name=\"Salon\"/>\nThroughout her escorting career, Monet was married and helped to raise her husband's two young children.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Escort-s-hot-tip-It-s-not-just-about-the-sex-2593542.php|newspaper= San Francisco Gate|title=Escort's hot tip: It's not just about the sex, it's about the mind|date=23 November 2005}}</ref> In 2004, Monet divorced her husband of fourteen years due to his relapse around pain pills. That same year, she transitioned from escorting to relationship coaching and moved from the California Bay Area to the Sierra Nevada Mountains. She spent the next eight years living in a mountain cabin while touring major American cities to promote her first book, ''Sex Secrets of Escorts,'' published by Penguin in 2005.\n\nIn the Fall of 2000, the [[Kinsey Institute]] established The Veronica Monet Collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iucat.iu.edu/kinsey/3354059|title=Indiana University, Bloomington - Veronica Monet collection}}</ref>\n\nAcademics in the field of [[psychology]] have referenced Monet's expertise on the dynamics of sexual shame and porn addiction. She is cited in the late Christopher Kennedy Lawford's ''Recover to Live: Kick Any Habit Manage Any Addiction'' (pages 166-167)<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lawford |first=Christopher Kennedy |date=18 December 2012 |title=Recover to Live: Kick Any Habit Manage Any Addiction |publisher=BenBella |isbn=1936661969 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/recovertolivekic0000lawf }}</ref>, and Stanford professor Philip Zimbardo's ''Man (Dis)Connected'' (page 223).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Zimbardo |first=Philip |date=17 May 2015 |title=Man (Dis)Connected |publisher=Rider |isbn= 1846044847}}</ref>\n\nMonet became a Certified Sexologist through the American College of Sexologists in 2007 and an Anger Management Specialist through Century Anger Management<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/therapists/veronica-monet-grass-valley-ca/217145|title=Psychology Today}}</ref> and is also a graduate of [[San Francisco Sex Information]]<ref>{{Cite book |last=Lawford |first=Christopher |date=17 May 2015 |title=Recover to Live |publisher=BenBella |isbn= 1936661977}}</ref> and now works as a relationship therapist helping people heal trauma and shame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/therapists/sexual-addiction/ca/grass-valley/217145?sid=5ce369c4c2456&ref=4&tr=ResultsName|title=Psychology Today directory}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===Books===\n\n*{{Cite book|title=Veronica Monet's Sex Secrets of Escorts: What Men Really Want|last=Monet|first=Veronica|date=2005|publisher=DK Publishing|year=|isbn=9781440690778|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Sex de Luxe: Profi-Tipps f\u00fcr hei\u00dfe N\u00e4chte|last=Monet|first=Veronica|date=2009|publisher=Goldmann Verlag|year=|isbn=9783641017033|location=|pages=|language=de}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monet, Veronica}}\n[[Category:Women sexologists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American sex educators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sexologists]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in the United States]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:People from Grant County, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: working class parents \u2192 working-class parents", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veronica_Monet"}
